{"title_page": "Eric S. Brown", "text_new": "{{notability|Biographies|date=February 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox Author\n|name         = Eric S. Brown\n|image        = \n|occupation   = Horror Novelist\n|language     = English\n|nationality  = [[US]]\n|genre        = [[Horror fiction|Horror]], [[Science Fiction]], [[Post-Apocalyptic]]\n|subject      = Fictional survival/creature horror\n|notableworks = Bigfoot War, Sasquatch Planet, Zombie Horror 101, Cowboys Vs. Zombies, Megalodon\n|years_active = 2003-present\n|website      = \n}}\n\n'''Eric S. Brown''' is an American [[novelist]] known for writing [[science fiction]]/[[Horror fiction|horror]] novels. He has written nearly forty novels and publishes most of them with [[Severed Press]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://monsterlibrarian.com/EricSBrownInterview.htm |title=Eric S Brown Interview |work=Monster Librarian |first=Michele |last=Lee |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> He began his writing career with short \"[[zombie]]\" horror stories, and then wrote his first full-length novel in 2003, entitled \"Dying Days\". It was followed by the \"Queen\" series, and then \"Cowboys vs. Zombies\". He now writes creature novels, post-apocalyptic fiction, and space-marine novels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sciencefiction.com/2013/08/19/exclusive-interview-with-author-eric-s-brown/ |title=Exclusive Interview With Author Eric S. Brown |work=ScienceFiction.com |first=Stuart |last=Conover |date=August 19, 2013 |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBrown began his career by writing short horror stories as well as illustrated graphic novels, which began with his first 2003 novel, \"Dying Days\". In 2004, he co-authored a novel entitled \"Portals of Terror\" along with Angeline Hawkes Craig.\n\nIn 2005, his net novel, entitled \"Cobble\" was released. It was co-authored by Susan Brydenbaugh. Brown had continued with \"The Queen\" which dealt with zombies controlling a cruise ship. Next was \"Barren Earth\", which was released in 2009. Also released in 2009 was his novel entitled \"World War of the Dead\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://horrornews.net/17733/book-review-world-war-of-the-dead-author-eric-s-brown/ |title=Book Review: World War of the Dead - Author Eric S. Brown |work=HorrorNews.Net |access-date=2017-11-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229004133/http://horrornews.net/17733/book-review-world-war-of-the-dead-author-eric-s-brown/ |archive-date=2017-12-29 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing a novel entitled \"The Human Experiment\", he got his big break when \"Bigfoot War\" was released. It was followed by \"Dead in the Woods\", which came out in 2011, along with the third entry, \"Food Chain\". Along with this new series, Brown wrote and published \"The Bloody Rage of Bigfoot\" in 2012.\n\nAfter writing over six more entries into the Bigfoot War series, Brown published his first stand-alone novel entitled \"Kaiju Dawn\" in 2014, which began another series. Its sequel, \"Kaiju Armageddon\", was released a few months later. He wrote seven more entries into the Kaiju series before publishing his next stand-alone novel, \"Megalodon\" which was released on e-book and paperback in April 2015. The next novel he wrote, which was also released in 2015, was entitled \"Megalodons\", and was co-authored by Clarence Writz.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.fantasticfiction.com/b/eric-s-brown/ |title=Eric S Brown |work=Fantastic Fiction |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nHis next novel was \"Megalodon Apocalypse\". Then, in February 2016, he released a new novel entitled \"Kraken\", which followed a Navy ship as it battled horrifying mutant squids. It had good reviews from critics and customers alike. It was followed by \"Alien Battleton\", which told the story of  Alien warfare. Then, \"Kraken Island\" was released just a month and a half later. It was followed by \"Kraken Vs. Megalodon\", where Eric combined the two mighty beasts of the deep.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== ''1632'' series ===\nIn 2014, Brown branched out into the [[alternate history]] genre by contributing several short stories to various issues of [[Eric Flint]]'s online magazine ''[[The Grantville Gazettes|The Grantville Gazette]]'' set in Flint's [[1632 Series|1632 universe]]. His first short story, ''The Magic of the Speedster'' appeared in volume 55 and it describes a 17th-century Native American's exposure to a 20th-century comic book that he had found on the body of a dead English colonist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://grantvillegazette.com/wp/article/the-magic-of-the-speedster/ |title=The Magic of the Speedster |magazine=[[The Grantville Gazettes|The Grantville Gazette]] |volume=55 |date=September 1, 2014 |first=Eric S. |last=Brown}}</ref>\n\nIn the following year, Brown started his ''The Monster Society'' series, an ongoing series of short stories about young adult [[LARPer]]s pretending to fight imaginary monsters in the outskirts of Grantville while growing up and dealing with the effects of 20th-century Grantville appearing suddenly in 17th-century Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://grantvillegazette.com/wp/article/the-monster-society/ |title=The Monster Society |magazine=[[The Grantville Gazettes|The Grantville Gazette]] |volume=61 |date=September 1, 2015 |first=Eric S. |last=Brown}}</ref> The first story of the series was successful enough to generate seven more sequels and subsequently republished as a single volume collection through the Flint's [[Ring of Fire Press]] in 2018.<ref name=\"mcvie2017\">{{cite web |url=https://authorsinterviews.wordpress.com/2017/11/08/here-is-my-interview-with-eric-s-brown/ |title=Here is my interview with Eric S Brown |date=November 8, 2017 |first=Fiona |last=Mcvie |work=Authors Interviews (blog)}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.smashwords.com/profile/view/ericbrowncoscom Smashwords Profile]\n* {{isfdb name|id=125025}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Eric S}}\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|Biographies|date=February 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox Author\n|name         = Eric S. Brown\n|image        = \n|occupation   = Horror Novelist\n|language     = English\n|nationality  = [[US]]\n|genre        = [[Horror fiction|Horror]], [[Science Fiction]], [[Post-Apocalyptic]]\n|subject      = Fictional survival/creature horror\n|notableworks = Bigfoot War, Sasquatch Planet, Zombie Horror 101, Cowboys Vs. Zombies, Megalodon\n|years_active = 2003-present\n|website      = \n}}\n\n'''Eric S. Brown''' is an American [[novelist]] known for writing [[science fiction]]/[[Horror fiction|horror]] novels. He has written nearly forty novels and publishes most of them with [[Severed Press]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://monsterlibrarian.com/EricSBrownInterview.htm |title=Eric S Brown Interview |work=Monster Librarian |first=Michele |last=Lee |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> He began his writing career with short \"[[zombie]]\" horror stories, and then wrote his first full-length novel in 2003, entitled \"Dying Days\". It was followed by the \"Queen\" series, and then \"Cowboys vs. Zombies\". He now writes creature novels, post-apocalyptic fiction, and space-marine novels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sciencefiction.com/2013/08/19/exclusive-interview-with-author-eric-s-brown/ |title=Exclusive Interview With Author Eric S. Brown |work=ScienceFiction.com |first=Stuart |last=Conover |date=August 19, 2013 |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBrown began his career by writing short horror stories as well as illustrated graphic novels, which began with his first 2003 novel, \"Dying Days\". In 2004, he co-authored a novel entitled \"Portals of Terror\" along with Angeline Hawkes Craig.\n\nIn 2005, his net novel, entitled \"Cobble\" was released. It was co-authored by Susan Brydenbaugh. Brown had continued with \"The Queen\" which dealt with zombies controlling a cruise ship. Next was \"Barren Earth\", which was released in 2009. Also released in 2009 was his novel entitled \"World War of the Dead\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://horrornews.net/17733/book-review-world-war-of-the-dead-author-eric-s-brown/ |title=Book Review: World War of the Dead - Author Eric S. Brown |work=HorrorNews.Net |access-date=2017-11-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229004133/http://horrornews.net/17733/book-review-world-war-of-the-dead-author-eric-s-brown/ |archive-date=2017-12-29 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing a novel entitled \"The Human Experiment\", he got his big break when \"Bigfoot War\" was released. It was followed by \"Dead in the Woods\", which came out in 2011, along with the third entry, \"Food Chain\". Along with this new series, Brown wrote and published \"The Bloody Rage of Bigfoot\" in 2012.\n\nAfter writing over six more entries into the Bigfoot War series, Brown published his first stand-alone novel entitled \"Kaiju Dawn\" in 2014, which began another series. Its sequel, \"Kaiju Armageddon\", was released a few months later. He wrote seven more entries into the Kaiju series before publishing his next stand-alone novel, \"Megalodon\" which was released on e-book and paperback in April 2015. The next novel he wrote, which was also released in 2015, was entitled \"Megalodons\", and was co-authored by Clarence Writz.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.fantasticfiction.com/b/eric-s-brown/ |title=Eric S Brown |work=Fantastic Fiction |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nHis next novel was \"Megalodon Apocalypse\". Then, in February 2016, he released a new novel entitled \"Kraken\", which followed a Navy ship as it battled horrifying mutant squids. It had good reviews from critics and customers alike. It was followed by \"Alien Battleton\", which told the story of  Alien warfare. Then, \"Kraken Island\" was released just a month and a half later. It was followed by \"Kraken Vs. Megalodon\", where Eric combined the two mighty beasts of the deep.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== ''1632'' series ===\nIn 2014, Brown branched out into the [[alternate history]] genre by contributing several short stories to various issues of [[Eric Flint]]'s online magazine ''[[The Grantville Gazettes|The Grantville Gazette]]'' set in Flint's [[1632 Series|1632 universe]]. His first short story, ''The Magic of the Speedster'' appeared in volume 55 and it describes a 17th-century Native American's exposure to a 20th-century comic book that he had found on the body of a dead English colonist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://grantvillegazette.com/wp/article/the-magic-of-the-speedster/ |title=The Magic of the Speedster |magazine=[[The Grantville Gazettes|The Grantville Gazette]] |volume=55 |date=September 1, 2014 |first=Eric S. |last=Brown}}</ref>\n\nIn the following year, Brown started his ''The Monster Society'' series, an ongoing series of short stories about young adult [[LARPer]]s pretending to fight imaginary monsters in the outskirts of Grantville while growing up and dealing with the effects of 20th-century Grantville appearing suddenly in 17th-century Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://grantvillegazette.com/wp/article/the-monster-society/ |title=The Monster Society |magazine=[[The Grantville Gazettes|The Grantville Gazette]] |volume=61 |date=September 1, 2015 |first=Eric S. |last=Brown}}</ref> The first story of the series was successful enough to generate seven more sequels and subsequently republished as a single volume collection through the Flint's [[Ring of Fire Press]] in 2018.<ref name=\"mcvie2017\">{{cite web |url=https://authorsinterviews.wordpress.com/2017/11/08/here-is-my-interview-with-eric-s-brown/ |title=Here is my interview with Eric S Brown |date=November 8, 2017 |first=Fiona |last=Mcvie |work=Authors Interviews (blog)}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.smashwords.com/profile/view/ericbrowncoscom Smashwords Profile]\n* {{isfdb name|id=125025}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Eric S}}\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_S._Brown"}
{"title_page": "I\u015f\u0131n Karaca", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = I\u015f\u0131n Karaca\n|image         = I\u015f\u0131n Karaca imza g\u00fcn\u00fc.jpg\n|caption       = Karaca in 2005\n|image_size    = \n|birth_name    = I\u015f\u0131n Funda B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|03|07}} \n|birth_place   = [[London]], UK\n|occupation    = Singer, songwriter, record producer, actress\n|spouse        = ? K\u0131van\u00e7 (div.)<br/>{{marriage|Sedat Do\u011fan|2011|2013|reason=div}}<br/>{{marriage|Tu\u011frul Odaba\u015f|2016|2019|reason=div}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/kelebek/magazin/isin-karaca-kimdir-esi-kim-41021187|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca kimdir, e\u015fi kim?|newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet|date=16 November 2018|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n|children      = 2\n|module        = {{infobox musician|embed=yes\n|background    = solo_singer  <!-- mandatory format: please do not change or remove -->\n|genre         = Pop\n|years_active  = 2001\u2013present\n|label         = {{hlist|Avrupa|[[Seyhan M\u00fczik|Seyhan]]|\u0130maj|Power|PDND|Ak\u0131\u015f}}\n}}\n|website       = {{URL|www.isinkaraca.com}}\n}}\n'''I\u015f\u0131n Funda B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca''' (born 7 March 1973), better known as '''I\u015f\u0131n Karaca''' ({{IPA-tr|\u026f\u0283\u02c8\u026fn ka\u027ea\u02c8d\u0292a}}), is a British-born [[Turkish Cypriot]] pop singer.\n\n== Personal life ==\nI\u015f\u0131n Funda B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca was born into a [[Turkish Cypriots|Turkish Cypriot]] family which had emigrated to the [[United Kingdom]]. Her mother \u015eeniz B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca is a restaurant owner in [[Cyprus]] and her father Ali B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca (died 2011<ref>{{cite web|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca'ya k\u00f6t\u00fc haber|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Yasam/2011/12/04/isin-karacaya-kotu-haber|publisher=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref>) was a real estate agent originally from [[Afyonkarahisar|Afyon]], [[Turkey]]. She graduated from the London IV King Edward School with a theatre major.<ref>{{cite web|title=O bir \u015fark\u0131c\u0131, I\u015f\u0131n Karaca|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/ek_haber.php?ek=r2&haberno=836|publisher=[[Radikal]]|accessdate=11 November 2013|language=tr}}</ref>\n\nKaraca has a son (Erda K\u0131van\u00e7, born 1993) from her first husband, whom she later divorced. She had an affair for 12 years with arranger-composer Erdem Y\u00f6r\u00fck.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/magazin/anasayfa/9451952.asp?gid=222&sz=68600 | title = 12 y\u0131ll\u0131k ili\u015fki bitti | accessdate = 2008-07-18 }}</ref> Karaca married director and motocross racer Sedat Do\u011fan on 30 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gunaydin/Magazin/2010/06/19/kariyer_yukseliste | title = Ayr\u0131l\u0131k kaderim | accessdate =  | publisher = [[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] | date = 2010-06-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/magazin/magazinhatti/17917518.asp?gid=383 | title = Hamile I\u015f\u0131n Karaca gelin oldu | accessdate = 2011-05-31  | publisher = [[H\u00fcrriyet]] | date = 2011-05-31 }}</ref> She gave birth to her daughter Sasha Mia in 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.habershow.com/v4/25708-bugun-anne-olan-isin-karaca-nin-esi-olumden-dondu | title = BUG\u00dcN ANNE OLAN I\u015eIN KARACA'NIN E\u015e\u0130 \u00d6L\u00dcMDEN D\u00d6ND\u00dc | accessdate = 2011-09-18 | publisher = Habershow | date = 2011-09-18 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20130426111724/http://www.habershow.com/v4/25708-bugun-anne-olan-isin-karaca-nin-esi-olumden-dondu | archive-date = 26 April 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The couple divorced 2 years later in November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca bo\u015fand\u0131|url=http://magazin.milliyet.com.tr/isin-karaca-bosandi/magazin/detay/1787737/default.htm|publisher=[[Milliyet]]|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> On 29 December 2016, she married Tu\u011frul Odaba\u015f.<ref>{{cite web|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca evlendi|url=http://www.cnnturk.com/magazin/isin-karaca-evlendi?page=1|publisher=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]]|accessdate=29 December 2016|language=tr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = I\u015f\u0131n Karaca ile Tu\u011frul Odaba\u015f evlendi | url = http://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2016/12/29/isin-karaca-ile-tugrul-odabas-evlendi | publisher = Sabah | accessdate = 7 February 2017 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161230154904/http://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2016/12/29/isin-karaca-ile-tugrul-odabas-evlendi | archivedate = 30 December 2016}}</ref> In 2017 and 2019, her ex-husband Sedat Do\u011fan was arrested in Brazil after being caught for stealing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/yasam/2017/09/13/sedat-dogan-brezilyada-yakalandi|title=Sedat Do\u011fan Brezilya'da yakaland\u0131|publisher=Sabah|date=13 September 2019|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2019/02/22/isin-karacanin-eski-esi-sedat-dogan-yeniden-cezaevinde|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca\u2019n\u0131n eski e\u015fi Sedat Do\u011fan yeniden cezaevinde!|publisher=Sabah|date=22 February 2019|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, it was revealed that Karaca was paying a {{Turkish lira}}1 million debt left by Sedat Do\u011fan. Earlier, she had changed her daughter's family name from Do\u011fan to B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca via a court decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/magazin/isin-karaca-eski-esi-sedat-doganin-borcunu-oduyor|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca eski e\u015fi Sedat Do\u011fan'\u0131n borcunu \u00f6d\u00fcyor!|publisher=CNN T\u00fcrk|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> On 6 November 2019, Karaca and her third husband Tu\u011frul Odaba\u015f divorced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/galeri-isin-karacadan-ilk-aciklama-tugrulun-canini-yakmayin-41367977|title=\"Tu\u011frul'un can\u0131n\u0131 yakmay\u0131n\" I\u015f\u0131n Karaca'n\u0131n evlili\u011fi tek celsede bitti|publisher=H\u00fcrriyet|date=6 November 2019|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, she started dating musician Can Yap\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu.<ref>{{cite web |title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca ve Can Yap\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu'ndan ilk foto\u011fraf |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/kelebek/magazin/isin-karaca-ve-can-yapicioglundan-ilk-fotograf-41405720 |website=www.hurriyet.com.tr |accessdate=26 December 2019 |language=tr}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n\n=== Backing vocalist and rise to fame (1997\u20132004) ===\n\n[[I\u015f\u0131n]] began her musical career as vocalist for [[Sezen Aksu]]. In 1997, she performed songs in the Turkish translation of Disney's Hercules' Soundtrack. She also performed the Turkish translations of this album. In 1999 she became the lead vocalist of the musical group \"Panic Attack\",<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://patlican.ekolay.net/haber.asp?PID=2509&HaberID=458335 Patlican.com], Retrieved 28 November 2007</ref> but the group separated before releasing any albums. In 2000 she competed for Turkey on [[Eurovision Song Contest]]'s pre-eliminations with \"Bir K\u0131r\u0131k Sevda\". She didn't pass pre-eliminations for Eurovision but she represented Turkey in the [[OGAE Second Chance Contest]] and became 7th with 104 points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sechuk.com/newpage2000.htm |title=OGAE SECOND CHANCE CONTEST 2000 |accessdate=2008-07-08 }}</ref> One year later she tried again with \"Kaderimsin\", but again she wasn't selected to represent Turkey for Eurovision. In OGAE Second Chance Contest, \"Kaderimsin\" became 14th with 52 points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sechuk.com/newpage2001.htm |title=OGAE SECOND CHANCE CONTEST 2001 |accessdate=2008-07-08 }}</ref> She also appeared in Sezen Aksu's music videos \"Oh oh\" and \"Allah\u0131n Varsa\". In 2000, she was featured in \"Ge\u00e7mi\u015fe Yolculuk\" from [[Fresh B]]'s \"[[Ger\u00e7ek Kal]]\" album. Until 2001 she continued working as back vocalist of Sezen Aksu. She also modeled for the XL fashion company \"Sumak\"'s Fall-Winter catalog in 2004\u20132005. She and her brother Ak\u0131n B\u00fcy\u00fckkaraca own a musical production company: Ak\u0131\u015f Production.\n\nIn November 2009, she modeled for [[Adil I\u015f\u0131k]]'s 2009\u20132010 Fall-Winter catalogue \"Love My Body\" collection. The photoshoot was shot by famous Turkish photographer [[Serkan \u015eedele]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gazeteport.com.tr/MAGAZIN/NEWS/GP_580340 |title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca model oldu |language=tr |accessdate=2009-11-11 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130418154710/http://www.gazeteport.com.tr/MAGAZIN/NEWS/GP_580340 |archive-date=18 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs she got her fame by working with Sezen Aksu as her backing vocalist, she released her debut album, ''[[Anadilim A\u015fk]]'' (''My Native Language is Love''), with help of her. The album is released in 2001 under \"Power Records\" label. All of the songs on this album were written by Sezen Aksu, except two of them have lyrics written by Ali \u0130lyas. She made a great success with this album, becoming popular all over Turkey. Her first single ''Tutunamad\u0131m'' and second single ''Ba\u015fka Bahar'' became hits. The video for the third single \"Aram\u0131za Yollar\" was shot by Waleed Nassif. This video was the first [[high-definition video|High Definition]] video in Turkey. Famous Turkish actor [[Toprak Sergen]] also appears in this video. There's a video shot for \"Do\u011fum G\u00fcn\u00fcn Kutlu Olsun O\u011flum\", but this video was never aired due to conflicts with her music company. First release of this album sold-out quickly and they re-released with an addition of \"Tutunamad\u0131m (remix)\" in 2001. This version also sold-out quickly, and in 2006 it was re-released with \"Seyhan M\u00fczik\" label. After the first album was released, she contributed to several albums like Selmi Andak's \"Uluslararas\u0131 \u00d6d\u00fcll\u00fc Selmi Andak \u015eark\u0131lar\u0131\", Hakk\u0131 Yal\u00e7\u0131n's \"[[O \u015eark\u0131lar]]\", Alpay's \"Sessiz Kalma\" and collection of \"Yeni T\u00fcrkiye Co\u015fku Dolu\". She performed a song in soundtrack album of [[Ezel Akay]]'s movie [[Where's Firuze?]]. She also starred in this movie as guest star. In 2004 she formed a group named \"Masalc\u0131lar [Storytellers]\" with Erdem Y\u00f6r\u00fck, Eda \u00d6z\u00fclk\u00fc and Metin \u00d6z\u00fclk\u00fc. They made their first album called \"''Masalc\u0131lar I''\" in which they tell stories to children. The group intended to make a series of albums like this and they credited this inside the cover of the album, but they never released another project.\n\nIn 2004, she released her second album, ''[[\u0130\u00e7inde A\u015fk Var]]'' (''There's Love Inside''). She worked with different writers like Aysel G\u00fcrel, Suat Suna, \u00dcmit Say\u0131n. She also wrote a song in this album. This album has only one song written by Sezen Aksu. First video ''Yetinmeyi Bilir misin?'' becomes a hit. Second video \"Bekleyelim de G\u00f6relim\" also made a great success. The last video came to a Sezen Aksu cover \"Ho\u015fg\u00f6r\u00fc\".\n\nIn 2006 she contributed in Mehmet Tokat's poetry album ''\u0130nad\u0131na Sevece\u011fim''. Then she performed \"Ben Sana Vurgunum\" for Ali Kocatepe's tribute album ''41 Kere Ma\u015fallah'' which was a celebration of Ali Kocatepe's 41st year as an artist. She performed \"Eski Bir Resim\" in rap-singer Ogeday's album ''Mecburi \u0130stikamet''. She also contributed in charity album ''Ya\u015fas\u0131n Okulumuz'' which aims to make schools or improve the conditions of them, mostly in sub-urban areas.\n\n=== ''Ba\u015fka'', ''Uyan\u0131\u015f'' and Arabesque albums (2006\u201311)===\nIn 2006 she released her third solo album, ''[[33/3 Ba\u015fka]]'' (''Different''). She worked with Alper Narman and Fettah Can on this album.  She wrote a song for this album too. There are no Sezen Aksu songs in this album. First video ''Mandalinalar'' became a hit. Second video came out for \"Kalp Tanr\u0131ya Emanet\". The third video became \"B\u0131rakma\".\n\nIn 2007 she performed \"The Final Countdown\" in [[Dolapdere Big Gang]]'s [[Just Feel]]. This was the first song performed in English by I\u015f\u0131n Karaca in an official recording.\n\n[[File:Isin Karaca antalya.jpg|thumb|right|Karaca in [[Antalya]], May 2008]]\nIn 2008 she was featured in [[Ogeday]]'s Maxi Single. They performed \"Eski Bir Resim\" in [[RnB]], [[electribe]], [[House music|house]], [[Reggaeton]] and [[Electronic music|electronic]] style.<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.ogeday.net Ogeday.net] Retrieved 2 January 2008</ref> In June 2008, she performed a cover of [[Esmeray]]'s hit \"Unutama Beni\" for the theme song of [[ATV Turkey|ATV]]'s \"Elif\" TV series.\n\nI\u015f\u0131n Karaca's fourth studio album, ''[[Uyan\u0131\u015f (album)|Uyan\u0131\u015f]]'', was released on 29 May 2009. She worked with [[Sibel Ala\u015f]], Erdem Y\u00f6r\u00fck, Erol Temizel and Zeki G\u00fcner on the album. She is also a songwriter for several songs in the album.\n\nIn April 2010, she released her first arabesque album: ''[[Arabesque: Ge\u00e7mi\u015f, Ge\u00e7memi\u015f Hi\u00e7...|Arabesque]]'', which included covers of famous arabesque songs. The album was released when Arabesque music gained popularity among Turkish pop music singers. The album has sold more than 100,000 copies, which is more than her pop albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/kultur_sanat/muzik/2010/07/13/arabesque_sefasi_suruyor |title='Arabesque' sefas\u0131 s\u00fcr\u00fcyor |accessdate=2012-10-17 |publisher=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] |language=tr}}</ref> This lead her to release the sequel album in June 2011: [[Arabesque II]]. The sequel album also become successful, which has sold more than 50.000 copies.<ref>{{Cite web | url= http://www.kraltvmuzikodulleri.com/dosyaindir.asp?id=3 | title= 18. kral M\u00fczik \u00d6d\u00fclleri | accessdate= 2012-06-03 | publisher= [[M\u00fc-yap]] }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Return to pop music and Classical Turkish music project (2013\u2013present) ===\nIn July 2012, she announced from her Twitter account that she has been working on a pop album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/ishinkaraca/statuses/230259469085466624 |title=Twitter |accessdate=2012-10-17}}</ref> Later she announced the album title as ''Her \u015eey A\u015fktan'' ([[English language|English]]: ''Everything is because of love'') from her Twitter account.\n<ref>{{cite tweet|user=ishinkaraca|author=isin Karaca|number=297482204831956992|date=1 February 2013|title=Ve nihayet t\u00fcm okumalar\u0131m bitti :) #HerseyAsktan i\u00e7in geri say\u0131ma ba\u015flad\u0131k :) nihayet @akinbuyukkaraca y\u0131 memnun etmenin haz\u0131 ile ne uyurum.}}</ref> The album was released on 8 May 2013.\n\nIn 2013, she performed \"Geceyi Sana Yazd\u0131m\" in \"Onurlu Y\u0131llar\" album, which is a tribute album for [[Onur Ak\u0131n]] in his 25th anniversary in music industry.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=showkulup|author=Show Kul\u00fcp|number=298447634610409473|date=4 February 2013|title=\" \u00c7ok Yak\u0131nda\" @YvzbNgl @ishinkaraca @yasar_gunacgun @seksendort  @YoncaLodi17 @kubatcomtr @haluk_levent  @HAYKOCPQN}}</ref> On 18 March 2013, she and 16 other singers sang \"\u00c7anakkale T\u00fcrk\u00fcs\u00fc\", a special song for 98th anniversary of [[Naval operations in the Dardanelles Campaign#The Battle of March 18|Gallipoli Memorial Day]].<ref>{{cite web|title=17 Farkl\u0131 Sanat\u00e7\u0131dan \u00c7anakkale T\u00fcrk\u00fcs\u00fc Dinle - 2013|url=http://haberciniz.biz/17-farkli-sanatcidan-canakkale-turkusu-dinle-2013-1933799h.htm|accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref> In May 2014, she performed \"Vestiyer\" in [[Ahmet Sel\u00e7uk \u0130lkan]]'s duets album ''[[S\u00f6z]]''.\n\nOn 30 January 2015, she has released her first [[Turkish classical music]] album, \"Ey A\u015fk\u0131n G\u00fczel K\u0131z\u0131\" ([[English language|English]]: ''Beautiful daughter of love'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Ey A\u015fk\u0131n G\u00fczel K\u0131z\u0131|url=https://itunes.apple.com/tr/album/ey-ask-n-guzel-k-z/id960371161|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref> The first video was \"Bir Garip Yolcu (Yalan D\u00fcnya)\" released on 13 February 2015.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=ishinkaraca|author=isin Karaca|number=566181090545913856|date=13 February 2015|title=Ve art\u0131k #EyA\u015fk\u0131nG\u00fczelK\u0131z\u0131 #YalanD\u00fcnya klibi yay\u0131nda... Buyursunlar efendim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yepyeni bir I\u015f\u0131n Karaca!|url=http://gecce.com/magazin/muzik/haber/yepyeni-bir-isin-karaca|accessdate=25 April 2015|language=tr|date=2015-02-05}}</ref> In February 2015, she took part in [[Deniz Seki]]'s \"Hayat 2 Bilet\" (English: ''Life is two tickets'') video, which was shot with Seki's friends while she was imprisoned.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deniz Seki'ye sanat\u00e7\u0131 arkada\u015flar\u0131ndan moral klibi|url=http://www.iha.com.tr/haber-deniz-sekiye-sanatci-arkadaslarindan-moral-klibi-441632/|publisher=[[\u0130hlas News Agency|\u0130HA]]|accessdate=22 May 2015|language=tr}}</ref> In May 2015, she sang \"Hasret Yaras\u0131\" in [[Musa Ero\u011flu]]'s tribute album \"Gelenekten Gelece\u011fe Musa Ero\u011flu ile Bir As\u0131r\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Musa Ero\u011flu i\u00e7in devler bulu\u015ftu|url=http://www.haberturk.com/kultur-sanat/haber/1080667-musa-eroglu-icin-devler-bulustu|publisher=[[Habert\u00fcrk]]|accessdate=22 May 2015|language=tr}}</ref> In June 2015, she sang \"Kolay m\u0131\" in [[Eda \u00d6z\u00fclk\u00fc|Eda]]-[[Metin \u00d6z\u00fclk\u00fc]]'s \"Bizim \u015eark\u0131lar\" album.<ref>{{cite web|title='Bizim \u015eark\u0131lar'da bulu\u015ftular|url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/-bizim-sarkilar-da-bulustular-magazin-2022484/|publisher=[[Milliyet]]|accessdate=29 May 2015|language=tr}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she released her sixth pop music album ''[[Eyvallah (I\u015f\u0131n Karaca album)|Eyvallah]]'', which was released in December 2017. First single from the album, \"G\u00fczelim\", was released on 10 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca'dan yeni \u015fark\u0131ya yeni klip|url=http://www.sehirmagazincisi.com/Hbr-3231-Isin-Karacadan-yeni-sarkiya-yeni-klip.html|publisher=sehirmagazincisi|accessdate=28 June 2016|language=tr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806031303/http://www.sehirmagazincisi.com/Hbr-3231-Isin-Karacadan-yeni-sarkiya-yeni-klip.html|archive-date=6 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Other fields==\n\n===Acting career===\nShe had a leading role in a movie called \"Sen Ne Dilersen\" (International English title:''Whatever You Wish'') directed by Cem Ba\u015feskioglu. The movie has very talented actors like I\u015f\u0131k Yenersu, Zeynep Eronat, [[Y\u0131ld\u0131z Kenter]], Fikret Ku\u015fkan, etc. She made a great performance with her role \"Marika\" although it's her first career movie.\n[[File:I\u015f\u0131n 035.jpg|thumb|right|I\u015f\u0131n Karaca at Concert in [[Ankara]], 2005]]\n\nShe was to act in \"Her\u015feyin Bitti\u011fi Yerden\" directed by Turkish film director and actor Ezel Akay, where she co-starred with [[Okan Bay\u00fclgen]]. The movie is about [[1999 \u0130zmit earthquake]]. The film was scheduled to be released in January 2009, however it was cancelled due to financial problems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cumaertesi.zaman.com.tr/?bl=11&hn=5766 |title=\u0130kinci bir deprem olmadan bu filmi izlemek laz\u0131m |language=Turkish |accessdate=2008-08-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080813133542/http://cumaertesi.zaman.com.tr/?bl=11&hn=5766 |archive-date=13 August 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Television====\nIn 2005 she hosted a musical program called \"''I\u015f\u0131n Show''\" in channel [[ATV Turkey|ATV]]. In the show she hosted several popular Turkish singers and actors every week. The program ended on 19 August 2005. She appeared in Turkish TV series [[Haziran Gecesi]] as a guest singer.\n\nIn 2007 she and [[Vatan \u015ea\u015fmaz]] hosted \"''Kad\u0131n Her Ya\u015fta G\u00fczeldir''\" which was a beauty contest between mothers. In 2007 she also became the musical coach of Vatan \u015ea\u015fmaz in first season of \"''\u015eark\u0131 S\u00f6ylemek Laz\u0131m''\", in which popular non-singer celebrities sing songs for the show. They became very successful that they come 4th out of 12 contestants. In mid-2007 she hosted a musical show \"''Haydi S\u00f6yle''\" in channel [[Turkmax]].\n\nIn 2009, she appeared as a guest actress in Turkish adaption of [[The Golden Girls]], [[Alt\u0131n K\u0131zlar]], with her role Nurse Binnaz.\n\nOn 18 September 2012, she started hosting \"Ba\u015fucu \u015eark\u0131lar\u0131\" in [[TRT M\u00fczik]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.trtmuzik.net.tr/Program/Detail/61799/basucu-sarkilari |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107121444/http://trtmuzik.net.tr/Program/Detail/61799/basucu-sarkilari |archive-date=7 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Authorship===\nAs of 2 March 2005 she was writing a blog named \"Kaleminden\" (''From her pen'') on her official website,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.isinkaraca.com/articles.php?id=undefined |title=Kaleminden |accessdate=2008-06-23 |language=Turkish }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> that is mainly about news of her works but occasionally contains her point of view on daily events. The articles sometimes concern about global awarenesses or national problems with a wide range of interests from politics to music industry. She currently had written 66<!-- Counted last article is \"Sonunda yaz bizim eve de u\u011frad\u0131 :)\" --> articles.\n\nIn 2005 she announced that she was writing a book. Later she told that it is a diet book named \"B\u00fcy\u00fcmek \u0130\u00e7in K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fclmek Laz\u0131m\" (''Need to get smaller to grow'') and will be published when she is [[Clothing sizes|36 in size]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ekolay.net/sehir/haber.asp?Pid=1829&HaberId=499181 |title=Hedef 36 beden! |accessdate=2008-06-23 |date=2007-08-31 |language=Turkish }}</ref> The book is about her memories while losing weight, and there will be also tips about diet recipes.\n\nIn 2008 she became columnist of 2kadin.com<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2kadin.com|title=En iyi Kad\u0131n Sitesi|website=2kadin.com}}</ref> website and has been writing since 18 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2kadin.com/blog.all.21174.htm |title=I\u015f\u0131n Karaca t\u00fcm yaz\u0131lar\u0131 |accessdate=2008-06-23 |language=Turkish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080901230756/http://www.2kadin.com/blog.all.21174.htm |archivedate=1 September 2008 }}</ref> Her columns are about relationships, and her target audience is women.\n\n===Fashion design===\nIn May 2016, she announced her \"2016 Fall-Winter\" fashion catalog to be released in September 2016. She said, she had designed clothes mainly aimed at plus-sized people.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Karahasan|first1=Sefa|title=I\u015eIN KARACA MODACI OLDU|url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/isin-karaca-modaci-oldu/cadde/ydetay/2241652/default.htm|publisher=[[Milliyet]]|accessdate=10 May 2016|language=tr|date=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2005, she rebuilt the library of \"G\u00f6lc\u00fck K\u0131z Meslek High School\" which was damaged in [[1999 \u0130zmit earthquake]]. On 3 July 2005 she gave a charity concert and donated the income to the school.<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.isinkaraca.com/articles.php?id=21 isinkaraca.com]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved 21 January 2008</ref> On 19 April 2006 she opened the library, which was named after her.<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.isinkaraca.com/articles.php?id=41 isinkaraca.com]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved 21 January 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=G\u00fclezer|first=Soner|title=E\u011fitime sanat\u00e7\u0131 deste\u011fi|url=http://hurarsiv.hurriyet.com.tr/goster/haber.aspx?id=4284821&tarih=2006-04-21|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|accessdate=4 May 2014|language=tr|date=2006-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 she contributed in [[Ya\u015fas\u0131n Okulumuz (album)|Ya\u015fas\u0131n Okulumuz]] project, which aims to make schools or improve the conditions of them, mostly in sub-urban areas.<ref name=\"tocev\">{{cite web|title=Ya\u015fas\u0131n Okulumuz|url=http://www.tocev.org.tr/projeler.asp?id=20|publisher=[[To\u00e7ev]]|accessdate=4 May 2014|language=tr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504141602/http://www.tocev.org.tr/projeler.asp?id=20|archive-date=4 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> She sang the theme song with other artists and gave one of her songs \"Sen\" to be included in the album made for the project. She also joined the charity night aired on [[Show TV]], where she and other voluntary artists answered calls for donations.<ref name=\"tocev\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=\u00c7akkal|first=\u00d6mer|title=S\u00f6zler beyaz camda kald\u0131|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/aktuel/?t=12.05.2007&i=44612|publisher=[[Yeni \u015eafak]]|accessdate=4 May 2014|language=tr|date=2007-05-10}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, she contributed in charity album \"Gel Sende Kat\u0131l Umudun \u015eark\u0131s\u0131na\" (''Come, join the song of hope''), a song made for \"KACUV\" (''Foundation of Hope for Kids with Cancer''). This project aims to build hygienic houses to be used for treatment of kids who had cancer.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV8'de kanserli \u00e7ocuklara 'Aile Evi'|url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/2008/04/23/tv/index.html|publisher=[[Milliyet]]|accessdate=4 May 2014|language=tr|date=2008-04-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she and Sedat Do\u011fan started a project named \"Do\u011fudan Do\u011fan I\u015f\u0131k\" (''The light that sets from east''). It is an exhibition, which aims renewal of village schools in Turkey. They started their first photoshoot in [[Mardin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/13096546.asp?gid=233 |title=\u0130ran k\u00fclt\u00fcr\u00fc Topkap\u0131'da |accessdate=2009-12-03 |date=2009-12-03 |publisher=H\u00fcrriyet |language=tr}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|I\u015f\u0131n Karaca discography}}\n\n===Albums===\n#''[[Anadilim A\u015fk]]'' [My Native Language is Love] (28 November 2001)\n#''[[\u0130\u00e7inde A\u015fk Var]]'' [There's Love Inside] (16 December 2004)\n#''[[Ba\u015fka 33/3]]'' [Different] (19 June 2006)\n#''[[Uyan\u0131\u015f (album)|Uyan\u0131\u015f]]'' [Awakening] (29 May 2009)\n# ''[[Arabesque: Ge\u00e7mi\u015f, Ge\u00e7memi\u015f Hi\u00e7...]]'' [Arabesque: Past, has never passed...] (22 April 2010)\n# ''[[Arabesque II|Arabesque II: Ge\u00e7mi\u015f Bize Yak\u0131\u015f\u0131yor]]'' [Arabesque II: Past suits us] (June 2011)\n#''[[Her \u015eey A\u015fktan]]'' [Everything is because of love] (8 May 2013)\n#''[[Ey A\u015fk\u0131n G\u00fczel K\u0131z\u0131]]'' [Beautiful daughter of love] (30 January 2015)\n# ''[[Eyvallah (I\u015f\u0131n Karaca album)|Eyvallah]]'' (1 December 2017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes !! Format\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Where's Firuze?]]'' (Turkish: Neredesin Firuze) || herself || guest singer ||rowspan=\"2\"| Film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2005 || ''[[Sen Ne Dilersen]]'' (int. title: Whatever You Wish) || Marika || First movie\n|-\n| ''[[I\u015f\u0131n Show]]'' || Host || Musical show, aired for 7 episodes || TV Show\n|-\n| ''[[Haziran Gecesi]]'' || herself || 17th episode, guest singer || TV Series\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2007 || ''Kad\u0131n Her Ya\u015fta G\u00fczeldir'' || Co-host || with [[Vatan \u015ea\u015fmaz]] ||rowspan=\"3\"| TV Show\n|-\n| ''\u015eark\