ref> returning  for a second run from 1 September to 7 October 2018, before being extended until 21 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/eugenius-return-palace-111409185/|title=Eugenius! to return to The Other Palace {{!}} Official London Theatre|work=Official London Theatre|access-date=2018-09-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Planned West End engagement ==\nFollowing the run at [[The Other Palace]], a transfer was planned for a limited 10-week season at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]] in [[West End theatre|London's West End]] from 27 October 2018 to 7 January 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/eugenius-west-end-transfer_47728.html|title=Eugenius! to transfer to the West End|access-date=2018-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref> however it was later announced that this would not be happening.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hemley |first1=Matthew |title=Musical Eugenius! cancels West End run |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2018/musical-eugenius-cancels-west-end-run/ |accessdate=11 October 2018 |work=The Stage |date=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Character\n!London Palladium\n<small>(2016 concert)</small>\n!The Other Palace\n<small>(2018 - 1st run)</small>\n!The Other Palace\n<small>(2018 - 2nd run)</small>\n!Recording Artist\n<small> (2019) <small>\n|-\n!Eugene\n| align=\"center\" |Louis Maskell\n| align=\"center\" |Liam Forde\n| align=\"center\" |Rob Houchen\n| align=\"center\" |Ben Adams\n|-\n!Janey\n| align=\"center\" |[[Amy Lennox]]\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |Laura Baldwin\n| align=\"center\" |[[Amy Lennox]]\n|-\n!Feris\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |Daniel Buckley\n|-\n!Evil Lord Hector\n| align=\"center\" |[[Warwick Davis]]\n| align=\"center\" |Ian Hughes\n| align=\"center\" |[[Neil McDermott]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Warwick Davis]]\n|-\n!Theo\n| align=\"center\" |Samuel Holmes\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |Scott Paige\n|-\n!Lex\n| align=\"center\" |[[David Bedella]]\n| align=\"center\" |Cameron Blakely\n| align=\"center\" |Alex Bourne\n|align=\"center\" |Mike Jibson\n|-\n!Carrie/Super Hot Lady\n| align=\"center\" |[[Summer Strallen]]\n| align=\"center\" |Melissa James\n| align=\"center\" |Emily Tierney\n|align=\"center\" |[[Joanne Clifton]]\n|-\n!Gerhard/Tough Man\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |Shaun Dalton\n\n|-\n!Space Diva/Mrs Truthstretcher\n!\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |Alison Arnopp\n|align=\"center\" |[[Sharon D. Clarke]]\n|-\n!Space Lord\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Brian Blessed]] <small>(voice)</small>\n!Narrator\n|align=\"center\" |[[Marcus Brigstocke]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.eugeniusthemusical.com}}\n\n[[Category:2016 musicals]]\n[[Category:Original musicals]]\n[[Category:British musicals]]\n[[Category:West End musicals]]\n", "name_user": "Boffy b", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed table which had no closing bracket", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugenius!"}
{"title_page": "Dimebag Darrell", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Dimebag|the episode of The Americans|Dimebag (The Americans)}}\n{{Short description|American musician and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Dimebag Darrell\n| image            = Dimebag.jpg\n| caption          = Abbott in June 2004\n| birth_name       = Darrell Lance Abbott\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1966|8|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Ennis, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2004|12|8|1966|8|20}}\n| death_place      = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_cause      = [[Gunshot wounds]]\n| resting_place    = Moore Memorial Gardens, [[Arlington, Texas]]\n| other_names      = {{ublist|Diamond Darrell (1981\u201393)|Dimebag Darrell (1994 on)}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 1981\u20132004\n| spouse           = \n| partner          = Rita Haney (1984\u20132004)\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed            = yes\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Groove metal]]|[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]|[[Southern metal]]|[[thrash metal]]|[[glam metal]] (early)}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Guitar|vocals}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Atco Records|Atco]]|[[Big Vin Records|Big Vin]]|[[East West Records|East West]]|[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]|Metal Magic}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Pantera]]|[[Damageplan]]|[[David Allan Coe]]|[[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]]|[[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]]|[[Gasoline (band)|Gasoline]]}}\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|dimebagdarrell.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Darrell Lance Abbott''' (August 20, 1966 \u2013 December 8, 2004), best known by his stage name '''Dimebag Darrell''', was an American musician and songwriter. He was the [[guitarist]] of the [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands [[Pantera]] and [[Damageplan]], both of which he co-founded alongside his brother [[Vinnie Paul]]. As one of the driving forces behind the development of [[groove metal]], he is considered among the most influential guitarists in heavy metal history.\n\nA son of [[country music]] producer [[Jerry Abbott]], Abbott began playing guitar at age 12, and Pantera released its debut album, ''[[Metal Magic]]'' (1983), when he was 16. Originally a [[glam metal]] musician, Abbott went by the stage name '''Diamond Darrell''' at the time. Two further albums in the glam metal style followed in [[Projects in the Jungle|1984]] and [[I Am the Night (album)|1985]], before original vocalist [[Terry Glaze]] was replaced by [[Phil Anselmo]] in 1986 and ''[[Power Metal (album)|Power Metal]]'' (1988) was released. The band's major-label debut, ''[[Cowboys from Hell]]'' (1990), introduced a groove metal sound to which Abbott's guitar playing was central. This sound was refined on ''[[Vulgar Display of Power]]'' (1992), and the group's third major-label record, ''[[Far Beyond Driven]]'', debuted at No. 1 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'' in 1994.  \n\nTensions within Pantera reduced its output after the release of ''[[The Great Southern Trendkill]]'' in 1996, and ''[[Reinventing the Steel]]'' (2000) was the band's final studio album before its acrimonious separation in 2003. Abbott subsequently formed Damageplan with his brother Vinnie Paul and released ''[[New Found Power]]'', the band's debut and only album, in 2004. Other works by Abbott included a collaboration with [[David Allan Coe]] titled ''[[Rebel Meets Rebel]]'' (2006) and numerous guest [[guitar solo]]s for bands such as [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]]. Abbott was [[Columbus nightclub shooting|shot and killed]] by a deranged fan on December 8, 2004, while on stage with Damageplan at the Alrosa Villa nightclub in Columbus, Ohio. Three others were murdered in the shooting before the perpetrator was killed by police. \n\nAbbott was ranked at No. 92 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" in 2011, and No. 19 on ''[[Metal Hammer|Louder]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 50 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" in 2018. He placed at No. 5 on [[Gibson]]'s list of \"The Top 10 Metal Guitarists of All Time\" in 2015, and the same year was ranked as the most influential metal guitarist of the past 25 years by [[VH1]].\n\n==Childhood==\n\nDarrell Lance Abbott was born in [[Ennis, Texas]],{{sfn|Daniels|2013|p=2}} on August 20, 1966, the second son to Carolyn and [[Jerry Abbott]], a [[country music]] producer.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=3}} His elder brother [[Vinnie Paul]] was born on March 11, 1964. Abbott's parents divorced in 1979, after seventeen years of marriage,{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=4}} but his family life remained happy.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=16}} The brothers lived with their mother Carolyn, in a [[ranch-style house]] on Monterrey Street in [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=8}} Carolyn was supportive of her sons' musical endeavors.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=5}}\n\nAbbott took up the guitar when he was twelve. His first guitar was a [[Gibson Les Paul|Les Paul]]-style [[Hondo (guitar company)|Hondo]], which he received along with a [[Pignose]] amplifier on his twelfth birthday.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=10}} Influenced by [[Black Sabbath]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] and [[Van Halen]],{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=11}} he would initially spend time in his room standing in front of a mirror holding the guitar while wearing [[Ace Frehley]]-style makeup, though he was unable to play the instrument at the time.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=8}}<ref name=vinnie2016>{{cite web|url =https://www.loudersound.com/features/he-was-the-wild-life-of-the-party-vinnie-paul-remembers-dimebag-darrell|title ='He was the wild life of the party' - Vinnie Paul remembers Dimebag Darrell|website =Louder|first =Jerry|last =Ewing|date =December 8, 2016}}</ref> Jerry learned Kiss songs on guitar in order to teach Darrell how to play them.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=11}} Darrell also learned from country musicians who recorded at Jerry's studio, such as [[Bugs Henderson]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=12}}\n\nVinnie had begun playing the drums before Darrell received his first guitar. Darrell had previously tried to play the drums; Vinnie later said: \"I just got better than him and wouldn't let him play them anymore.\"<ref name=vinnie2016/> The Abbott brothers' first [[jam session]] consisted of six hours of \"[[Smoke on the Water]]\".<ref name=vinnie2016/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=12}} They took inspiration from [[Alex Van Halen|Alex]] and [[Eddie Van Halen]],{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=217}} and Vinnie said in a 2016 interview that he and Darrell were \"inseparable\" after they began playing music together.<ref name=vinnie2016/>\n\nAt age 14, Abbott entered a guitar contest at the Agora Ballroom in [[Dallas]], in which [[Dean Zelinsky]], founder of [[Dean Guitars]], was one of the judges.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott's mother accompanied him to the club because he was not old enough to enter on his own.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=26}} He won the competition; Zelinsky recalled that \"[Abbott] blew everyone away.\"<ref name=reinventingsqueal>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/features/dimebag-darrell-reinventing-squeal|title =Dimebag Darrell: Reinventing the Squeal|website =Guitar World|first =Chris|last =Gill|date =January 2010}}</ref> Abbott won many other guitar contests in the area, and was eventually asked not to compete and instead judge the competitions so others could win.<ref name=australianguitar/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=111}}\n\n==Music career==\n===Pantera===\n{{Further|Pantera}}\n====Early glam metal years====\n\n[[Pantera]] was formed in 1981. Vinnie was asked to join a band alongside his high school classmates [[Terry Glaze]] (guitar), Tommy Bradford (bass) and Donny Hart (vocals). Vinnie accepted the invitation, but on the condition that Darrell would also join the band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=13}} Glaze later recalled that they were unsure about this request, as Darrell \"wasn't very good\" and, two years their junior, \"was a little skinny, scrawny dude\",{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=13}} but they ultimately agreed. In 1989, Darrell made the same request when [[Dave Mustaine]] asked him to join [[Megadeth]]. As Mustaine had already recruited drummer [[Nick Menza]] and would not hire Vinnie, Darrell decided to stay with Pantera.<ref name=\"Sharpe-Young\">{{cite book|last =Sharpe-Young|first =Garry|title =New Wave of American Heavy Metal|date =November 2005|publisher =Zonda Books|location =New Zealand|page =232|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=uIIf03bGyAAC}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|pp=14, 71}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/dimebag-darrell/6363759/dave-mustaine-on-dimebag-darrell-he-would-want-us-to-remember-him|title =Dave Mustaine on 'Dimebag' Darrell: 'He Would Want Us to Remember Him by Celebrating and Not Mourn'|website =Billboard|first =Dan|last =Epstein|date =December 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine =Guitar World|date =October 2004|url =https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/dave_mustaine_kerry_king_hates_my_guts.html|title =Dave Mustaine: Kerry King Hates My Guts|quote =That's true. That was around 1989. I had just hired Nick [Menza, drums] and Pantera were still playing around Texas. I asked Darrell if he was interested and he says to me [assumes southern accent], 'Yeah, man, but my brother's gotta come, too.' And I said, 'What is he, a roadie?' I told him I already had a drummer, and he said, 'Ah, then fuck it. Good luck, brother!'}}</ref>\n\nBy 1982, Hart left the band and was replaced by Glaze on vocals, while [[Rex Brown]] took Bradford's place as bassist.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=14}} Abbott originally shared lead guitar with Glaze, but soon took permanent status as lead guitarist. Glaze said: \"[Abbott] just morphed over a six-month period. ... When he came out, he could play, like, \"[[Eruption (instrumental)|Eruption]]\" and \"[[Crazy Train]]\".\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=16}} Abbott adopted the stage name \"Diamond Darrell\",{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=20}} in reference to the Kiss song \"[[Black Diamond (Kiss song)|Black Diamond]]\".{{sfn|Daniels|2013|p=32}}\n\nInspired by Kiss, Van Halen and Judas Priest, Pantera originally had a [[glam metal]] style and was image conscious: the members wore [[spandex]], makeup and hairspray when on stage.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=20}} The band signed to Metal Magic Records, which was created by \"Jerry Eld'n\", an alias of Abbott's father Jerry. Pantera released its first album, ''[[Metal Magic]]'', in 1983, when Abbott was 16.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=20}} A review in the November 1983 issue of Texas-based music magazine ''Buddy'' said Abbott's [[guitar solo|solos]] \"tend to be asymmetrical in that the old theory of musical thought consisting of statements alternating with appropriate responses is ignored and replaced by authoritative delivery of the player's own concept of what should happen\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=21}}\n\nPantera released ''[[Projects in the Jungle]]'' and ''[[I Am the Night (album)|I Am the Night]]'' in 1984 and 1985, respectively. Both albums followed on in the glam metal style, and were comparable to ''[[Shout at the Devil]]''-era [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]],{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=43}} though ''I Am the Night'' had a slightly heavier sound than previous releases.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=44}} Around this time, the Abbott brothers began listening to bands such as [[Metallica]] and [[Slayer]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=44}} Darrell was particularly taken by Metallica's ''[[Ride the Lightning]]'' (1984).{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=48}} Glaze was unhappy with the Abbott brothers' desire to move towards a heavier sound; he later said he \"didn't want to go that heavy. I didn't like it as well if the guitar was the main thing, like the Metallica songs.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=49}} This conflict, along with a contractual dispute, led to his departure in 1986.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=50}}\n\nGlaze was replaced by [[Phil Anselmo]] in late 1986.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=52}} This new lineup briefly signed with [[Gold Mountain Records]], but released ''[[Power Metal (album)|Power Metal]]'' (1988) on Metal Magic. Abbott said Gold Mountain \"wanted to change our style and make us sound like [[Bon Jovi]], which is not quite up our alley\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=53}} Anselmo did not write any of the lyrics for ''Power Metal'', and the band was still in the process of distancing themselves from glam metal,{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=54}} but the album evidenced a stylistic change.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=69}} A retrospective [[AllMusic]] album review by Bradley Torreano said Abbott's \"speedy riffs\" were one of the \"more charming elements\" of the band's sound.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allmusic.com/album/power-metal-mw0000858526|title =Power Metal - Pantera|website =AllMusic|first =Bradley|last =Torreano}}</ref> Brown said in a 1988 interview that \"Darrell has always been chunking those riffs out from the start. But now with Phil in the band we've got a chance to make those riffs fully happen instead of having some gay singer over the top of them!\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=54}}\n\n====Development of groove metal====\n\nAfter the release of ''Power Metal'', Pantera formed a relationship with Walter O'Brien and Andy Gould of [[Concrete Marketing|Concrete Management]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=69}} As Concrete managed other bands that were signed to [[Metal Blade Records]], Gould contacted [[Brian Slagel]] of Metal Blade and asked him to sign Pantera. The $75,000 requested for the production of a new album was too much for Slagel, who rejected the offer.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=70}} The Metal Blade rejection was one of many major-label rejections for the band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=71}} Pantera eventually attained a major-label deal with [[Atco Records]], after Atco's talent scout Mark Ross was impressed by one of the band's live performances.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=75}}\n\n''[[Cowboys from Hell]]'' was released on July 24, 1990. The album was produced by [[Terry Date]]; [[Max Norman]] was the original choice for producer but he opted to produce [[Lynch Mob]]'s ''[[Wicked Sensation]]'' instead. Date also served as producer for Pantera's next three albums.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=77}} ''Cowboys from Hell'' marked the development of what would become Pantera's familiar sound,<ref name=loudwire28/> to which Abbott's guitar playing was central.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=84}} Self-described as \"power groove\",<ref name=loudwire28>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-cowboys-from-hell-album-anniversary/|title =28 Years Ago: Pantera Find Their Voice With 'Cowboys From Hell'|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title =Music of the 1990s|first =Thomas|last =Harrison|publisher =ABC-CLIO|date =2011|isbn =9780313379437|page =101}}</ref> the album became a \"blueprint-defining\" work for [[groove metal]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/projects-in-the-jungle-mw0000909464 |title=Projects in the Jungle - Pantera |website =AllMusic|first =Eduardo|last =Rivadavia}}</ref> a sub-genre with the heaviness and intensity of [[thrash metal]] but played at a slower tempo.<ref name=loudwire28/><ref>{{cite book|title =Historical Dictionary of Popular Music|first =Norman|last =Abjorensen|publisher =Rowman & Littlefield|date =2017|isbn =9781538102152|page =384}}</ref> [[Southern rock]] elements were incorporated into the sound;<ref name=loudwire28/> Pantera's \"groove\" is commonly attributed to the Abbott brothers' fondness for [[ZZ Top]].<ref name=louderfeature>{{cite web|url =https://www.loudersound.com/features/how-pantera-went-from-a-glam-band-to-redefining-metal|title =Pantera: how an ex-glam band from Texas redefined metal|website =Louder|first =Dom|last =Lawson|date =December 21, 2018}}</ref> ''Cowboys from Hell'' was certified gold in 1993, and platinum in 1997.<ref name=loudwire28/>\n\nPantera played close to 200 shows supporting ''Cowboys from Hell'', as it toured for nearly two years.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=97}} Aside from breaks to develop new material, the band spent most of the 1990s touring;{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=78}} Abbott gained a reputation as a wild figure on tour and a heavy drinker.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=88}} Pantera recorded its second major-label album in the space of two months. Released on February 25, 1992, ''[[Vulgar Display of Power]]'' was a refinement of the groove metal sound.<ref name=louderfeature/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=98}} The band had sought to create a heavier album than ''Cowboys from Hell'', as Anselmo fully embraced a [[Hardcore punk|hardcore]]-inspired shouted vocal delivery. Abbott composed most of the riffs and song structures, and further attempted to mesh his guitar with Brown's bass to create what Brown later described as \"one giant tone\".<ref name=loudwire26>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-vulgar-display-of-power-anniversary/|title =26 Years Ago: Pantera Released The Groundbreaking 'Vulgar Display of Power'|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =February 25, 2019}}</ref> ''Vulgar Display of Power'' debuted at No. 44 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'', and it stayed on the chart for 79 weeks.<ref name=loudwire26/> In 2017, it was ranked at No. 10 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time\", with Abbott's \"serrated rhythms and squealing solos\" highlighted.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/pantera-vulgar-display-of-power-1992-195691/|title =The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time: Pantera, \u2018Vulgar Display of Power\u2019 (1992)|website =Rolling Stone|first =Richard|last =Bienstock|date =June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dimebag Darrell with Pantera.jpg|thumb|Abbott on stage with Pantera, 1991]]\nAbbott had transformed his appearance by the time of ''Vulgar Display of Power''{{'}}s release to that which he would maintain for the rest of his life. He sported a dyed [[goatee]], a razorblade pendant (in homage to Judas Priest's ''[[British Steel (album)|British Steel]]''), cargo shorts and sleeveless shirts.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=103}} Feeling that \"Diamond Darrell\" no longer suited his image or sound, Abbott adopted the stage name \"Dimebag Darrell\" instead.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/dimebag-stage-name-origins/|title =Dimebag - Stage Name Origins|website =Loudwire|first =Graham|last =Hartmann|date =June 6, 2012}}</ref> The name was originally coined by Anselmo.<ref name=billboardrita/> It was in reference to Abbott's refusal to accept more than a dime bag (slang for $10 worth)<ref>{{cite book|title =Sex, Drugs, and Murder: 15 Music Murder Scandals That Shocked the World|first =William|last =Webb|publisher =Absolute Crime|page =17}}</ref> of [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]]<ref>{{cite book|title =Historic Columbus Crimes: Mama's in the Furnace, the Thing & More|first1 =David|last1 =Meyers|first2 =Elise|last2 =Meyers-Walker|publisher =Arcadia Publishing|date =2010|isbn =9781614231202|page=131}}</ref> at one time\u2014even if offered for free\u2014as he did not want to be caught with the drug on-hand.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=23}}\n\nAll of Pantera's albums until 1994 were recorded at Pantego Sound, the studio owned by the Abbott brothers' father Jerry.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=107}} It was conveniently located a short distance from the Abbotts' home.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=108}} After ''Vulgar Display of Power'' was released, Jerry closed Pantego Sound and opened a new studio, Abtrax, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], as he hoped to fulfill his dream of becoming a country songwriter.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=105}} Pantera's third major-label album, ''[[Far Beyond Driven]]'', was recorded at Abtrax. Abbott said in a 1994 ''[[Guitar Player]]'' interview: \"We were fuckin' flying [to Nashville] for three weeks at a time, writing songs and cutting them.\" This led to the members spending most of their downtime in each other's hotel rooms consuming drugs, rather than following their normal routines as they did when recording at Pantego Sound.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=108}} They [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] the album at Dallas Sound Labs, which was close to their homes.<ref name=revolverfbd/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/magazine/dimebag-darrell-talks-far-beyond-driven-amps-and-more-previously-unreleased-1994-interview|title =Dimebag Darrell Talks 'Far Beyond Driven,' Amps and More: Previously Unreleased 1994 Interview|website =Guitar World|first =Chris|last =Gill|date =June 16, 2014}}</ref> ''Far Beyond Driven'' was released on March 15, 1994, on [[EastWest Records]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=116}} It sold 186,000 copies in its first week to debut at No. 1 on the ''Billboard 200'',{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=115}} and has since been described as the heaviest album ever to debut at No. 1.<ref name=revolverfbd/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=115}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/pantera-far-beyond-driven-1994-3-195056/|title =The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time: Pantera, \u2018Far Beyond Driven\u2019 (1994)|website =Rolling Stone|first =Richard|last =Bienstock|date =June 21, 2017}}</ref> Before the release, the band was expected to follow the lead of Metallica's [[Metallica (album)|eponymous album]] by taking a more commercially-friendly approach.<ref name=revolverfbd>{{cite web|url =https://www.revolvermag.com/music/panteras-far-beyond-driven-story-behind-heaviest-album-debut-no-1|title =Pantera's 'Far Beyond Driven': The Story Behind the Heaviest Album to Debut at No. 1|website =Revolver|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =April 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pantera-look-back-at-20-years-of-far-beyond-driven-241999/|title =Pantera Look Back at 20 Years of 'Far Beyond Driven'|website =Rolling Stone|first =Kory|last =Grow|date =March 27, 2014}}</ref> Instead, Pantera wanted an even heavier work than ''Vulgar Display of Power''. Abbott said in 1994: \"We're into topping ourselves. Most bands come out with a heavy record, then it gets lighter and lighter. You're stuck listening to the first record, wishing and dreaming. That ain't what we're about.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=117}}\n\n====Band tensions and separation====\n\nThe lead single from ''Far Beyond Driven'', \"[[I'm Broken]]\", was inspired by Anselmo's chronic back pain.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/philip-anselmo-pantera-im-broken-exclusive/|title =Philip Anselmo Talks Vulnerability on Pantera's 'I'm Broken'|website =Loudwire|first =Graham|last =Hartmann|date =March 25, 2014}}</ref> To treat the pain during the tour supporting ''Far Beyond Driven'', Anselmo began heavily consuming alcohol, painkillers and ultimately [[heroin]]. He would travel on his own tour bus and isolate himself from the other band members until twenty or thirty minutes before they were due to perform. Anselmo recalled in a 2014 interview that he would drink \"an entire bottle of [[Wild Turkey (bourbon)|Wild Turkey]] every night before a show to numb the pain\", and he often interrupted the performances by ranting on stage.<ref name=revolverfbd/> Due to the tensions within the band, recordings for Pantera's next album, ''[[The Great Southern Trendkill]]'', were held separately: Darrell, Vinnie and Brown recorded at Chasin' Jason Studio (a studio Darrell had constructed in a barn in his backyard) while Anselmo recorded the vocals at [[Trent Reznor]]'s Nothing Studios in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=loudwiregstk>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-the-great-southern-trendkill-album-anniversary/|title =22 Years Ago: Pantera Release 'The Great Southern Trendkill'|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =May 7, 2017}}</ref> Abbott experimented with new guitars during the recording; he stated in 1996 that he wrote \"[[Suicide Note (song)|Suicide Note Pt. 1]]\" the first time he used a [[twelve-string guitar]] which [[Washburn Guitars]] had sent to him.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=146}} The recording also saw Abbott draw on riffs he had composed much earlier:{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=146}} he wrote the [[Outro (music)|outro-solo]] to \"[[Floods (Pantera song)|Floods]]\" in the pre-Anselmo era, and he had previously recorded a 90-minute loop of it as a lullaby for his girlfriend.<ref>{{cite book|title =Official Truth, 101 Proof: The Inside Story of Pantera|first =Rex|last =Brown|publisher =Hachette|isbn =9780306821387|page =111}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 1996, ''The Great Southern Trendkill'' was released. It peaked at No. 4 on the ''Billboard 200'', staying on the chart for 13 weeks. It is considered to be Pantera's most [[extreme metal|extreme]] work,<ref name=loudwiregstk/> and features some of the band's [[Guitar tuning#Dropped tunings|lowest-tuned]] tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-the-great-southern-trendkill-20th-anniversary-edition/|title =Pantera's 'The Great Southern Trendkill' Gets 20th Anniversary Edition|website =Loudwire|first =Chad|last =Childers|date =August 12, 2016}}</ref> On July 13, Anselmo [[Opioid overdose|overdosed]] on heroin following the band's performance at the Dallas [[Starplex Amphitheatre]] and was [[clinically dead]] for \"four to five minutes\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}}<ref>{{cite web|url =http://articles.latimes.com/1996-07-19/entertainment/ca-25610_1_los-angeles|title =Back From the Brink|website =Los Angeles Times|first =Shauna|last =Snow|date =July 19, 1996}}</ref> He recovered quickly and performed at the band's next show in San Antonio two days afterwards, but the incident created a lasting rift within the band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=148}} Anselmo also had released ''[[NOLA (album)|NOLA]]'', the debut album of one of his side projects [[Down (band)|Down]], in 1995, and supported the album with a 13-show tour.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=148}} The other Pantera members were originally unperturbed by Anselmo's side projects; Abbott explained at the time: \"Phil's a musical guy and he likes to stay busy.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=148}}\n\nThe touring for ''The Great Southern Trendkill'' widened the rift within the band, and the recording sessions for their next album, ''[[Reinventing the Steel]]'', were troublesome.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=171}} Vinnie said in an interview after the album's release: \"It was like pulling teeth to get [Anselmo] down to the studio. He didn't like any of the material, and it was always just like this head-butting contest.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=172}} Also during the recording, the Abbotts' mother, Carolyn, was diagnosed with lung cancer, and died six weeks later on September 12, 1999. This had a profound effect on the brothers, especially Darrell.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=172}} ''Reinventing the Steel'' was released on March 21, 2000. Abbott said of it: \"We still play lead guitar ... Bands hardly ever play lead guitar anymore. Dude, back in the seventies, if you couldn't play the guitar or sing, you were nobody. Now music is so easy\u2014all you've got to do is tune your guitar to an open chord and jump around.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=176}} Like ''The Great Southern Trendkill'', ''Reinventing the Steel'' peaked at No. 4 on the ''Billboard 200''.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=176}}\n\nPantera were in Ireland, set to begin a European tour, on September 11, 2001. Due to the [[September 11 attacks]], the tour was canceled and the members returned to Texas, where they agreed to take a short hiatus.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=185}} In March 2002, Down released its second record, ''[[Down II: A Bustle in Your Hedgerow]]'', which featured Brown on bass. Two months later, [[Superjoint Ritual]]\u2014another of Anselmo's bands\u2014released its debut album, ''[[Use Once and Destroy]]''.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=186}} The Abbotts believed that Pantera would regroup in 2003, after the tours supporting ''Down II'' and ''Use Once and Destroy'' were concluded. Instead, Anselmo recorded a second album with Superjoint Ritual, ''[[A Lethal Dose of American Hatred]]'' (2003).{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=187}} Also around this time, Darrell received a phone call from Brown, who indicated that he would not return to Pantera.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=188}} The separation of Pantera was marked by the release of a greatest hits album, ''[[The Best of Pantera: Far Beyond the Great Southern Cowboys' Vulgar Hits!]]'', on September 23, 2003.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=188}}\n\n===Damageplan===\n{{Further|Damageplan}}\nAbbott was dejected by the separation of Pantera;{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=195}} he felt that all he had worked for had been \"ripped out from under [him]\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=197}} As continuing Pantera without Anselmo likely would have resulted in a lengthy and expensive legal battle regarding the ownership of the \"Pantera\" brand, the Abbott brothers decided to form a new band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=200}} They recorded demos at Darrell's backyard studio in February 2003.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=203}} [[Patrick Lachman]] of [[Halford (band)|Halford]] joined as vocalist and [[Bob Kakaha]] was recruited on bass, and the band signed with [[Elektra Records]] later in 2003. The name of the band originally was New Found Power, but they later decided on [[Damageplan]]. ''[[New Found Power]]'' instead served as the title of group's debut album, which was released on February 10, 2004.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=204}} It did not near the commercial success of Pantera's major-label releases:{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=220}} it sold 44,000 copies in its first week to debut at No. 38 on the ''Billboard 200'' and had sold a modest 160,000 copies by December.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=233}} \n\nDamageplan spent most of 2004 on its Devastation Across the Nation tour. To rebuild a fanbase, the band toured nightclubs across the country.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=210}} The members had planned to record a follow-up album.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=210}} This did not materialize due to [[#Death|Abbott's murder]] at a show in Columbus, Ohio, on December 8, 2004.\n\n===Other projects===\n\nThe Abbott brothers listened to country singer [[David Allan Coe]] while growing up as their parents were fans of the performer, and often used Coe's \"Jack Daniels If You Please\" as introductory music for Pantera shows.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=164}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/59584/panteracoe-album-unearthed-for-may-release|title =Pantera/Coe Album Unearthed For May Release|website =Billboard|author =Staff writer(s)|date =February 24, 2006}}</ref> Darrell first met Coe in 1999, at one of his performances at [[Billy Bob's Texas]]. After the performance, Darrell waited in an autograph line to introduce himself and give Coe his phone number. They subsequently formed a friendship and Coe began spending time at Darrell's house, where the Abbott brothers and Coe played music in Darrell's backyard studio. They recruited Brown to play bass and the group sporadically recorded from 1999 to 2003.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=165}} The resulting album, ''[[Rebel Meets Rebel]]'', was released on May 2, 2006, on Vinnie's [[Big Vin Records]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=166}} Megan Frye of AllMusic stated ''Rebel Meets Rebel'' is \"groundbreaking in that it will please fans of both country and metal because the music is simultaneously both styles \u2013 it's never a fusion, they simply exist together\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allmusic.com/album/rebel-meets-rebel-mw0000407040|title =Rebel Meets Rebel|website =AllMusic|first =Megan|last =Frye}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Abbott and the other Pantera members collaborated with [[Rob Halford]] on a track titled \"Light Comes Out of Black\", which was released on the [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)#Soundtrack|''Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' soundtrack]].<ref name=revolvervdop>{{cite web|url =https://www.revolvermag.com/music/panteras-vulgar-display-power-epic-story-behind-hostile-masterpiece|title =Pantera's 'Vulgar Display of Power': The Epic Story Behind a Hostile Masterpiece|website =Revolver|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/dimebag-darrell/6363754/rob-halford-on-his-close-friendship-with-dimebag-darrell-ive-got|title =Rob Halford on His Close Friendship With 'Dimebag' Darrell: 'I've Got Wonderful Memories'|website =Billboard|first =Dan|last =Epstein|date =December 8, 2014}}</ref> Abbott recorded the song \"Caged in a Rage\", on which he performed lead vocals and guitar, under his own name. It was included on the [[Supercop (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 1996 film ''[[Police Story 3: Super Cop|Supercop]]''. Adam Greenberg of AllMusic said Abbott sounded \"oddly similar to [[Rob Zombie]]\" on \"Caged in a Rage\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allmusic.com/album/supercop-mw0000072482|title =Supercop - Original Soundtrack|website =AllMusic|first =Adam|last =Greenberg}}</ref>\n\nAbbott provided guest guitar solos for [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] on several occasions: \"King Size\" and \"Riding Shotgun\" from ''[[Stomp 442]]'' (1995), \"Inside Out\" and \"Born Again Idiot\" from ''[[Volume 8: The Threat Is Real]]'' (1998), and \"Strap It On\" and \"Cadillac Rock Box\" from ''[[We've Come for You All]]'' (2003).{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} Anthrax's [[Scott Ian]] referred to Abbott as the \"sixth member\" of the band due to his frequent appearances.<ref name=revolvervdop/> Abbott also performed a guest solo on the title track of [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]]'s ''[[Voodoo (King Diamond album)|Voodoo]]'' (1998) and on \"Eyes of the South\" (2004) by Premenishen, a band that featured Abbott's cousins Heather Manly and April Adkisson on bass and guitar, respectively.{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} After Darrell's death, Vinnie granted [[Nickelback]] permission to use outtakes of Darrell's solos from the ''Vulgar Display of Power'' and ''Far Beyond Driven'' recordings on its tribute track \"[[Side of a Bullet]]\".{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} Darrell was a friend of Nickelback's [[Chad Kroeger]] and had provided a solo for Nickelback's cover of \"[[Saturday Night's Alright for Fighting]]\" on the soundtrack to the 2003 film ''[[Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle]]''.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=263}}\n\nDarrell and Vinnie performed shows as [[Gasoline (band)|Gasoline]] each New Year's Eve. Gasoline predominantly played covers of artists such as [[Ted Nugent]] and [[Pat Travers]], but also composed original songs such as \"Get Drunk Now\" and \"This Ain't a Beer Belly, It's a Gas Tank for My Love Machine\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=162}} Gasoline once served as a support act for [[Drowning Pool]].{{sfn|Daniels|2013|p=167}} In 2006, \"Country Western Transvestite Whore\", a song that Abbott recorded with local Dallas musician Throbbin' Donnie Rodd, was released. It features Abbott on lead guitar and vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.wprost.pl/muzyka/292115/zaginione-country-dimebaga.html|title =Zaginione Country Dimebaga|website =Wprost|author =Staff writer(s)|date =December 6, 2006|language =Polish}}</ref> Other works by Abbott that have been posthumously released include \"Dime's Blackout Society\" (2010) and ''The Hitz'' (2017), a five-track EP.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rhino.com/article/heavy-metal-monday-dimebag-darrell-the-hitz|title =Heavy Metal Monday: Dimebag Darrell, THE HITZ|publisher =Rhino Entertainment|author =Staff writer(s)|date =July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n{{Main|Columbus nightclub shooting}}\n\n[[File:Dimebag 001.jpg|thumb|A fan mourns outside the Alrosa Villa nightclub in Columbus, Ohio, where Abbott was murdered.]]\nOn December 8, 2004, Damageplan was performing at the Alrosa Villa nightclub in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. As the band played the first song of its setlist, Nathan Gale, a deranged fan, rushed onto the stage and shot Abbott multiple times with a [[Beretta 92FS]], a 9mm semi-automatic pistol.<ref>{{cite book|title =Power Chord: One Man's Ear Splitting Quest to Find His Guitar Heroes|first =Thomas Scott|last =McKenzie|publisher =HarperCollins|date =2012|page =12|isbn =9780062098986}}</ref> The band's head of security, Jeffrey \"Mayhem\" Thompson, then tackled Gale, but was fatally shot in the ensuing struggle. A fan, Nathan Bray, was also murdered as he attempted to aid Abbott and Thompson, as was Erin Halk, an employee of the venue who tried to disarm Gale while he was reloading. Three others were wounded before [[Columbus Division of Police|Columbus police officer]] James Niggemeyer entered the club and shot Gale once in the head with a 12-gauge [[Remington Model 870]], killing him.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/behind-the-murder-of-dimebag-darrell-233541/|title =Behind the Murder of \u2018Dimebag\u2019 Darrell|website =Rolling Stone|first =Peter|last =Wilkinson|date =December 30, 2004}}</ref>\n\nAbbott was pronounced dead at the scene, aged 38. Thousands of fans attended his public memorial, and the guest list included artists such as [[Eddie Van Halen]], [[Zakk Wylde]], [[Corey Taylor]], [[Jerry Cantrell]] and [[Dino Cazares]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title =A Raucous Farewell to the Cowboy From Hell|first =Zac|last =Crain|magazine =Spin|date =March 2005|volume =21|issue =3|pages =20\u201321|publisher =SPIN Media LLC}}</ref> Abbott was buried alongside his mother Carolyn at the Moore Memorial Gardens cemetery in Arlington, Texas. [[Gene Simmons]] donated a [[Kiss Kasket]] for the burial, and Eddie Van Halen donated his original black-and-yellow-striped 1979 [[Charvel]] \"Bumblebee\" guitar, which was featured on the back cover of ''[[Van Halen II]]'', to be included in the casket.{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} A few weeks prior to his death, Abbott had met Van Halen and asked him for a replica of the Bumblebee. Van Halen said at the funeral: \"Dime was an original and only an original deserves the original.\"<ref name=billboardrita/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarplayer.com/players/dimebag-darrell-buried-with-one-of-rocks-most-iconic-guitars|title =Dimebag Darrell Buried With One of Rock's Most Iconic Guitars|first =Jennifer|last =Bergeron|website =Guitar Player|date =December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter Vinnie Paul's death in 2018, he was buried next to Carolyn and Darrell, also in a Kiss Kasket.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.stereogum.com/2003980/panteras-vinnie-paul-will-be-buried-in-a-free-kiss-casket-like-his-brother-dimebag-darrell/news/|title =Pantera\u2019s Vinnie Paul Will Be Buried In A Free KISS Casket Like His Brother Dimebag Darrell|website =Stereogum|first =Peter|last =Helman|date =June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/vinnie-paul-to-be-buried-in-kiss-casket/|title =Report: Vinnie Paul to Be Buried in KISS Casket|website =Loudwire|first =Tyler|last =Sharp|date =June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nOriginally a [[glam metal]] musician, Abbott distanced himself from the subgenre by the late 1980s, and was a driving force behind the development of [[groove metal]] in the 1990s.<ref name=louderfeature/>\n\n===Influences===\n\nAlthough his father was a country music producer and songwriter, Abbott's primary musical influences were [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] acts such as [[Black Sabbath]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] and [[Van Halen]].{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}} [[Ace Frehley]] of Kiss inspired him to play guitar.<ref name=gw94>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/gw-archive/dimebag-darrell-discusses-his-roots-gear-and-pantera-1994-guitar-world-interview|title =Dimebag Darrell Discusses His Roots, Gear and Pantera in 1994 Guitar World Interview|website =Guitar World|first =Brad|last =Tolinski|date =November 1, 2011}}</ref> He was a member of the [[Kiss Army]] and had a portrait of Frehley tattooed on his chest in 1992. While at a photo shoot for the August 1993 issue of ''[[Guitar World]]'' along with Frehley, Abbott asked Frehley to sign an autograph near the tattoo. Abbott then had the signature tattooed.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=105}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/dimebag-darrell-rock-soldiers|title =Dimebag Darrell: Rock Soldiers|website =Guitar World|first =Jeff|last =Kitts|date =December 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nNo musician other than Frehley exerted more of an influence on Abbott than Eddie Van Halen.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=217}} Abbott stated that his background mirrored Van Halen's as both he and Van Halen were younger brothers who first played drums before moving on to the guitar due to competition from their elder brothers on drums. Another influence was [[Randy Rhoads]]. Abbott said in 1994: \"To me, Eddie Van Halen was heavy rock and roll, but Randy was heavy metal.\"<ref name=gw94/> He discovered [[double tracking]] leads through Rhoads.<ref name=gw94/> In numerous interviews, Abbott credited [[Tony Iommi]] of Black Sabbath for inspiring his guitar riffs.{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}} Abbott also said [[Def Leppard]]'s original guitarist [[Pete Willis]] \"was a great player. I was inspired by him because I was a small young dude and he was a small young dude, too\u2014and he was out there kickin' ass. He made me want to get out there and play.\"<ref name=gw93>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/magazine/prime-cuts-dimebag-darrell-chooses-his-12-favorite-tunes-1993-guitar-world-feature|title =Pantera's Dimebag Darrell Chooses His 12 Favorite Songs in 1993 Guitar World Interview|website =Guitar World|first =Jeff|last =Kitts|date =August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbbott was a fan of the [[Southern rock]] band [[ZZ Top]],<ref name=louderfeature/> and he was influenced by the band's guitarist and lead singer [[Billy Gibbons]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}} He said in 1993: \"I'm not a super [[blues]] player, but I was exposed to the [[Texas blues]] sound while I was growing up, and that definitely rubbed off on me.\"<ref name=gw93/> Abbott was also influenced by contemporary metal guitarists such as [[Kerry King]] of [[Slayer]], [[James Hetfield]] of [[Metallica]], and [[Zakk Wylde]] of [[List of Ozzy Osbourne band members|Ozzy Osbourne]] and [[Black Label Society]].{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}}\n\n===Technique===\n\nAbbott did not receive formal guitar lessons. He stated in a 1994 ''Guitar World'' interview that he once received \"a guitar lesson off this cat. He wrote down some weird [[Scale (music)|scale]] and tried to explain how it worked. After we finished he said, 'Now go on home, practice that scale, and show me how well you can play it next week.' So I took it home, played around with it for a few minutes and said, 'Fuck this, I just want to jam.' I respect people that can read [[tablature]] and all that shit, but I just don't even have the patience to read the newspaper.\"<ref name=gw94/>\n\nUnlike many other heavy metal guitarists, Abbott made extensive use of the [[major third]] in his riffs and leads, which added [[Consonance and dissonance|dissonance]] to minor key [[Tonality|tonalities]]. This was a Van Halen-inspired technique, as was his employment of symmetrical [[Fingering (music)|fingerings]]. Although Abbott had exceptional [[Guitar picking|picking]] ability, he favored [[legato]] phrasing. His love of legato gave his playing a fluid quality, and his powerful left hand technique enabled the implementation of the symmetrical patterns in his lead [[Lick (music)|licks]].<ref name=gw10p1>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/lessons/guitar-strength-10-commandments-playing-guitar-style-dimebag-darrell-part-1|title =10 Commandments of Playing Guitar in the Style of Pantera's Dimebag Darrell, Part 1|website =Guitar World|first =Scott|last =Marano|date =August 16, 2018}}</ref> Abbott avoided using scales and [[Mode (music)|modes]] in traditional fashions, and often used passing tones between [[Whole tone scale|scalar tones]] to add tension. These [[Chromatic scale|chromatic]] licks made up much of his playing.<ref name=gw10p2/> Regardless of the note or chord, Abbott played with a \"Texas style\", meaning a variety of techniques such as [[Slide guitar|sliding]], [[String bending|bending]], [[palm muting]], and use of the [[whammy bar]] and [[effects pedal]] to produce an idiosyncratic\nsound.<ref name=gw10p2/>  \n\nOne of the most distinctive features of Abbott's guitar playing was his use of [[String harmonic|harmonics]] to create a squealing sound,<ref name=gw10p1/> which he picked up from Gibbons.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}} Unsatisfied with standard techniques, Abbott often used [[Dyad (music)|dyads]] in place of traditional [[power chords]]. This added texture to his riffs and, when played with [[Distortion (music)|distortion]], created a tense sound.<ref name=gw10p1/> Abbott experimented with [[Guitar tunings#Alternative|alternate tunings]] throughout his career. Early on, his guitar was tuned down more than a quarter step, similar to ''[[Van Halen I]]'' and ''[[Van Halen II]]'' tuning. On ''Cowboys From Hell'' (1990), he utilized [[Guitar tunings#Dropped tunings|drop D tuning]], and beginning with ''Vulgar Display of Power'' (1992) he tuned his guitar down a whole step, which became his main tuning by the release of ''Reinventing the Steel'' (2000). He also used drop D down one step, down 1 \u00bd steps and drop D down 1 \u00bd steps tunings. Down 1 \u00bd steps tuning was prevalent on ''The Great Southern Trendkill'' (1996) and was Abbott's main tuning on ''New Found Power'' (2004).{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}}<ref name=gw10p2>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/lessons/guitar-strength-10-commandments-playing-guitar-style-dimebag-darrell-part-2|title =10 Commandments of Playing Guitar in the Style of Dimebag Darrell, Part 2|website =Guitar World|first =Scott|last =Marano|date =August 16, 2018}}</ref>  \n\nThree of Abbott's solos were ranked in ''Guitar World''{{'}}s \"100 Greatest Guitar Solos of All Time\": \"[[Walk (Pantera song)|Walk]]\" at No. 57;<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/features/100-greatest-guitar-solos-51-100|title =100 Greatest Guitar Solos: 51-100|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =October 30, 2008}}</ref> \"[[Cemetery Gates]]\" at No. 35;<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/lessons/100-greatest-guitar-solos-no-35-cemetery-gates-dimebag-darrell|title =100 Greatest Guitar Solos: No. 35 \"Cemetery Gates\" (Dimebag Darrell)|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =October 28, 2008}}</ref> and \"[[Floods (Pantera song)|Floods]]\" at No. 19.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/gw-archive/100-greatest-guitar-solos-no-19-floods-dimebag-darrell|title =100 Greatest Guitar Solos: No. 19 \"Floods\" (Dimebag Darrell)|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =December 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/gw-archive/50-greatest-guitar-solos|title =50 Greatest Guitar Solos|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =January 29, 2009}}</ref> Despite his virtuosity, Abbott said that while \"jerking off all over the [[Neck (music)|neck]]\", as he described, was suited to competing in guitar contests, it often did not benefit a song's composition. \"Slaughtered\" from ''Far Beyond Driven'' originally had a slow, melodic solo, but Abbott removed it after noting that it disrupted the song's momentum.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}}\n\n==Equipment==\n[[File:Dean Guitar.jpg|thumb|One of Abbott's signature [[headstock]]s|upright=0.75]]\n\nIn 1982, Abbott won a maroon [[Dean ML]] at a guitar contest in Dallas.<ref name=australianguitar>{{cite magazine|url =https://www.pressreader.com/australia/australian-guitar/20140601/281921656124411|title =The Dean from Hell|magazine =Australian Guitar|date =June 2014}}</ref><ref name=dean1>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/dimebag-s-dean-of-destiny-1|title =Dimebag's Dean of Destiny, Part 1|website =Premier Guitar|first =Chris|last =Kies|date =August 20, 2008}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=57}} Unbeknownst to Abbott, his father had bought him a sunburst ML shortly before the contest. Nearing driving age and seeking to purchase a [[Pontiac Firebird]], Abbott attempted to sell the maroon ML to his friend Buddy Blaze, a [[luthier]] and musician. Blaze felt that a guitar won as a prize should stay with its owner and refused to buy it.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=58}} Abbott instead sold the guitar to one of Blaze's bandmates. Blaze negotiated with his bandmate, and took possession of the ML in exchange for a [[Kramer Pacer]]. Blaze then replaced the standard ML hardware: he installed a custom [[Floyd Rose]] vibrato bridge and [[Bill Lawrence (guitar maker)|Bill Lawrence]] L-500XL [[pickup (music technology)|pickups]], and moved the stock [[DiMarzio]] pickup to the neck.\nHe also repainted the guitar, from its original maroon to blue-and-black with a lightning bolt finish.<ref name=australianguitar/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=58}}<ref name=dean2>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/dimebag-s-dean-of-destiny-1?page=2|title =Dimebag's Dean of Destiny, Part 2|website =Premier Guitar|first =Chris|last =Kies|date =August 20, 2008}}</ref> Blaze returned the ML to Abbott in 1987, who was initially unaware that it was the same guitar he won as a prize.<ref name=dean3>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/dimebag-s-dean-of-destiny-1?page=3|title =Dimebag's Dean of Destiny, Part 3|website =Premier Guitar|first =Chris|last =Kies|date =August 20, 2008}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=59}} It subsequently became Abbott's signature guitar and was later dubbed the \"Dean from Hell\".<ref name=australianguitar/>\n\nAfter the release of ''Cowboys from Hell'', Abbott signed an endorsement deal with [[Dean Guitars]].<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Dean went out of business in 1994 and Abbott then signed a ten-year contract with [[Washburn Guitars]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=152}} With Washburn, he played various signature guitars modeled after the ML, such as the Dime 333, Culprit and Stealth.<ref name=halleonard>{{cite book|title =100 Great Guitarists and the Gear That Made Them Famous|first =Dave|last =Rubin|publisher =Hal Leonard Corporation|date =2017|isbn =9781540019363|pages =86\u201387}}</ref> When his contract with Washburn expired in 2004, he became the main endorsee of the re-opened Dean.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=222}} Abbott's murder came shortly before the Dean contract was set to begin.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.bizjournals.com/tampabay/stories/2004/12/06/daily38.html|title =Despite shooting, Dean Guitars to proceed with 'Dimebag' model|website =Tampa Bay Business Journal|first =Carl|last =Cronan|date =December 10, 2004}}</ref> Abbott had designed the [[Dean Razorback]] and [[Dean Razorback V|Razorback V]] in the months prior to his death.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/dimebag-week-a-complete-guide-to-dimebag-darrell-signature-gear-611282|title =A complete guide to Dimebag Darrell signature gear|website =MusicRadar|first =Stuart|last =Williams|date =December 4, 2014}}</ref> Dean also posthumously released replicas of the Dean from Hell.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/12/dean-guitars-dimebag-darrell-win-lawsuit-dean-from-hell-guitar/|title =Dimebag Darrell estate and Dean Guitars win lawsuit over \u201cDean From Hell\u201d guitar|website =Consequence of Sound|first =Robert|last =Ham|date =December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAbbott was praised for his instrumental [[musical tone|tone]] and was included in ''Guitar Player''{{'}}s list of \"The 50 Greatest Tones of All Time\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Blackett |first=Matt |title=The 50 Greatest Tones of All Time |journal=Guitar Player |volume=38 |issue=10 |pages=44\u201366 |publisher= |date=October 2004 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarplayer.com/players/50-kings-of-tone-the-secrets-behind-their-sounds-video|title =50 Kings of Tone: The Secrets Behind Their Sounds|website =Guitar Player|first =Matt|last =Blackett|date =April 2, 2015}}</ref> Abbott used [[Guitar amplifier#Solid-state|solid-state]] [[Randall Amplifiers|Randall]] amplifiers for most of his career; he remarked in the [[liner notes]] for ''Cowboys from Hell'': \"Gotta have that Randall Crunch!\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=225}} He had won his first Randall amplifier in a guitar contest; he said in a 1993 interview it \"was a little nasty sounding, a little gritty, but I liked it. I knew that with time I could make it my own sound, and it came around.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/dimebag-darrell-home-deranged|title =Dimebag Darrell: Home of Deranged|website =Guitar World|first =Glenn|last =Thrush|date =December 8, 2009}}</ref> Abbott released a signature amplifier, the Randall Warhead, in 1999. The goal was to replicate the sound of his own rig: a Randall RG-100 head, Furman PQ-3 [[parametric equalizer]], [[MXR]] six-band [[graphic equalizer]] and MXR 126 [[flanger]].<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> He set his Furman EQ to boost the highs and lows while scooping the mids,<ref name=gw10p2/> and he used both the Furman EQ and MXR EQ to increase the gain to the Randall's front end.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott also used a [[Digitech whammy pedal]], a [[Korg]] DT-7 [[chromatic tuner]] and a Rocktron Hush IIC [[noise gate]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.seymourduncan.com/blog/backstage-pass/dimebag-darrell-of-pantera|title =Dimebag Darrell: Reinventing the Steel with the SH-13 Dimebucker|publisher =Seymour Duncan|first =Lisa|last =Sharken|date =February 9, 2007}}</ref> The noise gate allowed him to control the feedback associated with high levels of gain, and to create the distinctive holes of silence in his playing.<ref name=gw10p2/> \n\nWhen Abbott's endorsement deal with Washburn ended, his deal with Randall also ended, as Randall and Washburn both were subsidiaries of the [[U.S. Music Corporation]]. Abbott subsequently formed a partnership with Krank Amplifiers, a relatively small supplier.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=225}} He used the Krank Revolution, a [[tube amplifier]].<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott also invested in the company and designed an amplifier named the Krankenstein;{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=226}} he approved the final revision of the Krankenstein just days before his murder.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott helped design many other products. With [[Dunlop Manufacturing]], he designed the Dimebag Cry Baby from Hell, a [[wah-wah pedal]], and the Dime Distortion, a [[distortion pedal]]. He also designed a signature pickup with [[Seymour Duncan]] titled the Dimebucker, which was based on the Bill Lawrence pickups that he used in most of his guitars. [[Dean Zelinsky]] of Dean said in 2010 that Abbott's death was a \"bigger loss than we'll ever know. ...  I'm very proud of the work I did with him, but who knows what he would have accomplished if he was still with us.\"<ref name=reinventingsqueal/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAbbott grew up in the same neighborhood as his long-time partner Rita Haney, whom he first met at the age of eight.<ref name=billboardrita>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/dimebag-darrell/6363758/dimebag-darrells-longtime-partner-rita-haney-hed-actually-be|title ='Dimebag' Darrell's Longtime Partner Rita Haney: 'He'd Actually Be Surprised at How Many People He Touched'|website =Billboard|first =Dan|last =Epstein|date =December 8, 2014}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=41}} They began dating in 1984.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=42}} The couple never married. Haney said in a 2006 interview: \"We didn't believe in the marriage thing. ... Why have someone you don't know tell you it's OK to be with someone you do know? We didn't need the middleman! We had a one-on-one with the man upstairs ourselves.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=125}} \n\nIn 1995, Abbott bought a house with Haney in [[Dalworthington Gardens, Texas]], a short distance from his hometown Arlington.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=124}} Abbott kept a pet [[goat]] on the residence, and dyed its goatee like his own.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=125}} He was remembered by his neighbors as approachable. One neighbor who often walked dogs with Abbott said he \"was a hick with an attitude, and I say that respectfully. We'd talk conservative politics. He was a big, big supporter of [[George W. Bush|George Bush]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Pantera-fans-pay-their-respects-to-slain-rocker-1568482.php|title =Pantera fans pay their respects to slain rocker|website =Houston Chronicle|first =Thomas|last =Korosec|date =December 10, 2004}}</ref>\n\nDarrell and Vinnie opened the Clubhouse, an all-nude [[strip club]] in north-west Dallas, in 1996. Vinnie's original idea was a rock-and-roll-themed golf course, with \"a strip club at the nineteenth hole\", but the construction of a golf course was prohibitively expensive.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=160}}<ref name=texasmonthly>{{cite web|url =https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/bare-assets/|title =Bare Assets|website =Texas Monthly|first =Andy|last =Langer|date =May 2000}}</ref> Under the Abbott brothers' ownership, the Clubhouse was patronized by many artists who toured in the area, such as Black Sabbath, Kiss and Metallica, as well as [[NASCAR]] drivers, professional golfers,<ref name=texasmonthly/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=161}} and members of the [[Dallas Cowboys]] and the [[Dallas Stars]] (whose [[fight song]], \"[[Dallas Stars#Traditions|Puck Off]]\", was written and produced by Pantera).<ref name=texasmonthly/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=163}} After the Dallas Stars won the [[1999 Stanley Cup Finals]], the Abbott brothers hosted a party for the team at Vinnie's house. Vinnie later stated that the [[Stanley Cup]] was dented during the party after [[Guy Carbonneau]] threw it out of a window into a swimming pool, but barely missed the pool and hit the edge.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.hookedonhockeymagazine.com/dallas-stars-and-the-mystery-dent-in-the-stanley-cup/|title =The Dallas Stars and the Mystery Dent in the Stanley Cup|first =Brendon|last =Carlton|website =Hooked on Hockey|date =December 25, 2013}}</ref><ref name=lwsc>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/did-vinnie-paul-dent-stanley-cup/|title =That Time Vinnie Paul Dented the Stanley Cup|website =Loudwire|first =Michael|last =Christopher|date =June 25, 2018}}</ref> The brothers also performed on a [[Float (parade)|float]] during the celebration of the Stars' victory.<ref name=lwsc/>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{See also|Columbus nightclub shooting#Tributes}}\n\nOn May 17, 2007, Abbott was posthumously inducted into [[Hollywood's RockWalk]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/news/dimebag-darrell-gets-rockwalk-induction|title =Dimebag Darrell Gets Rockwalk Induction|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =April 23, 2007}}</ref> Ace Frehley was among the attendees at the induction ceremony, where he spoke in honor of Abbott.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://bravewords.com/news/ace-frehley-attends-dimebag-darrells-rockwalk-induction-photo-available|title =Ace Frehley Attends Dimebag Darrell's RockWalk induction|website =Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles|author =Staff writer(s)|date =May 18, 2007}}</ref> Frehley also dedicated his 2009 album ''[[Anomaly (Ace Frehley album)|Anomaly]]'' to Abbott, as well as former Kiss drummer [[Eric Carr]].<ref>{{cite web|url =http://bravewords.com/news/ace-frehley-eddie-trunk-reviews-anomaly|title =ACE FREHLEY - Eddie Trunk Reviews Anomaly|author =Staff writer(s)|website =Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles|date =September 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Abbott was ranked as the most influential metal guitarist of the past 25 years by [[VH1]]. Doc Coyle of [[God Forbid]] stated: \"[Abbott's] sparse, low-end, bluesy chug was the blueprint for post-thrash, [[nu-metal]], and [[metalcore]] in the subsequent years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170707082614/http://www.vh1.com/news/3639/most-influential-metal-guitarists-of-the-modern-era/|title =20 Most Influential Metal Guitarists Of The Modern Era|publisher =VH1|first =Doc|last =Coyle|date =April 10, 2015}}</ref> Also in 2015, Abbott placed at No. 5 on [[Gibson]]'s list of \"The Top 10 Metal Guitarists of All Time\". Anne Erickson said Abbott \"proved metal guitar could shred wildly, but still groove. ... He'll always be remembered as one of the most significant engineers of modern metal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://web.archive.org/web/20180818084419/http://www.gibson.com:80/News-Lifestyle/Features/en-us/shred-stars-0803-2011.aspx|title =Top 10 Metal Guitarists of All Time|publisher =Gibson|first =Anne|last =Erickson|date =September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked Abbott at No. 92 on its list of \"The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" in 2011, and described him as \"one of modern metal's key figures\". [[Geezer Butler]] of Black Sabbath said Abbott was \"one of the greatest musicians to grace our world\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/100-greatest-guitarists-153675/dimebag-darrell-41534/|title =100 Greatest Guitarists: Dimebag Darrell|website =Rolling Stone|first =Patrick|last =Doyle|date =2011}}</ref> In 2018, Abbott ranked at No. 19 on ''[[Metal Hammer|Louder]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 50 Greatest Guitarists Of All Time\". [[Sebastian Bach]] of [[Skid Row (American band)|Skid Row]] commented that Abbott \"reinvented heavy metal guitar\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-50-greatest-guitarists-of-all-time/4|title =The 50 Greatest Guitarists Of All Time|website =Louder|author =Staff writer(s)|date =September 29, 2018}}</ref> Jamie Humphries of ''[[Premier Guitar]]'' remarked in 2014: \"If there were ever a band and guitarist to credit for reinventing post-Metallica metal, it would have to be Pantera and the late Dimebag Darrell.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/21060-electric-etudes-dimebag-darrell|title =Electric Etudes: \u201cDimebag\u201d Darrell|website =Premier Guitar|first =Jamie|last =Humphries|date =June 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAbbott also ranked at No. 9 in a 2012 ''[[Guitar World]]'' readers' poll of \"The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\",<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/features/readers-poll-results-100-greatest-guitarists-all-time|title =Readers Poll Results: The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =October 10, 2012}}</ref> and was named the \"Greatest Metal Guitarist\" by ''[[Loudwire]]'' in 2013 after winning a reader-voted [[Bracket (tournament)|tournament bracket]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/dimebag-darrell-abbott-wins-loudwire-greatest-metal-guitarist-tournament/|title ='Dimebag' Darrell Abbott Declared Greatest Metal Guitarist|website =Loudwire|first =Spencer|last =Kaufman|date =August 13, 2013}}</ref> [[Jonathan Davis]] of [[Korn]] said in a 2014 interview with ''Loudwire'' that Abbott is \"one of the greatest guitar players ever. I mean if there was no Dimebag Darrell, there would be no Korn.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/remembering-dimebag-darrell-jonathan-davis-korn/|title =Remembering Dimebag Darrell: Korn's Jonathan Davis|first =Chad|last =Childers|website =Loudwire|date =December 3, 2014}}</ref> [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] stated that Abbott \"had a great tone and a great original style ... He was one of the best new guitar players that came out over a long period of time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/remembering-dimebag-darrell-slash/|title =Remembering Dimebag Darrell: Slash Praises Dime's Abilities|first =Graham|last =Hartmann|website =Loudwire|date =November 24, 2014}}</ref> [[Max Cavalera]] described Abbott as \"very talented, an amazing musician and a humble and cool guy \u2013 not a rock star asshole\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/remembering-dimebag-darrell-soulfly-max-cavalera/|title =Remembering Dimebag Darrell: Soulfly's Max Cavalera|first =Chad|last =Childers|website =Loudwire|date =December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA concert in memory of Abbott titled Dimebash has been held annually since 2010. All of the concert's proceeds go towards the [[Ronnie James Dio]] Stand Up and Shout Cancer Fund.<ref name=dimebash2010>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/news/dimebash-2010-all-star-concert-benefit-stand-and-shout-cancer-fund|title =Dimebash 2010: All-Star Concert to Benefit 'Stand Up and Shout Cancer Fund'|website =Guitar World|author =Editors|date =October 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/second-annual-dimebash-dimebag-darrell-december-14/|title =Second Annual 'DimeBash' Tribute to Dimebag Darrell Set for December 14|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =November 29, 2011}}</ref> Performers at Dimebash events have included artists such as [[Dave Grohl]],<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/corey-taylor-dave-grohl-walk-dimebash-2019/|title =Corey Taylor, Dave Grohl + More Cover 'Walk' at Dimebash 2019|website =Loudwire|first =Chad|last =Childers|date =January 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Kerry King]], [[Robb Flynn]],<ref name=dimebash2010/> [[Tom Morello]], and [[Serj Tankian]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/dimebash-2011-remembering-dimebag-darrell-21565/sebastian-bach-4-77628/|title =Dimebash 2011: Remembering Dimebag Darrell|website =Rolling Stone|author =Staff writer(s)|date =December 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Dimebag Darrell performances}}\n\n'''Pantera'''\n* ''[[Metal Magic]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Projects in the Jungle]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[I Am the Night (album)|I Am the Night]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Power Metal (album)|Power Metal]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Cowboys from Hell]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Vulgar Display of Power]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Far Beyond Driven]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Great Southern Trendkill]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Reinventing the Steel]]'' (2000)\n\n'''Damageplan'''\n*''[[New Found Power]]'' (2004)\n\n'''Rebel Meets Rebel'''\n*''[[Rebel Meets Rebel]]'' (2006)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=Q_DIQZsdsQcC|title =Black Tooth Grin: The High Life, Good Times, and Tragic End of \"Dimebag\" Darrell Abbott|first =Zac|last =Crain|publisher =Hachette Books|date =2009|isbn =9780786748020}}\n* {{citation|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=DL3I9qQWdeAC|title =Guitar Gods: The 25 Players who Made Rock History|first =Bob|last =Gulla|publisher =ABC-CLIO|date =2009|isbn =9780313358067}}\n* {{citation|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=ttGGDwAAQBAJ|title =Reinventing Metal: The True Story of Pantera and the Tragically Short Life of Dimebag Darrell|first =Neil|last =Daniels|publisher =Rowman & Littlefield|date =2013|isbn =9781480362734}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dimebag Darrell}}\n\n* {{allmusic|id=dimebag-darrell-mn0000262251}}\n* {{IMDB name|id=0201602}}\n* {{Findagrave|10061348}}\n\n{{Damageplan}}\n{{Pantera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darrell, Dimebag}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Burials in Texas]]\n[[Category:Damageplan members]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Murdered American musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Musicians who died on stage]]\n[[Category:Pantera members]]\n[[Category:People from Arlington, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Ennis, Texas]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Dimebag|the episode of The Americans|Dimebag (The Americans)}}\n{{Short description|American musician and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Dimebag Darrell\n| image            = Dimebag.jpg\n| caption          = Abbott in June 2004\n| birth_name       = Darrell Lance Abbott\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1966|8|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Ennis, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2004|12|8|1966|8|20}}\n| death_place      = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_cause      = [[Gunshot wounds]]\n| resting_place    = Moore Memorial Gardens, [[Arlington, Texas]]\n| other_names      = {{ublist|Diamond Darrell (1981\u201393)|Dimebag Darrell (1994 on)}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 1981\u20132004\n| spouse           = \n| partner          = Rita Haney (1984\u20132004)\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed            = yes\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Groove metal]]|[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]|[[Southern metal]]|[[thrash metal]]|[[glam metal]] (early)}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Guitar|vocals}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Atco Records|Atco]]|[[Big Vin Records|Big Vin]]|[[East West Records|East West]]|[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]|Metal Magic}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Pantera]]|[[Damageplan]]|[[David Allan Coe]]|[[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]]|[[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]]|[[Gasoline (band)|Gasoline]]}}\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|dimebagdarrell.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Darrell Lance Abbott''' (August 20, 1966 \u2013 December 8, 2004), best known by his stage name '''Dimebag Darrell''', was an American musician and songwriter. He was the [[guitarist]] of the [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands [[Pantera]] and [[Damageplan]], both of which he co-founded alongside his brother [[Vinnie Paul]]. As one of the driving forces behind the development of [[groove metal]], he is considered among the most influential guitarists in heavy metal history.\n\nA son of [[country music]] producer [[Jerry Abbott]], Abbott began playing guitar at age 12, and Pantera released its debut album, ''[[Metal Magic]]'' (1983), when he was 16. Originally a [[glam metal]] musician, Abbott went by the stage name '''Diamond Darrell''' at the time. Two further albums in the glam metal style followed in [[Projects in the Jungle|1984]] and [[I Am the Night (album)|1985]], before original vocalist [[Terry Glaze]] was replaced by [[Phil Anselmo]] in 1986 and ''[[Power Metal (album)|Power Metal]]'' (1988) was released. The band's major-label debut, ''[[Cowboys from Hell]]'' (1990), introduced a groove metal sound to which Abbott's guitar playing was central. This sound was refined on ''[[Vulgar Display of Power]]'' (1992), and the group's third major-label record, ''[[Far Beyond Driven]]'', debuted at No. 1 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'' in 1994.  \n\nTensions within Pantera reduced its output after the release of ''[[The Great Southern Trendkill]]'' in 1996, and ''[[Reinventing the Steel]]'' (2000) was the band's final studio album before its acrimonious separation in 2003. Abbott subsequently formed Damageplan with his brother Vinnie Paul and released ''[[New Found Power]]'', the band's debut and only album, in 2004. Other works by Abbott included a collaboration with [[David Allan Coe]] titled ''[[Rebel Meets Rebel]]'' (2006) and numerous guest [[guitar solo]]s for bands such as [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]]. Abbott was [[Columbus nightclub shooting|shot and killed]] by a deranged fan on December 8, 2004, while on stage with Damageplan at the Alrosa Villa nightclub in Columbus, Ohio. Three others were murdered in the shooting before the perpetrator was killed by police. \n\nAbbott was ranked at No. 92 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" in 2011, and No. 19 on ''[[Metal Hammer|Louder]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 50 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" in 2018. He placed at No. 5 on [[Gibson]]'s list of \"The Top 10 Metal Guitarists of All Time\" in 2015, and the same year was ranked as the most influential metal guitarist of the past 25 years by [[VH1]].\n\n==Childhood==\n\nDarrell Lance Abbott was born in [[Ennis, Texas]],{{sfn|Daniels|2013|p=2}} on August 20, 1966, the second son to Carolyn and [[Jerry Abbott]], a [[country music]] producer.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=3}} His elder brother [[Vinnie Paul]] was born on March 11, 1964. Abbott's parents divorced in 1979, after seventeen years of marriage,{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=4}} but his family life remained happy.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=16}} The brothers lived with their mother Carolyn, in a [[ranch-style house]] on Monterrey Street in [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=8}} Carolyn was supportive of her sons' musical endeavors.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=5}}\n\nAbbott took up the guitar when he was twelve. His first guitar was a [[Gibson Les Paul|Les Paul]]-style [[Hondo (guitar company)|Hondo]], which he received along with a [[Pignose]] amplifier on his twelfth birthday.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=10}} Influenced by [[Black Sabbath]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] and [[Van Halen]],{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=11}} he would initially spend time in his room standing in front of a mirror holding the guitar while wearing [[Ace Frehley]]-style makeup, though he was unable to play the instrument at the time.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=8}}<ref name=vinnie2016>{{cite web|url =https://www.loudersound.com/features/he-was-the-wild-life-of-the-party-vinnie-paul-remembers-dimebag-darrell|title ='He was the wild life of the party' - Vinnie Paul remembers Dimebag Darrell|website =Louder|first =Jerry|last =Ewing|date =December 8, 2016}}</ref> Jerry learned Kiss songs on guitar in order to teach Darrell how to play them.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=11}} Darrell also learned from country musicians who recorded at Jerry's studio, such as [[Bugs Henderson]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=12}}\n\nVinnie had begun playing the drums before Darrell received his first guitar. Darrell had previously tried to play the drums; Vinnie later said: \"I just got better than him and wouldn't let him play them anymore.\"<ref name=vinnie2016/> The Abbott brothers' first [[jam session]] consisted of six hours of \"[[Smoke on the Water]]\".<ref name=vinnie2016/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=12}} They took inspiration from [[Alex Van Halen|Alex]] and [[Eddie Van Halen]],{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=217}} and Vinnie said in a 2016 interview that he and Darrell were \"inseparable\" after they began playing music together.<ref name=vinnie2016/>\n\nAt age 14, Abbott entered a guitar contest at the Agora Ballroom in [[Dallas]], in which [[Dean Zelinsky]], founder of [[Dean Guitars]], was one of the judges.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott's mother accompanied him to the club because he was not old enough to enter on his own.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=26}} He won the competition; Zelinsky recalled that \"[Abbott] blew everyone away.\"<ref name=reinventingsqueal>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/features/dimebag-darrell-reinventing-squeal|title =Dimebag Darrell: Reinventing the Squeal|website =Guitar World|first =Chris|last =Gill|date =January 2010}}</ref> Abbott won many other guitar contests in the area, and was eventually asked not to compete and instead judge the competitions so others could win.<ref name=australianguitar/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=111}}\n\n==Music career==\n===Pantera===\n{{Further|Pantera}}\n====Early glam metal years====\n\n[[Pantera]] was formed in 1981. Vinnie was asked to join a band alongside his high school classmates [[Terry Glaze]] (guitar), Tommy Bradford (bass) and Donny Hart (vocals). Vinnie accepted the invitation, but on the condition that Darrell would also join the band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=13}} Glaze later recalled that they were unsure about this request, as Darrell \"wasn't very good\" and, two years their junior, \"was a little skinny, scrawny dude\",{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=13}} but they ultimately agreed. In 1989, Darrell made the same request when [[Dave Mustaine]] asked him to join [[Megadeth]]. As Mustaine had already recruited drummer [[Nick Menza]] and would not hire Vinnie, Darrell decided to stay with Pantera.<ref name=\"Sharpe-Young\">{{cite book|last =Sharpe-Young|first =Garry|title =New Wave of American Heavy Metal|date =November 2005|publisher =Zonda Books|location =New Zealand|page =232|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=uIIf03bGyAAC}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|pp=14, 71}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/dimebag-darrell/6363759/dave-mustaine-on-dimebag-darrell-he-would-want-us-to-remember-him|title =Dave Mustaine on 'Dimebag' Darrell: 'He Would Want Us to Remember Him by Celebrating and Not Mourn'|website =Billboard|first =Dan|last =Epstein|date =December 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine =Guitar World|date =October 2004|url =https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/dave_mustaine_kerry_king_hates_my_guts.html|title =Dave Mustaine: Kerry King Hates My Guts|quote =That's true. That was around 1989. I had just hired Nick [Menza, drums] and Pantera were still playing around Texas. I asked Darrell if he was interested and he says to me [assumes southern accent], 'Yeah, man, but my brother's gotta come, too.' And I said, 'What is he, a roadie?' I told him I already had a drummer, and he said, 'Ah, then fuck it. Good luck, brother!'}}</ref>\n\nBy 1982, Hart left the band and was replaced by Glaze on vocals, while [[Rex Brown]] took Bradford's place as bassist.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=14}} Abbott originally shared lead guitar with Glaze, but soon took permanent status as lead guitarist. Glaze said: \"[Abbott] just morphed over a six-month period. ... When he came out, he could play, like, \"[[Eruption (instrumental)|Eruption]]\" and \"[[Crazy Train]]\".\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=16}} Abbott adopted the stage name \"Diamond Darrell\",{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=20}} in reference to the Kiss song \"[[Black Diamond (Kiss song)|Black Diamond]]\".{{sfn|Daniels|2013|p=32}}\n\nInspired by Kiss, Van Halen and Judas Priest, Pantera originally had a [[glam metal]] style and was image conscious: the members wore [[spandex]], makeup and hairspray when on stage.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=20}} The band signed to Metal Magic Records, which was created by \"Jerry Eld'n\", an alias of Abbott's father Jerry. Pantera released its first album, ''[[Metal Magic]]'', in 1983, when Abbott was 16.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=20}} A review in the November 1983 issue of Texas-based music magazine ''Buddy'' said Abbott's [[guitar solo|solos]] \"tend to be asymmetrical in that the old theory of musical thought consisting of statements alternating with appropriate responses is ignored and replaced by authoritative delivery of the player's own concept of what should happen\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=21}}\n\nPantera released ''[[Projects in the Jungle]]'' and ''[[I Am the Night (album)|I Am the Night]]'' in 1984 and 1985, respectively. Both albums followed on in the glam metal style, and were comparable to ''[[Shout at the Devil]]''-era [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]],{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=43}} though ''I Am the Night'' had a slightly heavier sound than previous releases.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=44}} Around this time, the Abbott brothers began listening to bands such as [[Metallica]] and [[Slayer]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=44}} Darrell was particularly taken by Metallica's ''[[Ride the Lightning]]'' (1984).{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=48}} Glaze was unhappy with the Abbott brothers' desire to move towards a heavier sound; he later said he \"didn't want to go that heavy. I didn't like it as well if the guitar was the main thing, like the Metallica songs.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=49}} This conflict, along with a contractual dispute, led to his departure in 1986.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=50}}\n\nGlaze was replaced by [[Phil Anselmo]] in late 1986.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=52}} This new lineup briefly signed with [[Gold Mountain Records]], but released ''[[Power Metal (album)|Power Metal]]'' (1988) on Metal Magic. Abbott said Gold Mountain \"wanted to change our style and make us sound like [[Bon Jovi]], which is not quite up our alley\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=53}} Anselmo did not write any of the lyrics for ''Power Metal'', and the band was still in the process of distancing themselves from glam metal,{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=54}} but the album evidenced a stylistic change.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=69}} A retrospective [[AllMusic]] album review by Bradley Torreano said Abbott's \"speedy riffs\" were one of the \"more charming elements\" of the band's sound.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allmusic.com/album/power-metal-mw0000858526|title =Power Metal - Pantera|website =AllMusic|first =Bradley|last =Torreano}}</ref> Brown said in a 1988 interview that \"Darrell has always been chunking those riffs out from the start. But now with Phil in the band we've got a chance to make those riffs fully happen instead of having some gay singer over the top of them!\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=54}}\n\n====Development of groove metal====\n\nAfter the release of ''Power Metal'', Pantera formed a relationship with Walter O'Brien and Andy Gould of [[Concrete Marketing|Concrete Management]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=69}} As Concrete managed other bands that were signed to [[Metal Blade Records]], Gould contacted [[Brian Slagel]] of Metal Blade and asked him to sign Pantera. The $75,000 requested for the production of a new album was too much for Slagel, who rejected the offer.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=70}} The Metal Blade rejection was one of many major-label rejections for the band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=71}} Pantera eventually attained a major-label deal with [[Atco Records]], after Atco's talent scout Mark Ross was impressed by one of the band's live performances.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=75}}\n\n''[[Cowboys from Hell]]'' was released on July 24, 1990. The album was produced by [[Terry Date]]; [[Max Norman]] was the original choice for producer but he opted to produce [[Lynch Mob]]'s ''[[Wicked Sensation]]'' instead. Date also served as producer for Pantera's next three albums.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=77}} ''Cowboys from Hell'' marked the development of what would become Pantera's familiar sound,<ref name=loudwire28/> to which Abbott's guitar playing was central.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=84}} Self-described as \"power groove\",<ref name=loudwire28>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-cowboys-from-hell-album-anniversary/|title =28 Years Ago: Pantera Find Their Voice With 'Cowboys From Hell'|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title =Music of the 1990s|first =Thomas|last =Harrison|publisher =ABC-CLIO|date =2011|isbn =9780313379437|page =101}}</ref> the album became a \"blueprint-defining\" work for [[groove metal]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/projects-in-the-jungle-mw0000909464 |title=Projects in the Jungle - Pantera |website =AllMusic|first =Eduardo|last =Rivadavia}}</ref> a sub-genre with the heaviness and intensity of [[thrash metal]] but played at a slower tempo.<ref name=loudwire28/><ref>{{cite book|title =Historical Dictionary of Popular Music|first =Norman|last =Abjorensen|publisher =Rowman & Littlefield|date =2017|isbn =9781538102152|page =384}}</ref> [[Southern rock]] elements were incorporated into the sound;<ref name=loudwire28/> Pantera's \"groove\" is commonly attributed to the Abbott brothers' fondness for [[ZZ Top]].<ref name=louderfeature>{{cite web|url =https://www.loudersound.com/features/how-pantera-went-from-a-glam-band-to-redefining-metal|title =Pantera: how an ex-glam band from Texas redefined metal|website =Louder|first =Dom|last =Lawson|date =December 21, 2018}}</ref> ''Cowboys from Hell'' was certified gold in 1993, and platinum in 1997.<ref name=loudwire28/>\n\nPantera played close to 200 shows supporting ''Cowboys from Hell'', as it toured for nearly two years.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=97}} Aside from breaks to develop new material, the band spent most of the 1990s touring;{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=78}} Abbott gained a reputation as a wild figure on tour and a heavy drinker.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=88}} Pantera recorded its second major-label album in the space of two months. Released on February 25, 1992, ''[[Vulgar Display of Power]]'' was a refinement of the groove metal sound.<ref name=louderfeature/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=98}} The band had sought to create a heavier album than ''Cowboys from Hell'', as Anselmo fully embraced a [[Hardcore punk|hardcore]]-inspired shouted vocal delivery. Abbott composed most of the riffs and song structures, and further attempted to mesh his guitar with Brown's bass to create what Brown later described as \"one giant tone\".<ref name=loudwire26>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-vulgar-display-of-power-anniversary/|title =26 Years Ago: Pantera Released The Groundbreaking 'Vulgar Display of Power'|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =February 25, 2019}}</ref> ''Vulgar Display of Power'' debuted at No. 44 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'', and it stayed on the chart for 79 weeks.<ref name=loudwire26/> In 2017, it was ranked at No. 10 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time\", with Abbott's \"serrated rhythms and squealing solos\" highlighted.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/pantera-vulgar-display-of-power-1992-195691/|title =The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time: Pantera, \u2018Vulgar Display of Power\u2019 (1992)|website =Rolling Stone|first =Richard|last =Bienstock|date =June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dimebag Darrell with Pantera.jpg|thumb|Abbott on stage with Pantera, 1991]]\nAbbott had transformed his appearance by the time of ''Vulgar Display of Power''{{'}}s release to that which he would maintain for the rest of his life. He sported a dyed [[goatee]], a razorblade pendant (in homage to Judas Priest's ''[[British Steel (album)|British Steel]]''), cargo shorts and sleeveless shirts.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=103}} Feeling that \"Diamond Darrell\" no longer suited his image or sound, Abbott adopted the stage name \"Dimebag Darrell\" instead.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/dimebag-stage-name-origins/|title =Dimebag - Stage Name Origins|website =Loudwire|first =Graham|last =Hartmann|date =June 6, 2012}}</ref> The name was originally coined by Anselmo.<ref name=billboardrita/> It was in reference to Abbott's refusal to accept more than a dime bag (slang for $10 worth)<ref>{{cite book|title =Sex, Drugs, and Murder: 15 Music Murder Scandals That Shocked the World|first =William|last =Webb|publisher =Absolute Crime|page =17}}</ref> of [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]]<ref>{{cite book|title =Historic Columbus Crimes: Mama's in the Furnace, the Thing & More|first1 =David|last1 =Meyers|first2 =Elise|last2 =Meyers-Walker|publisher =Arcadia Publishing|date =2010|isbn =9781614231202|page=131}}</ref> at one time\u2014even if offered for free\u2014as he did not want to be caught with the drug on-hand.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=23}}\n\nAll of Pantera's albums until 1994 were recorded at Pantego Sound, the studio owned by the Abbott brothers' father Jerry.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=107}} It was conveniently located a short distance from the Abbotts' home.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=108}} After ''Vulgar Display of Power'' was released, Jerry closed Pantego Sound and opened a new studio, Abtrax, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], as he hoped to fulfill his dream of becoming a country songwriter.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=105}} Pantera's third major-label album, ''[[Far Beyond Driven]]'', was recorded at Abtrax. Abbott said in a 1994 ''[[Guitar Player]]'' interview: \"We were fuckin' flying [to Nashville] for three weeks at a time, writing songs and cutting them.\" This led to the members spending most of their downtime in each other's hotel rooms consuming drugs, rather than following their normal routines as they did when recording at Pantego Sound.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=108}} They [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] the album at Dallas Sound Labs, which was close to their homes.<ref name=revolverfbd/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/magazine/dimebag-darrell-talks-far-beyond-driven-amps-and-more-previously-unreleased-1994-interview|title =Dimebag Darrell Talks 'Far Beyond Driven,' Amps and More: Previously Unreleased 1994 Interview|website =Guitar World|first =Chris|last =Gill|date =June 16, 2014}}</ref> ''Far Beyond Driven'' was released on March 15, 1994, on [[EastWest Records]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=116}} It sold 186,000 copies in its first week to debut at No. 1 on the ''Billboard 200'',{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=115}} and has since been described as the heaviest album ever to debut at No. 1.<ref name=revolverfbd/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=115}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/pantera-far-beyond-driven-1994-3-195056/|title =The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time: Pantera, \u2018Far Beyond Driven\u2019 (1994)|website =Rolling Stone|first =Richard|last =Bienstock|date =June 21, 2017}}</ref> Before the release, the band was expected to follow the lead of Metallica's [[Metallica (album)|eponymous album]] by taking a more commercially-friendly approach.<ref name=revolverfbd>{{cite web|url =https://www.revolvermag.com/music/panteras-far-beyond-driven-story-behind-heaviest-album-debut-no-1|title =Pantera's 'Far Beyond Driven': The Story Behind the Heaviest Album to Debut at No. 1|website =Revolver|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =April 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pantera-look-back-at-20-years-of-far-beyond-driven-241999/|title =Pantera Look Back at 20 Years of 'Far Beyond Driven'|website =Rolling Stone|first =Kory|last =Grow|date =March 27, 2014}}</ref> Instead, Pantera wanted an even heavier work than ''Vulgar Display of Power''. Abbott said in 1994: \"We're into topping ourselves. Most bands come out with a heavy record, then it gets lighter and lighter. You're stuck listening to the first record, wishing and dreaming. That ain't what we're about.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=117}}\n\n====Band tensions and separation====\n\nThe lead single from ''Far Beyond Driven'', \"[[I'm Broken]]\", was inspired by Anselmo's chronic back pain.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/philip-anselmo-pantera-im-broken-exclusive/|title =Philip Anselmo Talks Vulnerability on Pantera's 'I'm Broken'|website =Loudwire|first =Graham|last =Hartmann|date =March 25, 2014}}</ref> To treat the pain during the tour supporting ''Far Beyond Driven'', Anselmo began heavily consuming alcohol, painkillers and ultimately [[heroin]]. He would travel on his own tour bus and isolate himself from the other band members until twenty or thirty minutes before they were due to perform. Anselmo recalled in a 2014 interview that he would drink \"an entire bottle of [[Wild Turkey (bourbon)|Wild Turkey]] every night before a show to numb the pain\", and he often interrupted the performances by ranting on stage.<ref name=revolverfbd/> Due to the tensions within the band, recordings for Pantera's next album, ''[[The Great Southern Trendkill]]'', were held separately: Darrell, Vinnie and Brown recorded at Chasin' Jason Studio (a studio Darrell had constructed in a barn in his backyard) while Anselmo recorded the vocals at [[Trent Reznor]]'s Nothing Studios in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=loudwiregstk>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-the-great-southern-trendkill-album-anniversary/|title =22 Years Ago: Pantera Release 'The Great Southern Trendkill'|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =May 7, 2017}}</ref> Abbott experimented with new guitars during the recording; he stated in 1996 that he wrote \"[[Suicide Note (song)|Suicide Note Pt. 1]]\" the first time he used a [[twelve-string guitar]] which [[Washburn Guitars]] had sent to him.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=146}} The recording also saw Abbott draw on riffs he had composed much earlier:{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=146}} he wrote the [[Outro (music)|outro-solo]] to \"[[Floods (Pantera song)|Floods]]\" in the pre-Anselmo era, and he had previously recorded a 90-minute loop of it as a lullaby for his girlfriend.<ref>{{cite book|title =Official Truth, 101 Proof: The Inside Story of Pantera|first =Rex|last =Brown|publisher =Hachette|isbn =9780306821387|page =111}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 1996, ''The Great Southern Trendkill'' was released. It peaked at No. 4 on the ''Billboard 200'', staying on the chart for 13 weeks. It is considered to be Pantera's most [[extreme metal|extreme]] work,<ref name=loudwiregstk/> and features some of the band's [[Guitar tuning#Dropped tunings|lowest-tuned]] tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://loudwire.com/pantera-the-great-southern-trendkill-20th-anniversary-edition/|title =Pantera's 'The Great Southern Trendkill' Gets 20th Anniversary Edition|website =Loudwire|first =Chad|last =Childers|date =August 12, 2016}}</ref> On July 13, Anselmo [[Opioid overdose|overdosed]] on heroin following the band's performance at the Dallas [[Starplex Amphitheatre]] and was [[clinically dead]] for \"four to five minutes\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}}<ref>{{cite web|url =http://articles.latimes.com/1996-07-19/entertainment/ca-25610_1_los-angeles|title =Back From the Brink|website =Los Angeles Times|first =Shauna|last =Snow|date =July 19, 1996}}</ref> He recovered quickly and performed at the band's next show in San Antonio two days afterwards, but the incident created a lasting rift within the band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=148}} Anselmo also had released ''[[NOLA (album)|NOLA]]'', the debut album of one of his side projects [[Down (band)|Down]], in 1995, and supported the album with a 13-show tour.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=148}} The other Pantera members were originally unperturbed by Anselmo's side projects; Abbott explained at the time: \"Phil's a musical guy and he likes to stay busy.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=148}}\n\nThe touring for ''The Great Southern Trendkill'' widened the rift within the band, and the recording sessions for their next album, ''[[Reinventing the Steel]]'', were troublesome.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=171}} Vinnie said in an interview after the album's release: \"It was like pulling teeth to get [Anselmo] down to the studio. He didn't like any of the material, and it was always just like this head-butting contest.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=172}} Also during the recording, the Abbotts' mother, Carolyn, was diagnosed with lung cancer, and died six weeks later on September 12, 1999. This had a profound effect on the brothers, especially Darrell.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=172}} ''Reinventing the Steel'' was released on March 21, 2000. Abbott said of it: \"We still play lead guitar ... Bands hardly ever play lead guitar anymore. Dude, back in the seventies, if you couldn't play the guitar or sing, you were nobody. Now music is so easy\u2014all you've got to do is tune your guitar to an open chord and jump around.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=176}} Like ''The Great Southern Trendkill'', ''Reinventing the Steel'' peaked at No. 4 on the ''Billboard 200''.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=176}}\n\nPantera were in Ireland, set to begin a European tour, on September 11, 2001. Due to the [[September 11 attacks]], the tour was canceled and the members returned to Texas, where they agreed to take a short hiatus.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=185}} In March 2002, Down released its second record, ''[[Down II: A Bustle in Your Hedgerow]]'', which featured Brown on bass. Two months later, [[Superjoint Ritual]]\u2014another of Anselmo's bands\u2014released its debut album, ''[[Use Once and Destroy]]''.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=186}} The Abbotts believed that Pantera would regroup in 2003, after the tours supporting ''Down II'' and ''Use Once and Destroy'' were concluded. Instead, Anselmo recorded a second album with Superjoint Ritual, ''[[A Lethal Dose of American Hatred]]'' (2003).{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=187}} Also around this time, Darrell received a phone call from Brown, who indicated that he would not return to Pantera.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=188}} The separation of Pantera was marked by the release of a greatest hits album, ''[[The Best of Pantera: Far Beyond the Great Southern Cowboys' Vulgar Hits!]]'', on September 23, 2003.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=188}}\n\n===Damageplan===\n{{Further|Damageplan}}\nAbbott was dejected by the separation of Pantera;{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=195}} he felt that all he had worked for had been \"ripped out from under [him]\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=197}} As continuing Pantera without Anselmo likely would have resulted in a lengthy and expensive legal battle regarding the ownership of the \"Pantera\" brand, the Abbott brothers decided to form a new band.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=200}} They recorded demos at Darrell's backyard studio in February 2003.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=203}} [[Patrick Lachman]] of [[Halford (band)|Halford]] joined as vocalist and [[Bob Kakaha]] was recruited on bass, and the band signed with [[Elektra Records]] later in 2003. The name of the band originally was New Found Power, but they later decided on [[Damageplan]]. ''[[New Found Power]]'' instead served as the title of group's debut album, which was released on February 10, 2004.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=204}} It did not near the commercial success of Pantera's major-label releases:{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=220}} it sold 44,000 copies in its first week to debut at No. 38 on the ''Billboard 200'' and had sold a modest 160,000 copies by December.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=233}} \n\nDamageplan spent most of 2004 on its Devastation Across the Nation tour. To rebuild a fanbase, the band toured nightclubs across the country.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=210}} The members had planned to record a follow-up album.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=210}} This did not materialize due to [[#Death|Abbott's murder]] at a show in Columbus, Ohio, on December 8, 2004.\n\n===Other projects===\n\nThe Abbott brothers listened to country singer [[David Allan Coe]] while growing up as their parents were fans of the performer, and often used Coe's \"Jack Daniels If You Please\" as introductory music for Pantera shows.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=164}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/59584/panteracoe-album-unearthed-for-may-release|title =Pantera/Coe Album Unearthed For May Release|website =Billboard|author =Staff writer(s)|date =February 24, 2006}}</ref> Darrell first met Coe in 1999, at one of his performances at [[Billy Bob's Texas]]. After the performance, Darrell waited in an autograph line to introduce himself and give Coe his phone number. They subsequently formed a friendship and Coe began spending time at Darrell's house, where the Abbott brothers and Coe played music in Darrell's backyard studio. They recruited Brown to play bass and the group sporadically recorded from 1999 to 2003.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=165}} The resulting album, ''[[Rebel Meets Rebel]]'', was released on May 2, 2006, on Vinnie's [[Big Vin Records]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=166}} Megan Frye of AllMusic stated ''Rebel Meets Rebel'' is \"groundbreaking in that it will please fans of both country and metal because the music is simultaneously both styles \u2013 it's never a fusion, they simply exist together\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allmusic.com/album/rebel-meets-rebel-mw0000407040|title =Rebel Meets Rebel|website =AllMusic|first =Megan|last =Frye}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Abbott and the other Pantera members collaborated with [[Rob Halford]] on a track titled \"Light Comes Out of Black\", which was released on the [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)#Soundtrack|''Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' soundtrack]].<ref name=revolvervdop>{{cite web|url =https://www.revolvermag.com/music/panteras-vulgar-display-power-epic-story-behind-hostile-masterpiece|title =Pantera's 'Vulgar Display of Power': The Epic Story Behind a Hostile Masterpiece|website =Revolver|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/dimebag-darrell/6363754/rob-halford-on-his-close-friendship-with-dimebag-darrell-ive-got|title =Rob Halford on His Close Friendship With 'Dimebag' Darrell: 'I've Got Wonderful Memories'|website =Billboard|first =Dan|last =Epstein|date =December 8, 2014}}</ref> Abbott recorded the song \"Caged in a Rage\", on which he performed lead vocals and guitar, under his own name. It was included on the [[Supercop (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 1996 film ''[[Police Story 3: Super Cop|Supercop]]''. Adam Greenberg of AllMusic said Abbott sounded \"oddly similar to [[Rob Zombie]]\" on \"Caged in a Rage\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allmusic.com/album/supercop-mw0000072482|title =Supercop - Original Soundtrack|website =AllMusic|first =Adam|last =Greenberg}}</ref>\n\nAbbott provided guest guitar solos for [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] on several occasions: \"King Size\" and \"Riding Shotgun\" from ''[[Stomp 442]]'' (1995), \"Inside Out\" and \"Born Again Idiot\" from ''[[Volume 8: The Threat Is Real]]'' (1998), and \"Strap It On\" and \"Cadillac Rock Box\" from ''[[We've Come for You All]]'' (2003).{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} Anthrax's [[Scott Ian]] referred to Abbott as the \"sixth member\" of the band due to his frequent appearances.<ref name=revolvervdop/> Abbott also performed a guest solo on the title track of [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]]'s ''[[Voodoo (King Diamond album)|Voodoo]]'' (1998) and on \"Eyes of the South\" (2004) by Premenishen, a band that featured Abbott's cousins Heather Manly and April Adkisson on bass and guitar, respectively.{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} After Darrell's death, Vinnie granted [[Nickelback]] permission to use outtakes of Darrell's solos from the ''Vulgar Display of Power'' and ''Far Beyond Driven'' recordings on its tribute track \"[[Side of a Bullet]]\".{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} Darrell was a friend of Nickelback's [[Chad Kroeger]] and had provided a solo for Nickelback's cover of \"[[Saturday Night's Alright for Fighting]]\" on the soundtrack to the 2003 film ''[[Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle]]''.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=263}}\n\nDarrell and Vinnie performed shows as [[Gasoline (band)|Gasoline]] each New Years' Eve. Gasoline predominantly played covers of artists such as [[Ted Nugent]] and [[Pat Travers]], but also composed original songs such as \"Get Drunk Now\" and \"This Ain't a Beer Belly, It's a Gas Tank for My Love Machine\".{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=162}} Gasoline once served as a support act for [[Drowning Pool]].{{sfn|Daniels|2013|p=167}} In 2006, \"Country Western Transvestite Whore\", a song that Abbott recorded with local Dallas musician Throbbin' Donnie Rodd, was released. It features Abbott on lead guitar and vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.wprost.pl/muzyka/292115/zaginione-country-dimebaga.html|title =Zaginione Country Dimebaga|website =Wprost|author =Staff writer(s)|date =December 6, 2006|language =Polish}}</ref> Other works by Abbott that have been posthumously released include \"Dime's Blackout Society\" (2010) and ''The Hitz'' (2017), a five-track EP.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rhino.com/article/heavy-metal-monday-dimebag-darrell-the-hitz|title =Heavy Metal Monday: Dimebag Darrell, THE HITZ|publisher =Rhino Entertainment|author =Staff writer(s)|date =July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n{{Main|Columbus nightclub shooting}}\n\n[[File:Dimebag 001.jpg|thumb|A fan mourns outside the Alrosa Villa nightclub in Columbus, Ohio, where Abbott was murdered.]]\nOn December 8, 2004, Damageplan was performing at the Alrosa Villa nightclub in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. As the band played the first song of its setlist, Nathan Gale, a deranged fan, rushed onto the stage and shot Abbott multiple times with a [[Beretta 92FS]], a 9mm semi-automatic pistol.<ref>{{cite book|title =Power Chord: One Man's Ear Splitting Quest to Find His Guitar Heroes|first =Thomas Scott|last =McKenzie|publisher =HarperCollins|date =2012|page =12|isbn =9780062098986}}</ref> The band's head of security, Jeffrey \"Mayhem\" Thompson, then tackled Gale, but was fatally shot in the ensuing struggle. A fan, Nathan Bray, was also murdered as he attempted to aid Abbott and Thompson, as was Erin Halk, an employee of the venue who tried to disarm Gale while he was reloading. Three others were wounded before [[Columbus Division of Police|Columbus police officer]] James Niggemeyer entered the club and shot Gale once in the head with a 12-gauge [[Remington Model 870]], killing him.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/behind-the-murder-of-dimebag-darrell-233541/|title =Behind the Murder of \u2018Dimebag\u2019 Darrell|website =Rolling Stone|first =Peter|last =Wilkinson|date =December 30, 2004}}</ref>\n\nAbbott was pronounced dead at the scene, aged 38. Thousands of fans attended his public memorial, and the guest list included artists such as [[Eddie Van Halen]], [[Zakk Wylde]], [[Corey Taylor]], [[Jerry Cantrell]] and [[Dino Cazares]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title =A Raucous Farewell to the Cowboy From Hell|first =Zac|last =Crain|magazine =Spin|date =March 2005|volume =21|issue =3|pages =20\u201321|publisher =SPIN Media LLC}}</ref> Abbott was buried alongside his mother Carolyn at the Moore Memorial Gardens cemetery in Arlington, Texas. [[Gene Simmons]] donated a [[Kiss Kasket]] for the burial, and Eddie Van Halen donated his original black-and-yellow-striped 1979 [[Charvel]] \"Bumblebee\" guitar, which was featured on the back cover of ''[[Van Halen II]]'', to be included in the casket.{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=7}} A few weeks prior to his death, Abbott had met Van Halen and asked him for a replica of the Bumblebee. Van Halen said at the funeral: \"Dime was an original and only an original deserves the original.\"<ref name=billboardrita/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarplayer.com/players/dimebag-darrell-buried-with-one-of-rocks-most-iconic-guitars|title =Dimebag Darrell Buried With One of Rock's Most Iconic Guitars|first =Jennifer|last =Bergeron|website =Guitar Player|date =December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter Vinnie Paul's death in 2018, he was buried next to Carolyn and Darrell, also in a Kiss Kasket.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.stereogum.com/2003980/panteras-vinnie-paul-will-be-buried-in-a-free-kiss-casket-like-his-brother-dimebag-darrell/news/|title =Pantera\u2019s Vinnie Paul Will Be Buried In A Free KISS Casket Like His Brother Dimebag Darrell|website =Stereogum|first =Peter|last =Helman|date =June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/vinnie-paul-to-be-buried-in-kiss-casket/|title =Report: Vinnie Paul to Be Buried in KISS Casket|website =Loudwire|first =Tyler|last =Sharp|date =June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nOriginally a [[glam metal]] musician, Abbott distanced himself from the subgenre by the late 1980s, and was a driving force behind the development of [[groove metal]] in the 1990s.<ref name=louderfeature/>\n\n===Influences===\n\nAlthough his father was a country music producer and songwriter, Abbott's primary musical influences were [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] acts such as [[Black Sabbath]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] and [[Van Halen]].{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}} [[Ace Frehley]] of Kiss inspired him to play guitar.<ref name=gw94>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/gw-archive/dimebag-darrell-discusses-his-roots-gear-and-pantera-1994-guitar-world-interview|title =Dimebag Darrell Discusses His Roots, Gear and Pantera in 1994 Guitar World Interview|website =Guitar World|first =Brad|last =Tolinski|date =November 1, 2011}}</ref> He was a member of the [[Kiss Army]] and had a portrait of Frehley tattooed on his chest in 1992. While at a photo shoot for the August 1993 issue of ''[[Guitar World]]'' along with Frehley, Abbott asked Frehley to sign an autograph near the tattoo. Abbott then had the signature tattooed.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=105}}<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/dimebag-darrell-rock-soldiers|title =Dimebag Darrell: Rock Soldiers|website =Guitar World|first =Jeff|last =Kitts|date =December 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nNo musician other than Frehley exerted more of an influence on Abbott than Eddie Van Halen.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=217}} Abbott stated that his background mirrored Van Halen's as both he and Van Halen were younger brothers who first played drums before moving on to the guitar due to competition from their elder brothers on drums. Another influence was [[Randy Rhoads]]. Abbott said in 1994: \"To me, Eddie Van Halen was heavy rock and roll, but Randy was heavy metal.\"<ref name=gw94/> He discovered [[double tracking]] leads through Rhoads.<ref name=gw94/> In numerous interviews, Abbott credited [[Tony Iommi]] of Black Sabbath for inspiring his guitar riffs.{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}} Abbott also said [[Def Leppard]]'s original guitarist [[Pete Willis]] \"was a great player. I was inspired by him because I was a small young dude and he was a small young dude, too\u2014and he was out there kickin' ass. He made me want to get out there and play.\"<ref name=gw93>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/magazine/prime-cuts-dimebag-darrell-chooses-his-12-favorite-tunes-1993-guitar-world-feature|title =Pantera's Dimebag Darrell Chooses His 12 Favorite Songs in 1993 Guitar World Interview|website =Guitar World|first =Jeff|last =Kitts|date =August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbbott was a fan of the [[Southern rock]] band [[ZZ Top]],<ref name=louderfeature/> and he was influenced by the band's guitarist and lead singer [[Billy Gibbons]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}} He said in 1993: \"I'm not a super [[blues]] player, but I was exposed to the [[Texas blues]] sound while I was growing up, and that definitely rubbed off on me.\"<ref name=gw93/> Abbott was also influenced by contemporary metal guitarists such as [[Kerry King]] of [[Slayer]], [[James Hetfield]] of [[Metallica]], and [[Zakk Wylde]] of [[List of Ozzy Osbourne band members|Ozzy Osbourne]] and [[Black Label Society]].{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}}\n\n===Technique===\n\nAbbott did not receive formal guitar lessons. He stated in a 1994 ''Guitar World'' interview that he once received \"a guitar lesson off this cat. He wrote down some weird [[Scale (music)|scale]] and tried to explain how it worked. After we finished he said, 'Now go on home, practice that scale, and show me how well you can play it next week.' So I took it home, played around with it for a few minutes and said, 'Fuck this, I just want to jam.' I respect people that can read [[tablature]] and all that shit, but I just don't even have the patience to read the newspaper.\"<ref name=gw94/>\n\nUnlike many other heavy metal guitarists, Abbott made extensive use of the [[major third]] in his riffs and leads, which added [[Consonance and dissonance|dissonance]] to minor key [[Tonality|tonalities]]. This was a Van Halen-inspired technique, as was his employment of symmetrical [[Fingering (music)|fingerings]]. Although Abbott had exceptional [[Guitar picking|picking]] ability, he favored [[legato]] phrasing. His love of legato gave his playing a fluid quality, and his powerful left hand technique enabled the implementation of the symmetrical patterns in his lead [[Lick (music)|licks]].<ref name=gw10p1>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/lessons/guitar-strength-10-commandments-playing-guitar-style-dimebag-darrell-part-1|title =10 Commandments of Playing Guitar in the Style of Pantera's Dimebag Darrell, Part 1|website =Guitar World|first =Scott|last =Marano|date =August 16, 2018}}</ref> Abbott avoided using scales and [[Mode (music)|modes]] in traditional fashions, and often used passing tones between [[Whole tone scale|scalar tones]] to add tension. These [[Chromatic scale|chromatic]] licks made up much of his playing.<ref name=gw10p2/> Regardless of the note or chord, Abbott played with a \"Texas style\", meaning a variety of techniques such as [[Slide guitar|sliding]], [[String bending|bending]], [[palm muting]], and use of the [[whammy bar]] and [[effects pedal]] to produce an idiosyncratic\nsound.<ref name=gw10p2/>  \n\nOne of the most distinctive features of Abbott's guitar playing was his use of [[String harmonic|harmonics]] to create a squealing sound,<ref name=gw10p1/> which he picked up from Gibbons.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}} Unsatisfied with standard techniques, Abbott often used [[Dyad (music)|dyads]] in place of traditional [[power chords]]. This added texture to his riffs and, when played with [[Distortion (music)|distortion]], created a tense sound.<ref name=gw10p1/> Abbott experimented with [[Guitar tunings#Alternative|alternate tunings]] throughout his career. Early on, his guitar was tuned down more than a quarter step, similar to ''[[Van Halen I]]'' and ''[[Van Halen II]]'' tuning. On ''Cowboys From Hell'' (1990), he utilized [[Guitar tunings#Dropped tunings|drop D tuning]], and beginning with ''Vulgar Display of Power'' (1992) he tuned his guitar down a whole step, which became his main tuning by the release of ''Reinventing the Steel'' (2000). He also used drop D down one step, down 1 \u00bd steps and drop D down 1 \u00bd steps tunings. Down 1 \u00bd steps tuning was prevalent on ''The Great Southern Trendkill'' (1996) and was Abbott's main tuning on ''New Found Power'' (2004).{{sfn|Gulla|2009|p=8}}<ref name=gw10p2>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/lessons/guitar-strength-10-commandments-playing-guitar-style-dimebag-darrell-part-2|title =10 Commandments of Playing Guitar in the Style of Dimebag Darrell, Part 2|website =Guitar World|first =Scott|last =Marano|date =August 16, 2018}}</ref>  \n\nThree of Abbott's solos were ranked in ''Guitar World''{{'}}s \"100 Greatest Guitar Solos of All Time\": \"[[Walk (Pantera song)|Walk]]\" at No. 57;<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/features/100-greatest-guitar-solos-51-100|title =100 Greatest Guitar Solos: 51-100|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =October 30, 2008}}</ref> \"[[Cemetery Gates]]\" at No. 35;<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/lessons/100-greatest-guitar-solos-no-35-cemetery-gates-dimebag-darrell|title =100 Greatest Guitar Solos: No. 35 \"Cemetery Gates\" (Dimebag Darrell)|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =October 28, 2008}}</ref> and \"[[Floods (Pantera song)|Floods]]\" at No. 19.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/gw-archive/100-greatest-guitar-solos-no-19-floods-dimebag-darrell|title =100 Greatest Guitar Solos: No. 19 \"Floods\" (Dimebag Darrell)|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =December 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/gw-archive/50-greatest-guitar-solos|title =50 Greatest Guitar Solos|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =January 29, 2009}}</ref> Despite his virtuosity, Abbott said that while \"jerking off all over the [[Neck (music)|neck]]\", as he described, was suited to competing in guitar contests, it often did not benefit a song's composition. \"Slaughtered\" from ''Far Beyond Driven'' originally had a slow, melodic solo, but Abbott removed it after noting that it disrupted the song's momentum.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=147}}\n\n==Equipment==\n[[File:Dean Guitar.jpg|thumb|One of Abbott's signature [[headstock]]s|upright=0.75]]\n\nIn 1982, Abbott won a maroon [[Dean ML]] at a guitar contest in Dallas.<ref name=australianguitar>{{cite magazine|url =https://www.pressreader.com/australia/australian-guitar/20140601/281921656124411|title =The Dean from Hell|magazine =Australian Guitar|date =June 2014}}</ref><ref name=dean1>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/dimebag-s-dean-of-destiny-1|title =Dimebag's Dean of Destiny, Part 1|website =Premier Guitar|first =Chris|last =Kies|date =August 20, 2008}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=57}} Unbeknownst to Abbott, his father had bought him a sunburst ML shortly before the contest. Nearing driving age and seeking to purchase a [[Pontiac Firebird]], Abbott attempted to sell the maroon ML to his friend Buddy Blaze, a [[luthier]] and musician. Blaze felt that a guitar won as a prize should stay with its owner and refused to buy it.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=58}} Abbott instead sold the guitar to one of Blaze's bandmates. Blaze negotiated with his bandmate, and took possession of the ML in exchange for a [[Kramer Pacer]]. Blaze then replaced the standard ML hardware: he installed a custom [[Floyd Rose]] vibrato bridge and [[Bill Lawrence (guitar maker)|Bill Lawrence]] L-500XL [[pickup (music technology)|pickups]], and moved the stock [[DiMarzio]] pickup to the neck.\nHe also repainted the guitar, from its original maroon to blue-and-black with a lightning bolt finish.<ref name=australianguitar/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=58}}<ref name=dean2>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/dimebag-s-dean-of-destiny-1?page=2|title =Dimebag's Dean of Destiny, Part 2|website =Premier Guitar|first =Chris|last =Kies|date =August 20, 2008}}</ref> Blaze returned the ML to Abbott in 1987, who was initially unaware that it was the same guitar he won as a prize.<ref name=dean3>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/dimebag-s-dean-of-destiny-1?page=3|title =Dimebag's Dean of Destiny, Part 3|website =Premier Guitar|first =Chris|last =Kies|date =August 20, 2008}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=59}} It subsequently became Abbott's signature guitar and was later dubbed the \"Dean from Hell\".<ref name=australianguitar/>\n\nAfter the release of ''Cowboys from Hell'', Abbott signed an endorsement deal with [[Dean Guitars]].<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Dean went out of business in 1994 and Abbott then signed a ten-year contract with [[Washburn Guitars]].{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=152}} With Washburn, he played various signature guitars modeled after the ML, such as the Dime 333, Culprit and Stealth.<ref name=halleonard>{{cite book|title =100 Great Guitarists and the Gear That Made Them Famous|first =Dave|last =Rubin|publisher =Hal Leonard Corporation|date =2017|isbn =9781540019363|pages =86\u201387}}</ref> When his contract with Washburn expired in 2004, he became the main endorsee of the re-opened Dean.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=222}} Abbott's murder came shortly before the Dean contract was set to begin.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.bizjournals.com/tampabay/stories/2004/12/06/daily38.html|title =Despite shooting, Dean Guitars to proceed with 'Dimebag' model|website =Tampa Bay Business Journal|first =Carl|last =Cronan|date =December 10, 2004}}</ref> Abbott had designed the [[Dean Razorback]] and [[Dean Razorback V|Razorback V]] in the months prior to his death.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/dimebag-week-a-complete-guide-to-dimebag-darrell-signature-gear-611282|title =A complete guide to Dimebag Darrell signature gear|website =MusicRadar|first =Stuart|last =Williams|date =December 4, 2014}}</ref> Dean also posthumously released replicas of the Dean from Hell.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/12/dean-guitars-dimebag-darrell-win-lawsuit-dean-from-hell-guitar/|title =Dimebag Darrell estate and Dean Guitars win lawsuit over \u201cDean From Hell\u201d guitar|website =Consequence of Sound|first =Robert|last =Ham|date =December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAbbott was praised for his instrumental [[musical tone|tone]] and was included in ''Guitar Player''{{'}}s list of \"The 50 Greatest Tones of All Time\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Blackett |first=Matt |title=The 50 Greatest Tones of All Time |journal=Guitar Player |volume=38 |issue=10 |pages=44\u201366 |publisher= |date=October 2004 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarplayer.com/players/50-kings-of-tone-the-secrets-behind-their-sounds-video|title =50 Kings of Tone: The Secrets Behind Their Sounds|website =Guitar Player|first =Matt|last =Blackett|date =April 2, 2015}}</ref> Abbott used [[Guitar amplifier#Solid-state|solid-state]] [[Randall Amplifiers|Randall]] amplifiers for most of his career; he remarked in the [[liner notes]] for ''Cowboys from Hell'': \"Gotta have that Randall Crunch!\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=225}} He had won his first Randall amplifier in a guitar contest; he said in a 1993 interview it \"was a little nasty sounding, a little gritty, but I liked it. I knew that with time I could make it my own sound, and it came around.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/dimebag-darrell-home-deranged|title =Dimebag Darrell: Home of Deranged|website =Guitar World|first =Glenn|last =Thrush|date =December 8, 2009}}</ref> Abbott released a signature amplifier, the Randall Warhead, in 1999. The goal was to replicate the sound of his own rig: a Randall RG-100 head, Furman PQ-3 [[parametric equalizer]], [[MXR]] six-band [[graphic equalizer]] and MXR 126 [[flanger]].<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> He set his Furman EQ to boost the highs and lows while scooping the mids,<ref name=gw10p2/> and he used both the Furman EQ and MXR EQ to increase the gain to the Randall's front end.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott also used a [[Digitech whammy pedal]], a [[Korg]] DT-7 [[chromatic tuner]] and a Rocktron Hush IIC [[noise gate]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.seymourduncan.com/blog/backstage-pass/dimebag-darrell-of-pantera|title =Dimebag Darrell: Reinventing the Steel with the SH-13 Dimebucker|publisher =Seymour Duncan|first =Lisa|last =Sharken|date =February 9, 2007}}</ref> The noise gate allowed him to control the feedback associated with high levels of gain, and to create the distinctive holes of silence in his playing.<ref name=gw10p2/> \n\nWhen Abbott's endorsement deal with Washburn ended, his deal with Randall also ended, as Randall and Washburn both were subsidiaries of the [[U.S. Music Corporation]]. Abbott subsequently formed a partnership with Krank Amplifiers, a relatively small supplier.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=225}} He used the Krank Revolution, a [[tube amplifier]].<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott also invested in the company and designed an amplifier named the Krankenstein;{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=226}} he approved the final revision of the Krankenstein just days before his murder.<ref name=reinventingsqueal/> Abbott helped design many other products. With [[Dunlop Manufacturing]], he designed the Dimebag Cry Baby from Hell, a [[wah-wah pedal]], and the Dime Distortion, a [[distortion pedal]]. He also designed a signature pickup with [[Seymour Duncan]] titled the Dimebucker, which was based on the Bill Lawrence pickups that he used in most of his guitars. [[Dean Zelinsky]] of Dean said in 2010 that Abbott's death was a \"bigger loss than we'll ever know. ...  I'm very proud of the work I did with him, but who knows what he would have accomplished if he was still with us.\"<ref name=reinventingsqueal/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAbbott grew up in the same neighborhood as his long-time partner Rita Haney, whom he first met at the age of eight.<ref name=billboardrita>{{cite web|url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/dimebag-darrell/6363758/dimebag-darrells-longtime-partner-rita-haney-hed-actually-be|title ='Dimebag' Darrell's Longtime Partner Rita Haney: 'He'd Actually Be Surprised at How Many People He Touched'|website =Billboard|first =Dan|last =Epstein|date =December 8, 2014}}</ref>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=41}} They began dating in 1984.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=42}} The couple never married. Haney said in a 2006 interview: \"We didn't believe in the marriage thing. ... Why have someone you don't know tell you it's OK to be with someone you do know? We didn't need the middleman! We had a one-on-one with the man upstairs ourselves.\"{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=125}} \n\nIn 1995, Abbott bought a house with Haney in [[Dalworthington Gardens, Texas]], a short distance from his hometown Arlington.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=124}} Abbott kept a pet [[goat]] on the residence, and dyed its goatee like his own.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=125}} He was remembered by his neighbors as approachable. One neighbor who often walked dogs with Abbott said he \"was a hick with an attitude, and I say that respectfully. We'd talk conservative politics. He was a big, big supporter of [[George W. Bush|George Bush]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Pantera-fans-pay-their-respects-to-slain-rocker-1568482.php|title =Pantera fans pay their respects to slain rocker|website =Houston Chronicle|first =Thomas|last =Korosec|date =December 10, 2004}}</ref>\n\nDarrell and Vinnie opened the Clubhouse, an all-nude [[strip club]] in north-west Dallas, in 1996. Vinnie's original idea was a rock-and-roll-themed golf course, with \"a strip club at the nineteenth hole\", but the construction of a golf course was prohibitively expensive.{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=160}}<ref name=texasmonthly>{{cite web|url =https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/bare-assets/|title =Bare Assets|website =Texas Monthly|first =Andy|last =Langer|date =May 2000}}</ref> Under the Abbott brothers' ownership, the Clubhouse was patronized by many artists who toured in the area, such as Black Sabbath, Kiss and Metallica, as well as [[NASCAR]] drivers, professional golfers,<ref name=texasmonthly/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=161}} and members of the [[Dallas Cowboys]] and the [[Dallas Stars]] (whose [[fight song]], \"[[Dallas Stars#Traditions|Puck Off]]\", was written and produced by Pantera).<ref name=texasmonthly/>{{sfn|Crain|2009|p=163}} After the Dallas Stars won the [[1999 Stanley Cup Finals]], the Abbott brothers hosted a party for the team at Vinnie's house. Vinnie later stated that the [[Stanley Cup]] was dented during the party after [[Guy Carbonneau]] threw it out of a window into a swimming pool, but barely missed the pool and hit the edge.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.hookedonhockeymagazine.com/dallas-stars-and-the-mystery-dent-in-the-stanley-cup/|title =The Dallas Stars and the Mystery Dent in the Stanley Cup|first =Brendon|last =Carlton|website =Hooked on Hockey|date =December 25, 2013}}</ref><ref name=lwsc>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/did-vinnie-paul-dent-stanley-cup/|title =That Time Vinnie Paul Dented the Stanley Cup|website =Loudwire|first =Michael|last =Christopher|date =June 25, 2018}}</ref> The brothers also performed on a [[Float (parade)|float]] during the celebration of the Stars' victory.<ref name=lwsc/>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{See also|Columbus nightclub shooting#Tributes}}\n\nOn May 17, 2007, Abbott was posthumously inducted into [[Hollywood's RockWalk]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/news/dimebag-darrell-gets-rockwalk-induction|title =Dimebag Darrell Gets Rockwalk Induction|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =April 23, 2007}}</ref> Ace Frehley was among the attendees at the induction ceremony, where he spoke in honor of Abbott.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://bravewords.com/news/ace-frehley-attends-dimebag-darrells-rockwalk-induction-photo-available|title =Ace Frehley Attends Dimebag Darrell's RockWalk induction|website =Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles|author =Staff writer(s)|date =May 18, 2007}}</ref> Frehley also dedicated his 2009 album ''[[Anomaly (Ace Frehley album)|Anomaly]]'' to Abbott, as well as former Kiss drummer [[Eric Carr]].<ref>{{cite web|url =http://bravewords.com/news/ace-frehley-eddie-trunk-reviews-anomaly|title =ACE FREHLEY - Eddie Trunk Reviews Anomaly|author =Staff writer(s)|website =Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles|date =September 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Abbott was ranked as the most influential metal guitarist of the past 25 years by [[VH1]]. Doc Coyle of [[God Forbid]] stated: \"[Abbott's] sparse, low-end, bluesy chug was the blueprint for post-thrash, [[nu-metal]], and [[metalcore]] in the subsequent years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170707082614/http://www.vh1.com/news/3639/most-influential-metal-guitarists-of-the-modern-era/|title =20 Most Influential Metal Guitarists Of The Modern Era|publisher =VH1|first =Doc|last =Coyle|date =April 10, 2015}}</ref> Also in 2015, Abbott placed at No. 5 on [[Gibson]]'s list of \"The Top 10 Metal Guitarists of All Time\". Anne Erickson said Abbott \"proved metal guitar could shred wildly, but still groove. ... He'll always be remembered as one of the most significant engineers of modern metal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://web.archive.org/web/20180818084419/http://www.gibson.com:80/News-Lifestyle/Features/en-us/shred-stars-0803-2011.aspx|title =Top 10 Metal Guitarists of All Time|publisher =Gibson|first =Anne|last =Erickson|date =September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked Abbott at No. 92 on its list of \"The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" in 2011, and described him as \"one of modern metal's key figures\". [[Geezer Butler]] of Black Sabbath said Abbott was \"one of the greatest musicians to grace our world\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/100-greatest-guitarists-153675/dimebag-darrell-41534/|title =100 Greatest Guitarists: Dimebag Darrell|website =Rolling Stone|first =Patrick|last =Doyle|date =2011}}</ref> In 2018, Abbott ranked at No. 19 on ''[[Metal Hammer|Louder]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 50 Greatest Guitarists Of All Time\". [[Sebastian Bach]] of [[Skid Row (American band)|Skid Row]] commented that Abbott \"reinvented heavy metal guitar\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-50-greatest-guitarists-of-all-time/4|title =The 50 Greatest Guitarists Of All Time|website =Louder|author =Staff writer(s)|date =September 29, 2018}}</ref> Jamie Humphries of ''[[Premier Guitar]]'' remarked in 2014: \"If there were ever a band and guitarist to credit for reinventing post-Metallica metal, it would have to be Pantera and the late Dimebag Darrell.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/21060-electric-etudes-dimebag-darrell|title =Electric Etudes: \u201cDimebag\u201d Darrell|website =Premier Guitar|first =Jamie|last =Humphries|date =June 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAbbott also ranked at No. 9 in a 2012 ''[[Guitar World]]'' readers' poll of \"The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\",<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/features/readers-poll-results-100-greatest-guitarists-all-time|title =Readers Poll Results: The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time|website =Guitar World|author =Staff writer(s)|date =October 10, 2012}}</ref> and was named the \"Greatest Metal Guitarist\" by ''[[Loudwire]]'' in 2013 after winning a reader-voted [[Bracket (tournament)|tournament bracket]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/dimebag-darrell-abbott-wins-loudwire-greatest-metal-guitarist-tournament/|title ='Dimebag' Darrell Abbott Declared Greatest Metal Guitarist|website =Loudwire|first =Spencer|last =Kaufman|date =August 13, 2013}}</ref> [[Jonathan Davis]] of [[Korn]] said in a 2014 interview with ''Loudwire'' that Abbott is \"one of the greatest guitar players ever. I mean if there was no Dimebag Darrell, there would be no Korn.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/remembering-dimebag-darrell-jonathan-davis-korn/|title =Remembering Dimebag Darrell: Korn's Jonathan Davis|first =Chad|last =Childers|website =Loudwire|date =December 3, 2014}}</ref> [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] stated that Abbott \"had a great tone and a great original style ... He was one of the best new guitar players that came out over a long period of time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/remembering-dimebag-darrell-slash/|title =Remembering Dimebag Darrell: Slash Praises Dime's Abilities|first =Graham|last =Hartmann|website =Loudwire|date =November 24, 2014}}</ref> [[Max Cavalera]] described Abbott as \"very talented, an amazing musician and a humble and cool guy \u2013 not a rock star asshole\".<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/remembering-dimebag-darrell-soulfly-max-cavalera/|title =Remembering Dimebag Darrell: Soulfly's Max Cavalera|first =Chad|last =Childers|website =Loudwire|date =December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA concert in memory of Abbott titled Dimebash has been held annually since 2010. All of the concert's proceeds go towards the [[Ronnie James Dio]] Stand Up and Shout Cancer Fund.<ref name=dimebash2010>{{cite web|url =https://www.guitarworld.com/news/dimebash-2010-all-star-concert-benefit-stand-and-shout-cancer-fund|title =Dimebash 2010: All-Star Concert to Benefit 'Stand Up and Shout Cancer Fund'|website =Guitar World|author =Editors|date =October 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/second-annual-dimebash-dimebag-darrell-december-14/|title =Second Annual 'DimeBash' Tribute to Dimebag Darrell Set for December 14|website =Loudwire|first =Jon|last =Wiederhorn|date =November 29, 2011}}</ref> Performers at Dimebash events have included artists such as [[Dave Grohl]],<ref>{{cite web|url =https://loudwire.com/corey-taylor-dave-grohl-walk-dimebash-2019/|title =Corey Taylor, Dave Grohl + More Cover 'Walk' at Dimebash 2019|website =Loudwire|first =Chad|last =Childers|date =January 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Kerry King]], [[Robb Flynn]],<ref name=dimebash2010/> [[Tom Morello]], and [[Serj Tankian]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/dimebash-2011-remembering-dimebag-darrell-21565/sebastian-bach-4-77628/|title =Dimebash 2011: Remembering Dimebag Darrell|website =Rolling Stone|author =Staff writer(s)|date =December 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Dimebag Darrell performances}}\n\n'''Pantera'''\n* ''[[Metal Magic]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Projects in the Jungle]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[I Am the Night (album)|I Am the Night]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Power Metal (album)|Power Metal]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Cowboys from Hell]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Vulgar Display of Power]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Far Beyond Driven]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Great Southern Trendkill]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Reinventing the Steel]]'' (2000)\n\n'''Damageplan'''\n*''[[New Found Power]]'' (2004)\n\n'''Rebel Meets Rebel'''\n*''[[Rebel Meets Rebel]]'' (2006)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=Q_DIQZsdsQcC|title =Black Tooth Grin: The High Life, Good Times, and Tragic End of \"Dimebag\" Darrell Abbott|first =Zac|last =Crain|publisher =Hachette Books|date =2009|isbn =9780786748020}}\n* {{citation|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=DL3I9qQWdeAC|title =Guitar Gods: The 25 Players who Made Rock History|first =Bob|last =Gulla|publisher =ABC-CLIO|date =2009|isbn =9780313358067}}\n* {{citation|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=ttGGDwAAQBAJ|title =Reinventing Metal: The True Story of Pantera and the Tragically Short Life of Dimebag Darrell|first =Neil|last =Daniels|publisher =Rowman & Littlefield|date =2013|isbn =9781480362734}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dimebag Darrell}}\n\n* {{allmusic|id=dimebag-darrell-mn0000262251}}\n* {{IMDB name|id=0201602}}\n* {{Findagrave|10061348}}\n\n{{Damageplan}}\n{{Pantera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darrell, Dimebag}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Burials in Texas]]\n[[Category:Damageplan members]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Murdered American musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Musicians who died on stage]]\n[[Category:Pantera members]]\n[[Category:People from Arlington, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Ennis, Texas]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther projects:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: New Years' Eve \u2192 New Year's Eve", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimebag_Darrell"}
{"title_page": "Rodgers Crossing Dam", "text_new": "'''Rodgers Crossing Dam''' was a major dam proposed for the [[Kings River (California)|Kings River]] in [[Central California]]. The dam would have been situated at the unincorporated community of [[Rodgers Crossing, California|Rodgers Crossing]] in [[Fresno County, California|Fresno County]], in the foothills of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] {{convert|30|mi|km}} east of [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]. The project was pushed during the 1960s and 1970s by the Kings River Conservation District (KRCD) to provide flood control and irrigation water supply. The estimated annual yield would be {{convert|100000|acre feet|km3}}.<ref name=\"krcd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.krcd.org/water/storage_studies/rodgers_crossing.html|title=Rodgers Crossing|publisher=Kings River Conservation District|date=|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref>\n\nThe purpose was to nearly double the storage capacity on the Kings River, as the existing [[Pine Flat Dam]] is unable to provide the high degree of flood protection for which it was originally built.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usbr.gov/mp/sccao/storage/docs/phase1_rpt_fnl/tech_app/10_rodgers_crossing.pdf|title=Upper San Joaquin River Basin Storage Investigation: Rodgers Crossing Reservoir|publisher=U.S. Bureau of Reclamation|work=|date=October 2003|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref> The original plan called for a concrete [[gravity dam]] {{convert|640|ft|m}} high, which would have formed a reservoir flooding {{convert|11|mi|km}} of the Kings River, nearly up to the boundary of [[Kings Canyon National Park]]. The reservoir would have a capacity of {{convert|737000|acre feet|km3}}, and the dam would have a [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric]] generating capacity of 310 [[megawatt]]s.<ref name=\"krcd\"/>\n\nDuring the 1980s, the Rodgers Crossing dam was dropped due to poor economic justifications, and pushback from conservationists and the tourism sector who did not want to see the Kings River, a popular whitewater run, flooded by a reservoir.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-03-20/local/me-7850_1_kings-river|title=Long Live the Kings|author=|work=Los Angeles Times|date=1987-03-20|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref> In 1987, a compromise was reached as the Kings River was incorporated into the [[National Wild and Scenic Rivers System]], with the Rodgers Crossing dam site placed under \"unified federal protection\" that would require an act of Congress to overturn if the dam were to be built in the future.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-02/news/mn-2010_1_kings-river|author=Houston, Paul|title=Kings River to Get Federal Protection in Compromise Bill|work=Los Angeles Times|date=1987-04-02|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of dams and reservoirs in California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tulare Basin Hydrography}}\n\n{{coord missing|California}}\n\n[[Category:Dams in the Tulare Basin]]\n[[Category:Kings River (California)]]\n[[Category:Dams in California]]\n[[Category:Cancelled dams]]\n[[Category:Cancelled hydroelectric power stations]]\n", "text_old": "'''Rodgers Crossing Dam''' was a major dam proposed for the [[Kings River (California)|Kings River]] in [[Central California]]. The dam would have been situated at the unincorporated community of [[Rodgers Crossing, California|Rodgers Crossing]] in [[Fresno County, California|Fresno County]], in the foothills of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] {{convert|30|mi|km}} east of [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]. The project was pushed during the 1960s and 1970s by the Kings River Conservation District (KRCD) to provide flood control and irrigation water supply. The estimated annual yield would be {{convert|100000|acre feet|km3}}.<ref name=\"krcd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.krcd.org/water/storage_studies/rodgers_crossing.html|title=Rodgers Crossing|publisher=Kings River Conservation District|date=|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref>\n\nThe purpose was to nearly double the storage capacity on the Kings River, as the existing [[Pine Flat Dam]] is unable to provide the high degree of flood protection for which it was originally built.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usbr.gov/mp/sccao/storage/docs/phase1_rpt_fnl/tech_app/10_rodgers_crossing.pdf|title=Upper San Joaquin River Basin Storage Investigation: Rodgers Crossing Reservoir|publisher=U.S. Bureau of Reclamation|work=|date=October 2003|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref> The original plan called for a concrete [[gravity dam]] {{convert|640|ft|m}} high, which would have formed a reservoir flooding {{convert|11|mi|km}} of the Kings River, nearly up to the boundary of [[Kings Canyon National Park]]. The reservoir would have a capacity of {{convert|737000|acre feet|km3}}, and the dam would have a [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric]] generating capacity of 310 [[megawatt]]s.<ref name=\"krcd\"/>\n\nDuring the 1980s, the Rodgers Crossing dam was dropped due to poor economic justifications, and pushback from conservationists and the tourism sector who did not want to see the Kings River, a popular whitewater run, flooded by a reservoir.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-03-20/local/me-7850_1_kings-river|title=Long Live the Kings|author=|work=Los Angeles Times|date=1987-03-20|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref> In 1987, a compromise was reached as the Kings River was incorporated into the [[National Wild and Scenic Rivers System]], with the Rodgers Crossing dam site placed under \"unified federal protection\" that would require an act of Congress to overturn if the dam were to be built in the future.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-02/news/mn-2010_1_kings-river|author=Houston, Paul|title=Kings River to Get Federal Protection in Compromise Bill|work=Los Angeles Times|date=1987-04-02|accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of dams and reservoirs in California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tulare Basin Hydrography}}\n\n{{coord missing|California}}\n\n[[Category:Dams in the Tulare Basin]]\n[[Category:Proposed dams]]\n[[Category:Kings River (California)]]\n[[Category:Dams in California]]\n", "name_user": "Macquaria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved from category \"Proposed dams\" to \"Cancelled dams\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodgers_Crossing_Dam"}
{"title_page": "Tom Eastwood", "text_new": "'''Thomas Hugh Eastwood''' (12 March 1922 \u2013 25 October 1999) was an [[England|English]] [[composer]].<ref name=\"Grove\">{{cite web|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.08485|title=Eastwood, Thomas Hugh (1922 - 1999), composer|author=Richard Cooke|website=Grove Music Online|access-date=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Hawley, Hampshire]], the son of General Sir Thomas [[Ralph Eastwood]] and Lady Mabel Vivian Temperley Eastwood. His grandmother was Ellinor Hall Smyth (married name Eastwood), sister of the British composer Dame [[Ethel Smyth]].\n\nTom Eastwood was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] University. During [[World War II]] he was [[aide-de-camp]] to his father who was then [[Governor of Gibraltar]].\n\nHe first studied music in Turkey with Necil Akses, then in Berlin and London with Boris Blacher and Professor Erwin Stein. Tom Eastwood's inspirations included Greek theatre and later in life his musical imagination was fired by Brazilian folklore, history and music. His music encompasses contemporary themes such as the murdered environmental activist, Chico Mendes. He won a prize at the 1949 Cheltenham Music Festival for his String Trio.<ref name=\"Grove\"/>\n\nTom Eastwood worked for the [[British Council]] in [[Ankara]] and Berlin 1947\u201354, was a member of the Council of the [[Society for the Promotion of New Music]] from 1959 and was on the executive committee in 1959. In 1969 he wrote a [[List of television operas|television opera]] for the BBC, ''The Rebel''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jennifer Barnes|title=Television Opera: The Fall of Opera Commissioned for Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6fwSLslWOjsC&pg=PA5|year=2003|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-912-6|pages=5\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eastwood, Tom}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n\n\n{{UK-composer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Hugh Eastwood''' (12 March 1922 \u2013 25 October 1999) was an [[England|English]] [[composer]].<ref name=\"Grove\">{{cite web|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.08485|title=Eastwood, Thomas Hugh (1922 - 1999), composer|author=Richard Cooke|website=Grove Music Online|access-date=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Hawley, Hampshire]], the son of General Sir Thomas [[Ralph Eastwood]] and Lady Mabel Vivian Temperley Eastwood. His grandmother was Ellinor Hall Smyth (married name Eastwood), sister of the British composer Dame [[Ethel Smyth]].\n\nTom Eastwood was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] University. During [[World War II]] he was [[aide-de-camp]] to his father who was then [[Governor of Gibraltar]].\n\nHe first studied music in Turkey with Necil Akses, then in Berlin and London with Boris Blacher and Professor Erwin Stein. Tom Eastwood's inspirations included Greek theatre and later in life his musical imagination was fired by Brazilian folklore, history and music. His music encompasses contemporary themes such as the murdered environmental activist, Chico Mendes. He won a prize at the 1949 Cheltenham Music Festival for his String Trio.<ref name=\"Grove\"/>\n\nTom Eastwood worked for the [[British Council]] in [[Ankara]] and Berlin 1947\u201354, was a member of the Council of the [[Society for the Promotion of New Music]] from 1959 and was on the executive committee in 1959. In 1969 he wrote a television opera for the BBC, ''The Rebel''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jennifer Barnes|title=Television Opera: The Fall of Opera Commissioned for Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6fwSLslWOjsC&pg=PA5|year=2003|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-912-6|pages=5\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eastwood, Tom}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n\n\n{{UK-composer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Eastwood"}
{"title_page": "Ezra Koenig", "text_new": "{{short description|American rock musician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Ezra Koenig\n| image            = Ezra Koenig Close up.png\n| caption          = Ezra Koenig performing in [[San Francisco]] in 2014\n| birth_name       = Ezra Michael Koenig\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1984|4|8|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| home_town        = {{nowrap|[[Glen Ridge, New Jersey|Glen Ridge]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.}}\n| residence        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater       = [[Columbia University]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer-songwriter|record producer|television writer|radio host}}\n| partner          = [[Rashida Jones]] (2015\u2013present)\n| children         = 1\n| television       = ''[[Neo Yokio]]''\n| website          = {{URL|vampireweekend.com}}\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|piano|percussion|saxophone}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Indie pop]]|[[indie rock]]|[[baroque pop]]|[[worldbeat]]}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|[[XL Recordings]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Vampire Weekend]]|[[Chromeo]]|[[Haim]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ezra Michael Koenig''' (born April 8, 1984)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/6900fc31-d624-422c-9aa8-b3e6c8cc25ea|title=Ezra Koenig - New Songs, Playlists & Latest News - BBC Music|website=BBC|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhUJX3IlSyb/|title=Ezra Koenig on Instagram: \"April 8, 1994 \ud83c\udf82\"|website=Instagram|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/d10be23ee669433d9e16abe93d69b5f4|title=Today in Entertainment History|website=AP NEWS|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> is an American musician, singer-songwriter, television producer, record producer, radio personality, and screenwriter. He is best known as the lead vocalist, guitarist, and lyricist of [[indie rock]] band [[Vampire Weekend]]. Additionally, Koenig is the creator of the [[Netflix]] animated comedy series ''[[Neo Yokio]]'' and also hosts the [[Apple Music]] radio talk show ''[[Time Crisis with Ezra Koenig]]. Time Crisis'' is airing its fourth season, as of 2019.\n\nOver his career Koenig has received many accolades for his efforts including 5 [[Grammy Award]] nominations for his work with Vampire Weekend in 2010,\n2013 and 2019 (including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]), with wins in 2013 and 2019 for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album]]. He was also nominated in 2016 for his production work on [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s album ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/vampire-weekend-share-new-songs-harmony-hall-and-2021-listen/|title=Vampire Weekend Reveal New Album Title Father of the Bride, Share New Songs: Listen|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKoenig was born in [[New York City]] and is the son of Bobby Bass, a [[psychotherapist]], and Robin Koenig, a [[set dresser]] on film and TV productions.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/26/garden/emma-koenigs-so-called-redacted-life.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Penelope | last=Green | title=Emma Koenig's So-Called Redacted Life | date=July 25, 2012 | access-date=}}</ref> His parents lived on the [[Upper West Side]] of [[Manhattan]] before moving to [[Glen Ridge, New Jersey]] shortly after their son's birth. He is [[Jewish]], and his family came to the U.S. from Europe (including [[History of the Jews in Romania|Romania]] and [[History of the Jews in Hungary|Hungary]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/7541984/Vampire-Weekend-interview.html|title=Vampire Weekend interview|last=Perry|first=Andrew|date=March 31, 2010|work=The Telegraph|access-date=May 25, 2018|language=|issn=}}</ref><ref name=note>{{cite news|author=Anthony Carew|title=Interview: Ezra Koenig of Vampire Weekend|url=http://altmusic.about.com/od/interviews/a/vampireweekend.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716031553/http://altmusic.about.com/od/interviews/a/vampireweekend.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 July 2011|work=about.com|date=23 November 2009|access-date=2010-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/arts/music/26017/vampire-weekend-dont-call-us-white |title=Vampire Weekend: Don't call us white &#124; The Jewish Chronicle |publisher=Thejc.com |date=2010-01-15 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jan/07/vampire-weekend-contra|title=Vampire Weekend: 'They're attacking a version of us that doesn't exist'|last=Lester|first=Paul|date=January 7, 2010|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref> He grew up in [[Northern New Jersey]] and attended [[Glen Ridge High School]]. Ezra has a younger sister, Emma Koenig (born 1988), who is the author of the blog and book \"FUCK! i'm in my twenties\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/26/garden/emma-koenigs-so-called-redacted-life.html | work=The New York Times | first=Penelope | last=Green | title=Emma Koenig's So-Called Redacted Life | date=2012-07-25}}</ref> and wrote on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC-TV]] comedy, ''[[Manhattan Love Story]]''. Ezra began writing music around the age of ten, and his first song ever was titled \"Bad Birthday Party\".\n\nAfter graduating he taught English through [[Teach for America]] at Junior High School 258 in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. Students recalled Koenig bringing his guitar with him to class, despite trying to hide it and his music career. He was described as a \"laid-back\" teacher who successfully made bonds with his students.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guanlao |first=Nicole |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1589744/students-recall-teasing-their-teacher-vampire-weekends-ezra-koenig.jhtml |title=Vampire Weekend Frontman Ezra Koenig's Students Recall Playing Pranks On The Future Rock Star - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV.com |date=2008-06-23 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> In fall 2007, a deal with [[XL Recordings]] cut short Koenig's teaching career.\n\nDuring his schooling and college years, he was involved in numerous musical projects with [[Wes Miles]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts |first=Michael |url=http://blogs.westword.com/backbeat/2008/06/qa_with_wes_miles_of_ra_ra_rio.php |title=Q&A With Wes Miles of Ra Ra Riot - Denver - Music - Backbeat |publisher=Blogs.westword.com |date=2008-06-11 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> a childhood friend and now current frontman of [[Ra Ra Riot]]. Koenig and Miles' formed an experimental band, The Sophisticuffs, which was described as \"wildly inventive musical work\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madeablog.com/2009/07/reginalds-lament-sophisticuffs.html |title=Look at me, I made a blog: \"Reginald's Lament\" - The Sophisticuffs |publisher=Madeablog.com |date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2013-05-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304233437/http://www.madeablog.com/2009/07/reginalds-lament-sophisticuffs.html |archive-date=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2004, Koenig formed the rap band, L'Homme Run, notable for the comedic track, \"Pizza Party\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5hhXgsHrv7c&feature=channel/ |title=Video Hits Interview Vampire Weekend |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-05-13 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> with Andrew Kalaidjian and fellow Vampire Weekend band member [[Chris Tomson]], played saxophone for the [[indie rock]] band [[Dirty Projectors]] and worked as an intern for [[The Walkmen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/39758-5-10-15-20-ezra-koenig/ |title=5-10-15-20: Ezra Koenig &#124; News |website=Pitchfork |date=2010-08-17 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===''Vampire Weekend''===\n{{Main|Vampire Weekend}}\nIn 2005, Ezra formed the indie rock band [[Vampire Weekend]]. The name of the group was in reference to an unreleased indie film of the same name that Ezra and his friends produced during a vacation. In the film, Ezra portrayed the protagonist, Walcott, a man hell-bent on escaping [[Cape Cod]] as he believed vampires were coming. Many songs from the band's eponymous release made reference to the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vampire Weekend\u2019s Ezra Koenig on His Early Influences, the Continued Oxford Comma Debate, and the Most Important Hometown Shows|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/ezra-koenig-new-york-music-scene.html|website=Vulture|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vampire Weekend FDS 1.jpg|thumb|right|Koenig performing with Vampire Weekend (2014)]]\n \nEzra met his bandmates at [[Columbia University]], prior to 2003. After already having met drummer Chris Tomson, Koenig became acquainted with [[Rostam Batmanglij]]. The two immediately bonded over [[Radiohead]] at a party during freshman year and vowed to start a band one day. Rounding out the group was [[Chris Baio]], Koenig's suite-mate in his sophomore year, and they shared a love of [[Destiny's Child]]. The group immediately got to work, playing their first show in 2006 at a battle of the bands in a campus basement. They placed third out of four. Later that year, some of their demos appeared online, earning raves from sites like [[Stereogum]] and [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} Before they knew it, they were selling out shows and appearing on the cover of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' without even having released an album.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Semi-Charmed Life of Vampire Weekend|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-semi-charmed-life-of-vampire-weekend-20100204|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nTheir [[Vampire Weekend (album)|eponymous debut album]] arrived on January 29, 2008, and by the end of the year they had performed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', played for 40,000 fans at England's Glastonbury festival and sold nearly half a million albums. The album was self-produced while they were working full-time jobs. Since then, the band have released another three albums: ''[[Contra (album)|Contra]]'' (2010), ''[[Modern Vampires of the City]]'' (2013), and ''[[Father of the Bride (album)|Father of the Bride]]'' (2019).\n\nThe band has been nominated for multiple [[Grammy Awards]]. In 2011, ''Contra'' was nominated for Best Alternative Album, however the band lost to [[The Black Keys]]. In 2014, ''Modern Vampires of the City'' won the [[Grammy award]] for Best Alternative Album. Following the win, Koenig exclaimed, \"I'm the pre-eminent Ezra of my time, and when I die, then we can talk about who comes next.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vampire Weekend Win Best Alternative Music Album|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/videos/vampire-weekend-win-best-alternative-music-album|website=GRAMMY.com|date=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Time Crisis''===\n{{Main|Time Crisis with Ezra Koenig}}\nAfter the release of [[Apple Music]], Koenig began hosting his own radio show on the Apple Music radio service, [[Beats 1]].\n\nThe show, ''Time Crisis'', mainly features Koenig and a variety of notable guest stars, including regular co-host, L.A. based painter and former [[Dirty Projectors]] member, [[Jake Longstreth]]. Each episode is two-hours in length, during that time, Koenig and company discuss relevant news topics, respond to obscure listener emails regarding 1970s [[rock music]], explore the current terrain of U.S. politics, as well as frequently analyzing the history of corporate snack foods. Additionally, Koenig compares and contrasts contemporary popular music with music of an era relevant to the discourse of the specific episode.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Vampire Weekend's Ezra Koenig Gets Beats 1 Show|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/60265-vampire-weekends-ezra-koenig-gets-beats-1-show/|website = Pitchfork|accessdate = 2015-11-18}}</ref>\n\nOther guests have appeared, such as [[Jonah Hill]], [[Rashida Jones]], [[Mark Ronson]], [[Florence Welch]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Tim Heidecker]], [[James Corden]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch James Corden Crash Ezra Koenig\u2019s 'Time Crisis'|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-james-corden-crash-ezra-koenigs-time-crisis/|website=Pitchfork}}</ref> [[David Longstreth]] of the [[Dirty Projectors]] and Koenig's sister, Emma Koenig.\n\nThe show debuted on July 12, 2015, and new episodes air fortnightly. As of September 23, 2019, 101 episodes have aired.<ref>{{cite web|title=Time Crisis|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/curator/time-crisis/993269786|publisher=Apple Music: Beats 1}}</ref> The show is in its fourth season.\n\n===''Neo Yokio''===\n{{Main|Neo Yokio}}\nFollowing a hiatus from ''Vampire Weekend'', Koenig wrote and produced an animated comedy-adventure series about a depressive, demon-slaying playboy voiced by [[Jaden Smith]]. The series, titled ''[[Neo Yokio]]'', debuted on [[Netflix]] in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=This New Netflix Show May Finally Get You Hooked On Anime|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2017/09/171005/neo-yokio-ezra-koenig-jaden-smith-netflix-anime|last=Luu|first=Christopher|work=[[Refinery29]]|date=September 29, 2017|accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref> The show was written and produced in 2015, with the final sound mix being completed in January 2016,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ezra Koenig Talks Netflix's 'Neo Yokio' and Its Homage to Anime|url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/9/ezra-koenig-netflix-anime-neo-yokio-dazed-interview|website=HYPEBEAST}}</ref> however, due to issues with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], the show was postponed until finally being picked up by Netflix.<ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to \"Zane Lowe and Ezra Koenig\" posted by Zane Lowe on Apple Music.|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/post/idsa.30e0bfb0-9d66-11e7-9ed6-b8f56cd80eaa}}</ref>\n\n''Yokio'' is presented in the style of a Japanese [[anime]] series. However, in an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, he stated that he believes the show is not a traditional anime, \"First of all, out of respect for true anime, I've always called Neo Yokio \"anime-inspired\" \u2013 it's a hybrid. But I've always been a fan of anime, and I always wanted to do something that was kind of an homage to it. Maybe a loving parody. Initially the people I was working with thought I should be the voice of the main character, but I was, like, 'I just spent seven years being the frontman of something, using my voice all the time. What I need right now is to slip into the background of something.'\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Ezra Koenig on New Animated Series, Next Vampire Weekend LP|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ezra-koenig-on-neo-yokio-new-vampire-weekend-lp-kanye-w506044|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nUpon release, the show's first season received mixed reviews from critics, earning a 54% score on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Neo Yokio: Season 1 - Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/neo_yokio/s01/}}</ref> Writer, Shannon Liao of [[The Verge]] criticised the show's story and voice-acting, citing, \"the initial glamor of the backdrops and talent involved wears off fast. It has awful voice acting, and a pointless, predictable story that\u2019s only surprising because it\u2019s so willing to hit the bottom of the barrel.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Netflix\u2019s Neo Yokio has the makings of a brilliant anime, but fails the execution|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/22/16333006/neo-yokio-anime-jaden-smith-ezra-koenig-review-netflix|website=The Verge}}</ref> Contrastingly, ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the show a more optimistic review, stating, \"if a defensive reading of the line, \u201cYes, my girlfriend broke up with me to take a finance job in San Francisco,\u201d makes you chuckle, \u201cNeo Yokio\u201d may be for you.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hale|first1=Mike|title=Review: An Anime New York in Netflix\u2019s \u2018Neo Yokio\u2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/21/arts/television/netflix-neo-yokio-review-jaden-smith.html|website=The New York Times|date=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn an episode of ''Time Crisis'' in early 2018, Koenig spoke about the future of ''Yokio'', hinting that \"Neo's not dead.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Crisis|first1=Time|title=Time Crisis: Episode 62 - Sublime Goldfish|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/station/sublime-goldfish/ra.1341448334|website=Apple Music|publisher=Beats1|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> However the following month Netflix cancelled the show after one season and a Christmas special.\n\n==Other projects and appearances==\nIn 2009, Koenig provided vocals on the song \"Carby\" on ''[[LP (Discovery album)|LP]]'', the debut album from [[Discovery (band)|Discovery]], a group which features Vampire Weekend keyboardist [[Rostam Batmanglij]] and [[Ra Ra Riot]] vocalist Wes Miles. Additionally that year, he appeared on \"[[Warm Heart of Africa]]\" by [[The Very Best]], \"Pyromiltia\" by [[Theophilus London]], \"I Could Be Wrong\" by [[Chromeo]] and \"Dynamo\" by [[Abd al Malik (rapper)|Abd al Malik]].\n\nIn 2012, he performed \"I Think Ur a Contra\" with [[Angelique Kidjo]] in her PBS special. He appeared and provided vocals in the music video for [[Duck Sauce]]'s \"[[Barbra Streisand (song)|Barbra Streisand]]\". His recording of the song \"Papa Hobo\", by [[Paul Simon]], was included as part of the soundtrack for [[Max Winkler]]'s film ''[[Ceremony (film)|Ceremony]]''.\n\nIn 2013, Koenig was featured in the song \"Jessica\" by [[Major Lazer]]. In 2014, he was featured on \"Ezra's Interlude\" by Chromeo, as well as \"New Dorp, New York\" by [[SBTRKT]]. Additionally that year, he appeared on the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch: Vampire Weekend's Ezra Koenig Made a Cameo on \"Girls\" {{!}} Pitchfork|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/49602-watch-vampire-weekends-ezra-koenig-made-a-cameo-on-girls/|website=pitchfork.com|language=en}}</ref> and performed the voice of Ryland on the animated series ''[[Major Lazer (TV series)|Major Lazer]]''. At the [[86th Academy Awards]], Koenig accompanied [[Karen O]] on backing vocals and acoustic guitar for her performance of the Oscar-nominated song \"[[The Moon Song]]\" from the film ''[[Her (film)|Her]]''.\n\nIn 2014, he made an appearance in [[Haim (band)|Haim]]'s music video for \"[[My Song 5]]\" featuring [[A$AP Ferg]].<ref>http://www.nme.com/news/haim/79251</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Koenig was credited as a writer and producer on the song \"[[Hold Up (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Hold Up]]\" by [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/63381-beyonce-releases-new-album-lemonade-featuring-kendrick-lamar-jack-white-the-weeknd-james-blake/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Releases New Album Lemonade Featuring Kendrick Lamar, Jack White, the Weeknd, James Blake|date=23 April 2016|access-date=23 April 2016|website=[[Pitchfork Media]]}}</ref> Due to these contributions, Koenig was nominated for a [[Grammy]]-award for the album ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]''. In January and April 2016, Koenig vocally supported political candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] by performing at a number of his rallies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/20/bernie-sanders-vampire-weekend-grizzly-bear-endorsements|title=Vampire Weekend frontman on the 'end of the road' for Bernie Sanders|last1=Puglise|first1=Nicole|date=20 June 2016|website=the Guardian|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he made an appearance in [[Charli XCX]]'s music video for \"[[Boys (Charli XCX song)|Boys]]\". In 2018, he was credited as a songwriter and producer on the single \"I Promise You\" by [[James Corden]], from the film [[Peter Rabbit (film)|Peter Rabbit]], which also featured prominently Vampire Weekend songs. His demo of the song was also released.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ezra Koenig \u2014 \"I Promise You\"|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/02/ezra-koenig-i-promise-you/|website=Spin|date=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, he and Vampire Weekend performed at a rally for U.S  Presidential Candidate Bernie Sanders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B7ozCo7lOTp/|title=Ezra Koenig on Instagram: \"this picture (and caption) are from February 2016 when we played our first-ever Bernie rally in Iowa City. we\u2019re doing it again February 1, 2020 in Cedar Rapids. (Also @boniver is playing a rally the night before in Clive)\u2063\"|website=Instagram|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/vampire-weekend-perform-at-bernie-sanders-rally-watch/|title=Vampire Weekend Perform at Bernie Sanders Rally: Watch|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nSince the age of 9, Koenig has been an admirer of music. In a 2014 interview with [[Vulture.com|Vulture]], he stated, \"My dad is a massive music fan, so even just growing up in the house, he was buying new cool music, up through when I was born. So I was very familiar with the [[Ramones]], [[Run DMC]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]\u2014core New York music. My parents would often play the Ramones song, \"We\u2019re a Happy Family\", so I remember when I was 9 or 10, learning the lyrics and trying to understand.\" By the time he got to high school, his taste slightly changed, \"I had some older friends who were really obsessed with hip-hop, [[De La Soul]], [[Tribe Called Quest]]. There\u2019s something about ''[[Midnight Marauders]]''; it feels like a late night in the city album.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vampire Weekend\u2019s Ezra Koenig on His Early Influences, the Continued Oxford Comma Debate, and the Most Important Hometown Shows|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/ezra-koenig-new-york-music-scene.html|website=Vulture|language=en|date=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nKoenig is also a self-professed fan of bands such as [[The Grateful Dead]] and [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]], who he believes largely influenced his musical taste.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn August 2018, Koenig had a son with his girlfriend, actress [[Rashida Jones]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/rashida-jones-welcomes-son-isaiah-ezra-koenig/|title=It's a Boy! Rashida Jones, 42, and Vampire Weekend's Ezra Koenig Welcome Son Isaiah|website=PEOPLE.com|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n* {{IMDb name|3587864}}\n\n{{Vampire Weekend}}\n{{Dirty Projectors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koenig, Ezra}}\n[[Category:American indie rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Glen Ridge, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Vampire Weekend members]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Teach For America alumni]]\n[[Category:Dirty Projectors members]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:Educators from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rock musician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Ezra Koenig\n| image            = Ezra Koenig Close up.png\n| caption          = Ezra Koenig performing in [[San Francisco]] in 2014\n| birth_name       = Ezra Michael Koenig\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1984|4|8|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| home_town        = {{nowrap|[[Glen Ridge, New Jersey|Glen Ridge]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.}}\n| residence        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater       = [[Columbia University]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer-songwriter|record producer|television writer|radio host}}\n| partner          = [[Rashida Jones]] (2015\u2013present)\n| children         = 1\n| television       = ''[[Neo Yokio]]''\n| website          = {{URL|vampireweekend.com}}\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|piano|percussion|saxophone}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Indie pop]]|[[indie rock]]|[[baroque pop]]|[[worldbeat]]}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|[[XL Recordings]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Vampire Weekend]]|[[Chromeo]]|[[Haim]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ezra Michael Koenig''' (born April 8, 1984)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/6900fc31-d624-422c-9aa8-b3e6c8cc25ea|title=Ezra Koenig - New Songs, Playlists & Latest News - BBC Music|website=BBC|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhUJX3IlSyb/|title=Ezra Koenig on Instagram: \"April 8, 1994 \ud83c\udf82\"|website=Instagram|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/d10be23ee669433d9e16abe93d69b5f4|title=Today in Entertainment History|website=AP NEWS|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> is an American musician, singer-songwriter, television producer, record producer, radio personality, and screenwriter. He is best known as the lead vocalist, guitarist, and lyricist of [[indie rock]] band [[Vampire Weekend]]. Additionally, Koenig is the creator of the [[Netflix]] animated comedy series ''[[Neo Yokio]]'' and also hosts the [[Apple Music]] radio talk show ''[[Time Crisis with Ezra Koenig]]. Time Crisis'' is airing its fourth season, as of 2019.\n\nOver his career Koenig has received many accolades for his efforts including 5 [[Grammy Award]] nominations for his work with Vampire Weekend in 2010,\n2013 and 2019 (including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]), with wins in 2013 and 2019 for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album]]. He was also nominated in 2016 for his production work on [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s album ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/vampire-weekend-share-new-songs-harmony-hall-and-2021-listen/|title=Vampire Weekend Reveal New Album Title Father of the Bride, Share New Songs: Listen|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKoenig was born in [[New York City]] and is the son of Bobby Bass, a [[psychotherapist]], and Robin Koenig, a [[set dresser]] on film and TV productions.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/26/garden/emma-koenigs-so-called-redacted-life.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Penelope | last=Green | title=Emma Koenig's So-Called Redacted Life | date=July 25, 2012 | access-date=}}</ref> His parents lived on the [[Upper West Side]] of [[Manhattan]] before moving to [[Glen Ridge, New Jersey]] shortly after their son's birth. He is [[Jewish]], and his family came to the U.S. from Europe (including [[History of the Jews in Romania|Romania]] and [[History of the Jews in Hungary|Hungary]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/7541984/Vampire-Weekend-interview.html|title=Vampire Weekend interview|last=Perry|first=Andrew|date=March 31, 2010|work=The Telegraph|access-date=May 25, 2018|language=|issn=}}</ref><ref name=note>{{cite news|author=Anthony Carew|title=Interview: Ezra Koenig of Vampire Weekend|url=http://altmusic.about.com/od/interviews/a/vampireweekend.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716031553/http://altmusic.about.com/od/interviews/a/vampireweekend.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 July 2011|work=about.com|date=23 November 2009|access-date=2010-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/arts/music/26017/vampire-weekend-dont-call-us-white |title=Vampire Weekend: Don't call us white &#124; The Jewish Chronicle |publisher=Thejc.com |date=2010-01-15 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jan/07/vampire-weekend-contra|title=Vampire Weekend: 'They're attacking a version of us that doesn't exist'|last=Lester|first=Paul|date=January 7, 2010|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref> He grew up in [[Northern New Jersey]] and attended [[Glen Ridge High School]]. Ezra has a younger sister, Emma Koenig (born 1988), who is the author of the blog and book \"FUCK! i'm in my twenties\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/26/garden/emma-koenigs-so-called-redacted-life.html | work=The New York Times | first=Penelope | last=Green | title=Emma Koenig's So-Called Redacted Life | date=2012-07-25}}</ref> and wrote on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC-TV]] comedy, ''[[Manhattan Love Story]]''. Ezra began writing music around the age of ten, and his first song ever was titled \"Bad Birthday Party\".\n\nAfter graduating he taught English through [[Teach for America]] at Junior High School 258 in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. Students recalled Koenig bringing his guitar with him to class, despite trying to hide it and his music career. He was described as a \"laid-back\" teacher who successfully made bonds with his students.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guanlao |first=Nicole |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1589744/students-recall-teasing-their-teacher-vampire-weekends-ezra-koenig.jhtml |title=Vampire Weekend Frontman Ezra Koenig's Students Recall Playing Pranks On The Future Rock Star - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV.com |date=2008-06-23 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> In fall 2007, a deal with [[XL Recordings]] cut short Koenig's teaching career.\n\nDuring his schooling and college years, he was involved in numerous musical projects with [[Wes Miles]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts |first=Michael |url=http://blogs.westword.com/backbeat/2008/06/qa_with_wes_miles_of_ra_ra_rio.php |title=Q&A With Wes Miles of Ra Ra Riot - Denver - Music - Backbeat |publisher=Blogs.westword.com |date=2008-06-11 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> a childhood friend and now current frontman of [[Ra Ra Riot]]. Koenig and Miles' formed an experimental band, The Sophisticuffs, which was described as \"wildly inventive musical work\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madeablog.com/2009/07/reginalds-lament-sophisticuffs.html |title=Look at me, I made a blog: \"Reginald's Lament\" - The Sophisticuffs |publisher=Madeablog.com |date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2013-05-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304233437/http://www.madeablog.com/2009/07/reginalds-lament-sophisticuffs.html |archive-date=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2004, Koenig formed the rap band, L'Homme Run, notable for the comedic track, \"Pizza Party\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5hhXgsHrv7c&feature=channel/ |title=Video Hits Interview Vampire Weekend |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-05-13 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> with Andrew Kalaidjian and fellow Vampire Weekend band member [[Chris Tomson]], played saxophone for the [[indie rock]] band [[Dirty Projectors]] and worked as an intern for [[The Walkmen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/39758-5-10-15-20-ezra-koenig/ |title=5-10-15-20: Ezra Koenig &#124; News |website=Pitchfork |date=2010-08-17 |accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===''Vampire Weekend''===\n{{Main|Vampire Weekend}}\nIn 2005, Ezra formed the indie rock band [[Vampire Weekend]]. The name of the group was in reference to an unreleased indie film of the same name that Ezra and his friends produced during a vacation. In the film, Ezra portrayed the protagonist, Walcott, a man hell-bent on escaping [[Cape Cod]] as he believed vampires were coming. Many songs from the band's eponymous release made reference to the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vampire Weekend\u2019s Ezra Koenig on His Early Influences, the Continued Oxford Comma Debate, and the Most Important Hometown Shows|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/ezra-koenig-new-york-music-scene.html|website=Vulture|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vampire Weekend FDS 1.jpg|thumb|right|Koenig performing with Vampire Weekend (2014)]]\n \nEzra met his bandmates at [[Columbia University]], prior to 2003. After already having met drummer Chris Tomson, Koenig became acquainted with [[Rostam Batmanglij]]. The two immediately bonded over [[Radiohead]] at a party during freshman year and vowed to start a band one day. Rounding out the group was [[Chris Baio]], Koenig's suite-mate in his sophomore year, and they shared a love of [[Destiny's Child]]. The group immediately got to work, playing their first show in 2006 at a battle of the bands in a campus basement. They placed third out of four. Later that year, some of their demos appeared online, earning raves from sites like [[Stereogum]] and [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} Before they knew it, they were selling out shows and appearing on the cover of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' without even having released an album.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Semi-Charmed Life of Vampire Weekend|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-semi-charmed-life-of-vampire-weekend-20100204|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nTheir [[Vampire Weekend (album)|eponymous debut album]] arrived on January 29, 2008, and by the end of the year they had performed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', played for 40,000 fans at England's Glastonbury festival and sold nearly half a million albums. The album was self-produced while they were working full-time jobs. Since then, the band have released another three albums: ''[[Contra (album)|Contra]]'' (2010), ''[[Modern Vampires of the City]]'' (2013), and ''[[Father of the Bride (album)|Father of the Bride]]'' (2019).\n\nThe band has been nominated for multiple [[Grammy Awards]]. In 2011, ''Contra'' was nominated for Best Alternative Album, however the band lost to [[The Black Keys]]. In 2014, ''Modern Vampires of the City'' won the [[Grammy award]] for Best Alternative Album. Following the win, Koenig exclaimed, \"I'm the pre-eminent Ezra of my time, and when I die, then we can talk about who comes next.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vampire Weekend Win Best Alternative Music Album|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/videos/vampire-weekend-win-best-alternative-music-album|website=GRAMMY.com|date=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Time Crisis''===\n{{Main|Time Crisis with Ezra Koenig}}\nAfter the release of [[Apple Music]], Koenig began hosting his own radio show on the Apple Music radio service, [[Beats 1]].\n\nThe show, ''Time Crisis'', mainly features Koenig and a variety of notable guest stars, including regular co-host, L.A. based painter and former [[Dirty Projectors]] member, [[Jake Longstreth]]. Each episode is two-hours in length, during that time, Koenig and company discuss relevant news topics, respond to obscure listener emails regarding 1970s [[rock music]], explore the current terrain of U.S. politics, as well as frequently analyzing the history of corporate snack foods. Additionally, Koenig compares and contrasts contemporary popular music with music of an era relevant to the discourse of the specific episode.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Vampire Weekend's Ezra Koenig Gets Beats 1 Show|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/60265-vampire-weekends-ezra-koenig-gets-beats-1-show/|website = Pitchfork|accessdate = 2015-11-18}}</ref>\n\nOther guests have appeared, such as [[Jonah Hill]], [[Rashida Jones]], [[Mark Ronson]], [[Florence Welch]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Tim Heidecker]], [[James Corden]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch James Corden Crash Ezra Koenig\u2019s 'Time Crisis'|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-james-corden-crash-ezra-koenigs-time-crisis/|website=Pitchfork}}</ref> [[David Longstreth]] of the [[Dirty Projectors]] and Koenig's sister, Emma Koenig.\n\nThe show debuted on July 12, 2015, and new episodes air fortnightly. As of September 23, 2019, 101 episodes have aired.<ref>{{cite web|title=Time Crisis|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/curator/time-crisis/993269786|publisher=Apple Music: Beats 1}}</ref> The show is in its fourth season.\n\n===''Neo Yokio''===\n{{Main|Neo Yokio}}\nFollowing a hiatus from ''Vampire Weekend'', Koenig wrote and produced an animated comedy-adventure series about a depressive, demon-slaying playboy voiced by [[Jaden Smith]]. The series, titled ''[[Neo Yokio]]'', debuted on [[Netflix]] in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=This New Netflix Show May Finally Get You Hooked On Anime|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2017/09/171005/neo-yokio-ezra-koenig-jaden-smith-netflix-anime|last=Luu|first=Christopher|work=[[Refinery29]]|date=September 29, 2017|accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref> The show was written and produced in 2015, with the final sound mix being completed in January 2016,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ezra Koenig Talks Netflix's 'Neo Yokio' and Its Homage to Anime|url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/9/ezra-koenig-netflix-anime-neo-yokio-dazed-interview|website=HYPEBEAST}}</ref> however, due to issues with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], the show was postponed until finally being picked up by Netflix.<ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to \"Zane Lowe and Ezra Koenig\" posted by Zane Lowe on Apple Music.|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/post/idsa.30e0bfb0-9d66-11e7-9ed6-b8f56cd80eaa}}</ref>\n\n''Yokio'' is presented in the style of a Japanese [[anime]] series. However, in an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, he stated that he believes the show is not a traditional anime, \"First of all, out of respect for true anime, I've always called Neo Yokio \"anime-inspired\" \u2013 it's a hybrid. But I've always been a fan of anime, and I always wanted to do something that was kind of an homage to it. Maybe a loving parody. Initially the people I was working with thought I should be the voice of the main character, but I was, like, 'I just spent seven years being the frontman of something, using my voice all the time. What I need right now is to slip into the background of something.'\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Ezra Koenig on New Animated Series, Next Vampire Weekend LP|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ezra-koenig-on-neo-yokio-new-vampire-weekend-lp-kanye-w506044|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nUpon release, the show's first season received mixed reviews from critics, earning a 54% score on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Neo Yokio: Season 1 - Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/neo_yokio/s01/}}</ref> Writer, Shannon Liao of [[The Verge]] criticised the show's story and voice-acting, citing, \"the initial glamor of the backdrops and talent involved wears off fast. It has awful voice acting, and a pointless, predictable story that\u2019s only surprising because it\u2019s so willing to hit the bottom of the barrel.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Netflix\u2019s Neo Yokio has the makings of a brilliant anime, but fails the execution|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/22/16333006/neo-yokio-anime-jaden-smith-ezra-koenig-review-netflix|website=The Verge}}</ref> Contrastingly, ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the show a more optimistic review, stating, \"if a defensive reading of the line, \u201cYes, my girlfriend broke up with me to take a finance job in San Francisco,\u201d makes you chuckle, \u201cNeo Yokio\u201d may be for you.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hale|first1=Mike|title=Review: An Anime New York in Netflix\u2019s \u2018Neo Yokio\u2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/21/arts/television/netflix-neo-yokio-review-jaden-smith.html|website=The New York Times|date=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn an episode of ''Time Crisis'' in early 2018, Koenig spoke about the future of ''Yokio'', hinting that \"Neo's not dead.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Crisis|first1=Time|title=Time Crisis: Episode 62 - Sublime Goldfish|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/station/sublime-goldfish/ra.1341448334|website=Apple Music|publisher=Beats1|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> However the following month Netflix cancelled the show after one season and a Christmas special.\n\n==Other projects and appearances==\nIn 2009, Koenig provided vocals on the song \"Carby\" on ''[[LP (Discovery album)|LP]]'', the debut album from [[Discovery (band)|Discovery]], a group which features Vampire Weekend keyboardist [[Rostam Batmanglij]] and [[Ra Ra Riot]] vocalist Wes Miles. Additionally that year, he appeared on \"[[Warm Heart of Africa]]\" by [[The Very Best]], \"Pyromiltia\" by [[Theophilus London]], \"I Could Be Wrong\" by [[Chromeo]] and \"Dynamo\" by [[Abd al Malik (rapper)|Abd al Malik]].\n\nIn 2012, he performed \"I Think Ur a Contra\" with [[Angelique Kidjo]] in her PBS special. He appeared and provided vocals in the music video for [[Duck Sauce]]'s \"[[Barbra Streisand (song)|Barbra Streisand]]\". His recording of the song \"Papa Hobo\", by [[Paul Simon]], was included as part of the soundtrack for [[Max Winkler]]'s film ''[[Ceremony (film)|Ceremony]]''.\n\nIn 2013, Koenig was featured in the song \"Jessica\" by [[Major Lazer]]. In 2014, he was featured on \"Ezra's Interlude\" by Chromeo, as well as \"New Dorp, New York\" by [[SBTRKT]]. Additionally that year, he appeared on the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch: Vampire Weekend's Ezra Koenig Made a Cameo on \"Girls\" {{!}} Pitchfork|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/49602-watch-vampire-weekends-ezra-koenig-made-a-cameo-on-girls/|website=pitchfork.com|language=en}}</ref> and performed the voice of Ryland on the animated series ''[[Major Lazer (TV series)|Major Lazer]]''. At the [[86th Academy Awards]], Koenig accompanied [[Karen O]] on backing vocals and acoustic guitar for her performance of the Oscar-nominated song \"[[The Moon Song]]\" from the film ''[[Her (film)|Her]]''.\n\nIn 2014, he made an appearance in [[Haim (band)|Haim]]'s music video for \"[[My Song 5]]\" featuring [[A$AP Ferg]].<ref>http://www.nme.com/news/haim/79251</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Koenig was credited as a writer and producer on the song \"[[Hold Up (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Hold Up]]\" by [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/63381-beyonce-releases-new-album-lemonade-featuring-kendrick-lamar-jack-white-the-weeknd-james-blake/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Releases New Album Lemonade Featuring Kendrick Lamar, Jack White, the Weeknd, James Blake|date=23 April 2016|access-date=23 April 2016|website=[[Pitchfork Media]]}}</ref> Due to these contributions, Koenig was nominated for a [[Grammy]]-award for the album ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]''. In January and April 2016, Koenig vocally supported political candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] by performing at a number of his rallies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/20/bernie-sanders-vampire-weekend-grizzly-bear-endorsements|title=Vampire Weekend frontman on the 'end of the road' for Bernie Sanders|last1=Puglise|first1=Nicole|date=20 June 2016|website=the Guardian|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he made an appearance in [[Charli XCX]]'s music video for \"[[Boys (Charli XCX song)|Boys]]\". In 2018, he was credited as a songwriter and producer on the single \"I Promise You\" by [[James Corden]], from the film [[Peter Rabbit (film)|Peter Rabbit]], which also featured prominently Vampire Weekend songs. His demo of the song was also released.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ezra Koenig \u2014 \"I Promise You\"|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/02/ezra-koenig-i-promise-you/|website=Spin|date=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February of 2020, he and Vampire Weekend performed at a rally for U.S  Presidential Candidate Bernie Sanders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B7ozCo7lOTp/|title=Ezra Koenig on Instagram: \"this picture (and caption) are from February 2016 when we played our first-ever Bernie rally in Iowa City. we\u2019re doing it again February 1, 2020 in Cedar Rapids. (Also @boniver is playing a rally the night before in Clive)\u2063\"|website=Instagram|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/vampire-weekend-perform-at-bernie-sanders-rally-watch/|title=Vampire Weekend Perform at Bernie Sanders Rally: Watch|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nSince the age of 9, Koenig has been an admirer of music. In a 2014 interview with [[Vulture.com|Vulture]], he stated, \"My dad is a massive music fan, so even just growing up in the house, he was buying new cool music, up through when I was born. So I was very familiar with the [[Ramones]], [[Run DMC]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]\u2014core New York music. My parents would often play the Ramones song, \"We\u2019re a Happy Family\", so I remember when I was 9 or 10, learning the lyrics and trying to understand.\" By the time he got to high school, his taste slightly changed, \"I had some older friends who were really obsessed with hip-hop, [[De La Soul]], [[Tribe Called Quest]]. There\u2019s something about ''[[Midnight Marauders]]''; it feels like a late night in the city album.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vampire Weekend\u2019s Ezra Koenig on His Early Influences, the Continued Oxford Comma Debate, and the Most Important Hometown Shows|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/ezra-koenig-new-york-music-scene.html|website=Vulture|language=en|date=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nKoenig is also a self-professed fan of bands such as [[The Grateful Dead]] and [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]], who he believes largely influenced his musical taste.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn August 2018, Koenig had a son with his girlfriend, actress [[Rashida Jones]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/rashida-jones-welcomes-son-isaiah-ezra-koenig/|title=It's a Boy! Rashida Jones, 42, and Vampire Weekend's Ezra Koenig Welcome Son Isaiah|website=PEOPLE.com|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n* {{IMDb name|3587864}}\n\n{{Vampire Weekend}}\n{{Dirty Projectors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koenig, Ezra}}\n[[Category:American indie rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Glen Ridge, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Vampire Weekend members]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Teach For America alumni]]\n[[Category:Dirty Projectors members]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:Educators from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther projects and appearances:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: February of 2020 \u2192 February 2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ezra_Koenig"}
